ion=[[Hanoi]]\n|attendance=4,839\n|referee=[[Yu Ming-hsun]] ([[Chinese Taipei Football Association|Chinese Taipei]])\n|aggregatescore=3\u20132\n|result=L|}}\n''H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i won 3\u20132 on aggregate.''\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n<references /><references group=\"note\"/>\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website|http://ceresfootball.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019 Ceres-Negros F.C. season}}\n[[Category:Ceres\u2013Negros F.C. seasons]]\n[[Category:Philippines Football League clubs seasons|Ceres-Negros 2019]]\n[[Category:Philippine football club seasons|Ceres-Negros 2019]]\n", "name_user": "Jollibinay", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeason overview", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Ceres%E2%80%93Negros_F.C._season"}
{"title_page": "Agape International Missions", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name          = Agape International Missions\n| former name   = \n| bgcolor       = <!-- header background color -->\n| fgcolor       = <!-- header text color -->\n| image         = Nefarious - Interview.jpg\n| image_border  = \n| size          = <!-- default 200px -->\n| alt           = A black-and-white photograph of three men sitting on chairs facing each other and wearing shorts and t-shirts all next to another empty chair\n| caption       = CEO Don Brewster (left) being interviewed by filmmaker [[Benjamin Nolot]] (right) for the documentary ''[[Nefarious: Merchant of Souls]]''\n| map           = <!-- optional -->\n| msize         = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| malt          = <!-- map alt text -->\n| mcaption      = <!-- optional -->\n| map2          = \n| abbreviation  = AIM\n| motto         = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| formation     = 1989 (USA), 2006 (Cambodia)\n| extinction    = <!-- date of extinction, optional -->\n| type          = [[nonprofit organization|NPO]], [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]\n| status        = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n| purpose       = Rescue, restore and reintegrate victims of [[sex trafficking in Cambodia]]\n| headquarters  = [[Roseville, California|Roseville]], [[California]]\n| location      = [[Svay Pak]], [[Russei Keo District]], [[Phnom Penh]], [[Cambodia]]\n| coords        = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template -->\n| region_served = [[Southeast Asia]]\n| membership    = \n| language      = <!-- official languages -->\n| general       = <!-- Secretary General -->\n| leader_title  = CEO\n| leader_name   = Don and Bridget Brewster\n| leader_title2 = Board Chair\n| leader_name2  = Ken Petersen\n| leader_title3 = \n| leader_name3  = \n| leader_title4 = \n| leader_name4  = \n| key_people    = \n| main_organ    = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n| parent_organization = <!-- if one -->\n| affiliations  = 3Strands\n| budget        = \n| num_staff     = \n| num_volunteers = \n| website       = {{url|http://agapewebsite.org/}}\n| remarks       = \n}}\n'''Agape International Missions''' ('''AIM''') is a [[nonprofit organization|nonnonprofit]], [[non-denominational]], [[non-governmental organization]] working to rescue, restore, and reintegrate girls who are victims child [[sex trafficking in Cambodia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/family-education/article/1543646/don-and-bridget-brewster-agape-international-missions|title=Don and Bridget Brewster of Agape International Missions on combating Cambodia's child sex traffickers|date=July 1, 2014|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/93966/trafficking-fight-honoured/|title=Trafficking fight honoured|date=December 5, 2017|website=Khmer Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2017/june/cambodias-child-sex-industry-trafficking-christians.html?share=4FLM5MMq+XISeTkCLcImaKIOaUDYprgm|title=Cambodia\u2019s Child Sex Industry Is Dwindling\u2014And They Have Christians to Thank|date=\nMay 19, 2017|website=CT}}</ref> It has staff in [[California]] and [[Southeast Asia]] and carries out housing, education, health, employment, rehabilitation, and community care initiatives in [[Cambodia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2017/june/worlds-biggest-trafficking-problem-labor-cambodia.html?share=4FLM5MMq+XLqwsMyjxv5v4OB0Z2cuD7f&start=1|title=The World\u2019s Biggest Trafficking Problem Remains in the Background|date=May 19, 2017|website=CT}}</ref> The AIM Shop is a retail store that sells jewelry and other products made by survivors and supports the organization's initiatives. AIM received [[Guidestar|GuideStar USA, Inc.'s]] gold seal of transparency in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/94-3100052|title=AIM|date=2019|website=GuideStar}}</ref> [[Charity Navigator]] gave AIM the highest rating of 4 out of 4 stars and a score of 100 out of 100 for accountability & transparency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=16103|title=Agape International Missions|website=Charity Navigator}}</ref> \n\nAIM has a [[SWAT]] team, authorized by the Cambodian government, that conducts investigations, raids brothels and indirect sex establishments (i.e. beer gardens, massage parlours, salons, karaoke bars, retail spaces, and non-commercial sites), rescues sex trafficked victims, and arrests perpetrators alongside Cambodian law enforcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3006909/non-profit-group-which-helps-sex-trafficking-victims-seeks|title=Non-profit group, which helps sex-trafficking victims, seeks tie-ups with ethical business partners in Hong Kong|date=April 21, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/reporters-notebook-brothel-raids-missionaries-rescuing-girls-cambodia/story?id=46100713|title=Reporter's notebook: Covering brothel raids and Christian missionaries rescuing girls in Cambodia|date=March 13, 2017|website=ABC News}}</ref> AIM also rescues girls and women [[sex trafficking in China|sex trafficked to China.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3006909/non-profit-group-which-helps-sex-trafficking-victims-seeks|title=Non-profit group, which helps sex-trafficking victims, seeks tie-ups with ethical business partners in Hong Kong|date=April 21, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\nRescued victims are provided with support, education, employment opportunities, and more so they are well taken care of, heal from physical and psychological trauma, and do not end up in [[child prostitution]] again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/inside-world-cambodias-child-sex-trade-told-eyes/story?id=45990734|title=Inside the world of Cambodia's child sex trade, as told through the eyes of a survivor|date=March 8, 2017|website=ABC News}}</ref> \n \nAIM was founded by Bridget and Don Brewster, a former [[pastor]] of Adventure Christian Church,<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|title=Girls turn camera on world: Teacher aids victims of child sex trade|author=Jennifer K. Morita|date=August 7, 2008|page=G7}}</ref> in California in 1989 and began operations in Cambodia in 2006. The organization opened its first shelter and restoration center for former child [[sexual slavery|sex slaves]] in the village of [[Svay Pak]], Cambodia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/family-education/article/1543646/don-and-bridget-brewster-agape-international-missions|title=Don and Bridget Brewster of Agape International Missions on combating Cambodia's child sex traffickers|date=July 1, 2014|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n<ref name=Magagnini>{{cite news|last1=Magagnini|first1=Stephen|title=A PLACE OF SAFETY Granite Bay missionaries bring message of hope for a better life to victims of child sex trade in Cambodia (profile)|publisher=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|date=16 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Locke|first1=Cathy|title=Granite Bay event to focus on efforts to combat sex trafficking|publisher=[[McClatchy - Tribune Business News]]|date=21 August 2011}}</ref> \n<ref name=Bramhan>{{cite news|last1=Bramhan|first1=Daphne|title=Svay Pak's glimmers of hope; Vancouver-based Ratanak International and others work to rebuild a community|publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]]|date=26 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sara Sidner\">{{Cite journal|journal=[[CNN]]|author=Sara Sidner|title=Cambodian village has disturbing reputation for child sex slavery|date=October 24, 2011|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/10/23/world/asia/cambodia-child-sex-slaves/|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations that combat human trafficking]]\n[[Category:Charities based in California]]\n[[Category:Foreign charities operating in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Educational charities based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Women's rights organizations]]\n[[Category:Children's rights organizations]]\n[[Category:Christian educational organizations]]\n[[Category:Victims' rights organizations]]\n[[Category:Christian missions]]\n[[Category:Phnom Penh]]\n[[Category:Human trafficking in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Sex worker organizations in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Child-related organisations in Cambodia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name          = Agape International Missions\n| former name   = \n| bgcolor       = <!-- header background color -->\n| fgcolor       = <!-- header text color -->\n| image         = Nefarious - Interview.jpg\n| image_border  = \n| size          = <!-- default 200px -->\n| alt           = A black-and-white photograph of three men sitting on chairs facing each other and wearing shorts and t-shirts all next to another empty chair\n| caption       = CEO Don Brewster (left) being interviewed by filmmaker [[Benjamin Nolot]] (right) for the documentary ''[[Nefarious: Merchant of Souls]]''\n| map           = <!-- optional -->\n| msize         = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| malt          = <!-- map alt text -->\n| mcaption      = <!-- optional -->\n| map2          = \n| abbreviation  = AIM\n| motto         = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| formation     = 1989 (USA), 2006 (Cambodia)\n| extinction    = <!-- date of extinction, optional -->\n| type          = [[nonprofit organization|NPO]], [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]\n| status        = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n| purpose       = Rescue, restore and reintegrate victims of [[sex trafficking in Cambodia]]\n| headquarters  = [[Roseville]], [[California]]\n| location      = [[Svay Pak]], [[Russei Keo District]], [[Phnom Penh]], [[Cambodia]]\n| coords        = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template -->\n| region_served = [[Southeast Asia]]\n| membership    = \n| language      = <!-- official languages -->\n| general       = <!-- Secretary General -->\n| leader_title  = CEO\n| leader_name   = Don and Bridget Brewster\n| leader_title2 = Board Chair\n| leader_name2  = Ken Petersen\n| leader_title3 = \n| leader_name3  = \n| leader_title4 = \n| leader_name4  = \n| key_people    = \n| main_organ    = <!-- gral. assembly, board of directors, etc -->\n| parent_organization = <!-- if one -->\n| affiliations  = 3Strands\n| budget        = \n| num_staff     = \n| num_volunteers = \n| website       = {{url|http://agapewebsite.org/}}\n| remarks       = \n}}\n'''Agape International Missions''' ('''AIM''') is a [[nonprofit organization|nonnonprofit]], [[non-denominational]], [[non-governmental organization]] working to rescue, restore, and reintegrate girls who are victims child [[sex trafficking in Cambodia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/family-education/article/1543646/don-and-bridget-brewster-agape-international-missions|title=Don and Bridget Brewster of Agape International Missions on combating Cambodia's child sex traffickers|date=July 1, 2014|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/93966/trafficking-fight-honoured/|title=Trafficking fight honoured|date=December 5, 2017|website=Khmer Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2017/june/cambodias-child-sex-industry-trafficking-christians.html?share=4FLM5MMq+XISeTkCLcImaKIOaUDYprgm|title=Cambodia\u2019s Child Sex Industry Is Dwindling\u2014And They Have Christians to Thank|date=\nMay 19, 2017|website=CT}}</ref> It has staff in [[California]] and [[Southeast Asia]] and carries out housing, education, health, employment, rehabilitation, and community care initiatives in [[Cambodia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2017/june/worlds-biggest-trafficking-problem-labor-cambodia.html?share=4FLM5MMq+XLqwsMyjxv5v4OB0Z2cuD7f&start=1|title=The World\u2019s Biggest Trafficking Problem Remains in the Background|date=May 19, 2017|website=CT}}</ref> The AIM Shop is a retail store that sells jewelry and other products made by survivors and supports the organization's initiatives. AIM received [[Guidestar|GuideStar USA, Inc.'s]] gold seal of transparency in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/94-3100052|title=AIM|date=2019|website=GuideStar}}</ref> [[Charity Navigator]] gave AIM the highest rating of 4 out of 4 stars and a score of 100 out of 100 for accountability & transparency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=16103|title=Agape International Missions|website=Charity Navigator}}</ref> \n\nAIM has a [[SWAT]] team, authorized by the Cambodian government, that conducts investigations, raids brothels and indirect sex establishments (i.e. beer gardens, massage parlours, salons, karaoke bars, retail spaces, and non-commercial sites), rescues sex trafficked victims, and arrests perpetrators alongside Cambodian law enforcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3006909/non-profit-group-which-helps-sex-trafficking-victims-seeks|title=Non-profit group, which helps sex-trafficking victims, seeks tie-ups with ethical business partners in Hong Kong|date=April 21, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/reporters-notebook-brothel-raids-missionaries-rescuing-girls-cambodia/story?id=46100713|title=Reporter's notebook: Covering brothel raids and Christian missionaries rescuing girls in Cambodia|date=March 13, 2017|website=ABC News}}</ref> AIM also rescues girls and women [[sex trafficking in China|sex trafficked to China.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3006909/non-profit-group-which-helps-sex-trafficking-victims-seeks|title=Non-profit group, which helps sex-trafficking victims, seeks tie-ups with ethical business partners in Hong Kong|date=April 21, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\nRescued victims are provided with support, education, employment opportunities, and more so they are well taken care of, heal from physical and psychological trauma, and do not end up in [[child prostitution]] again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/inside-world-cambodias-child-sex-trade-told-eyes/story?id=45990734|title=Inside the world of Cambodia's child sex trade, as told through the eyes of a survivor|date=March 8, 2017|website=ABC News}}</ref> \n \nAIM was founded by Bridget and Don Brewster, a former [[pastor]] of Adventure Christian Church,<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|title=Girls turn camera on world: Teacher aids victims of child sex trade|author=Jennifer K. Morita|date=August 7, 2008|page=G7}}</ref> in California in 1989 and began operations in Cambodia in 2006. The organization opened its first shelter and restoration center for former child [[sexual slavery|sex slaves]] in the village of [[Svay Pak]], Cambodia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/family-education/article/1543646/don-and-bridget-brewster-agape-international-missions|title=Don and Bridget Brewster of Agape International Missions on combating Cambodia's child sex traffickers|date=July 1, 2014|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n<ref name=Magagnini>{{cite news|last1=Magagnini|first1=Stephen|title=A PLACE OF SAFETY Granite Bay missionaries bring message of hope for a better life to victims of child sex trade in Cambodia (profile)|publisher=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|date=16 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Locke|first1=Cathy|title=Granite Bay event to focus on efforts to combat sex trafficking|publisher=[[McClatchy - Tribune Business News]]|date=21 August 2011}}</ref> \n<ref name=Bramhan>{{cite news|last1=Bramhan|first1=Daphne|title=Svay Pak's glimmers of hope; Vancouver-based Ratanak International and others work to rebuild a community|publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]]|date=26 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sara Sidner\">{{Cite journal|journal=[[CNN]]|author=Sara Sidner|title=Cambodian village has disturbing reputation for child sex slavery|date=October 24, 2011|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/10/23/world/asia/cambodia-child-sex-slaves/|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Organizations that combat human trafficking]]\n[[Category:Charities based in California]]\n[[Category:Foreign charities operating in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Educational charities based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Women's rights organizations]]\n[[Category:Children's rights organizations]]\n[[Category:Christian educational organizations]]\n[[Category:Victims' rights organizations]]\n[[Category:Christian missions]]\n[[Category:Phnom Penh]]\n[[Category:Human trafficking in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Sex worker organizations in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Child-related organisations in Cambodia]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Roseville\u2192Roseville, California", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agape_International_Missions"}
{"title_page": "Zakho", "text_new": "{{about|a city in northern Iraq}}{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name            = Zakho\n| native_name              = {{lang|ku|\u0632\u0627\u062e\u06c6 ,Zaxo}}<br>{{lang|syr|\u0719\u0735\u071f\u0742\u0718\u073f}}\n| other_name               =\n|image_skyline          = Pira.delal.zaxo.jpg\n|imagesize              =\n|image_caption          = The Little Khabur flowing through Zakho\n|image_flag =\n|image_seal =\n|image_map =\n|map_caption =\n|pushpin_map = Iraqi Kurdistan#Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position =bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location in Iraq\n|coordinates            = {{coord|37|08|37.00|N|42|40|54.88|E|region:IQ|display=inline}}\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      =Region\n|subdivision_type2      = Governorate\n|subdivision_type3      = District\n|subdivision_name1      ={{flag|Kurdistan Region}}\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Dohuk Governorate]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Zakho District]]\n|established_title =\n|established_date =\n|government_type =\n|leader_title =\n|leader_name =\n|area_magnitude =\n|area_total_km2 =\n|area_total_sq_mi =\n|area_land_km2 =\n|area_land_sq_mi =\n|area_urban_km2 =\n|area_urban_sq_mi =\n|area_metro_km2 =\n|area_metro_sq_mi =\n|elevation_footnotes=\n|elevation_m = 440\n|elevation_ft =\n|population_total = 212,000+\n|population_as_of= 2018\n|population_density_km2 =\n|population_density_sq_mi =\n|population_urban =\n|population_metro =\n|postal_code_type =\n|postal_code =\n|area_code =\n|website =\n|footnotes =\n|timezone = UTC+3\n|utc_offset =\n|timezone_DST = not observed\n|utc_offset_DST =\n}}\n\n'''Zakho''' ({{lang-ku|\u0632\u0627\u062e\u06c6 ,Zaxo}},<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0632\u0627\u062e\u06c6 |url=http://bot.gov.krd/kurdish/duhok-province/zakho |accessdate=18 December 2019 |language=ku}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=Celil\u00ea Celil, Dzhalile Dzhalil |title=Jiyana rew\u015fenb\u00eer\u00ee \u00fb s\u00eeyas\u00ee ya Kurdan: di daw\u00eeya sedsala 19'a \u00fb destp\u00eaka sedsala 20'a da |date=1985 |page=154 |language=ku}}</ref> {{lang-ar|\u0632\u0627\u062e\u0648}};<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0632\u0627\u062e\u0648 {{!}} \u0643\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0647\u0634\u0629 - \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0633\u0645\u064a \u0644\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0627\u062d\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 |url=http://bot.gov.krd/arabic/duhok-province/zakho |website=bot.gov.krd |accessdate=19 December 2019 |language=ar}}</ref> {{lang-syr|\u0719\u0735\u071f\u0323\u0718\u0307|Z\u0101kh\u014d}},<ref>{{cite web |title=List of all entries |url=http://www.assyrianlanguages.org/sureth/list.php?initial=z |website=Assyrian Languages |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> {{lang-he-n|\u05d6\u05d0\u05db\u05d5}};<ref>{{cite web |title=\u05e7\u05d4\u05d9\u05dc\u05d5\u05ea - \u05d6\u05d0\u05db\u05d5 |url=http://www.kurdishjewry.org.il/kehil/Zako.htm |website=www.kurdishjewry.org.il |accessdate=19 December 2019 |language=he}}</ref> {{Lang-hy|\u0536\u0561\u056d\u0578}}<ref>{{cite news |title=\u053b\u0550\u0531\u0554\u0545\u0531\u0546 \u0554\u0548\u0552\u0550\u0534\u053b\u054d\u054f\u0531\u0546 |url=https://akunq.net/am/?p=5093 |accessdate=19 December 2019 |work=\u0531\u0580\u0565\u0582\u0574\u057f\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0565\u0582 \u0531\u0580\u0565\u0582\u0574\u057f\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u0540\u0561\u0580\u0581\u0565\u0580\u0578\u0582 \u0548\u0582\u057d\u0578\u0582\u0574\u0576\u0561\u057d\u056b\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u053f\u0565\u0564\u0580\u0578\u0576 |date=19 October 2010 |language=hy}}</ref>) is a city in the [[Kurdistan Region]] of [[Iraq]], at the centre of the eponymous [[Zakho District]] of the [[Dohuk Governorate]], located a few kilometers from the [[Iraq\u2013Turkey border]]. The city has a population of 212,000.\n\nThe original settlement may have been on a small island in the [[Khabur (Tigris)|Little Khabur]] river, which flows through the modern city. The Khabur flows west from Zakho to form the border between Iraq and Turkey, continuing into the [[Tigris]]. The most important rivers in the area are the Zeriza, Seerkotik and the aforementioned Little Khabur.<ref>http://www.zaxo.at/index.php?page=32 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706095721/http://www.zaxo.at/index.php?page=32 |date=2011-07-06 }} retrieved the 15th of May 2011</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Zakho became the seat of the [[University of Zakho]], one of only eleven public universities in the Kurdistan Region.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe derivation of the name \"Zakho\" is from the [[Aramaic]] word ''z\u0101\u1e35\u016b'' (\u05d6\u05b8\u05db\u05d5\u05bc, \"victory\"), after the battle fought between the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] and the [[Persian Empire|Persians]] near the city, which resulted in a Roman victory.\n\n==History==\n{{Further|1991 uprising in Zakho}}\nAccording to an oral tradition transmitted by a Jewish informant from Zakho, Me'allim Levi, Zakho was established in 1568 by Slivani tribesmen, whose territory was streached south of the location of the town. The family of Shamdin Agha came originally from the Slivani tribe, settled in Zakho, and became the most prominent family in Zakho. From the late 19th century onwards, the family of Shamdin Agha ruled \u201call the Muslims, Jews and Christians of Zakho and its surroundings.\u201d<ref>Mordcechai Zaken, Jewish Subjects and their Tribal Vhieftains in Kurdistan, 2007: 33-35.</ref> Zakho was known to the ancient Greeks. In 1844, the traveller [[William Francis Ainsworth]] commented: \"The appearance of Zakho in the present day coincides in a remarkable manner with what it was described to be in the time of Xenophon.\"\n\n[[Gertrude Bell]] was convinced that Zakho was same place as the ancient town of Hasaniyeh. She also reported that the first Christian missionary to the region, the Dominican friar Poldo Soldini, was buried there in 1779. His grave was still a pilgrimage destination in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite book |title= Amurath to Amurath |publisher=Macmillan |last=Bell |first=Gertrude Lothian\n|year=1924 |url= https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.106098\n|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref><ref name=\"Campanile 1953\">{{cite web |title= Histoire du Kurdistan\n|publisher=Le Kr\u00e9y\u00e9|last=Campanile|first=Giuseppe|year=1953|url= http://www.institutkurde.org/publications/etude_kurdes/pdf/Campanile.pdf\n|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nZakho has served as a checkpoint for many decades. It is a major marketplace with its goods and merchandise serving the Kurdish controlled area and most of north and middle Iraq. Writing in 1818, Campanile described the town as a great trading centre, famous for its gallnuts as well as rice, oil, sesame, wax, lentils and many fruits.<ref name=\"Campanile 1953\" />\n\n=== Recent history ===\nDue to its strategic location and the abundance of job opportunities, Zakho has attracted many workers and job seekers from different parts of [[Iraq]] and even from [[Syria]] and [[Turkey]]. Trade with Turkey is now the major element of the economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/topic,45a5199f2,45a519d32,4a697dee1e,0.html|title=KDP Flexes Muscles in Dohuk|date=2009-07-21|publisher=Institute for War and Peace Reporting|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> Oil drilling began in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.institutkurde.org/en/info/foreign-oil-deal-renews-debate-on-kurd-autonomy--1134220944.html|title=Foreign oil deal renews debate on Kurd autonomy|date=2005-12-09|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991 Zakho was the centre of the [[:wikt:safe haven|haven]] established by the British and the Americans in [[Operation Provide Comfort]] to protect the Iraqi Kurds from being massacred by [[Saddam Hussein]] when he responded brutally to the Kurdish rebellion. Most of the inhabitants of the city had fled to the mountains. When the American forces arrived, they described the town as a ghost city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA254123&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf|title=Operation Provide Comfort: a model for future operations|last=Cavanaugh|first=John P.|year=1992|publisher=School of advanced military studies, Fort Leavenworth, Kansas|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nWhen the American Army closed its military base in Zakho in 1996, they evacuated several thousand Kurds who had connections to the base and who feared reprisals. Many of them were given asylum in the USA. According to McDowall, this constituted a sudden and brutal brain-drain, with Zakho losing many of its most educated citizens.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dgDi9qFT41oC&dq=a+modern+history+of+the+kurds&printsec=frontcover&source=bl&ots=C9A7a3YbKQ&sig=Ln-V06XexCrcuOsCNAcMjNajTT8|title=A modern history of the Kurds|last=McDowall|first=David|publisher=Tauris|year=2004|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 it was reported that the Turkish army maintained four bases in the Zakho district, under an agreement concluded with the Iraqi government in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.istockanalyst.com/article/viewiStockNews/articleid/2462785|title=Iraqi Kurdish Paper Says Turkish Military Bases Inside Kurdistan Region|date=2008-08-01|publisher=iStockAnalyst|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004135848/http://www.istockanalyst.com/article/viewiStockNews/articleid/2462785|archivedate=2011-10-04|accessdate=2009-09-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2011 Dohuk riots]] which targeted Assyrian-owned businesses were sparked by Muslim clerics in the town.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/12/03/world/meast/iraq-kurdistan-attack/|title=Kurdish leader: Clerics 'instigated ... acts of sabotage,' wounding 25|last=Tawfeeq|first=Mohammed|date=3 December 2011|newspaper=[[CNN]]|accessdate=4 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n===Assyrians of Zakho===\n[[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] have lived in Zakho since at least the 5th century, with some Assyrian bishops being mentioned from the fifth to the seventh century, which indicates its long history (Chabot, \"Synodicon orientale\", 676). Additionally, The city was the center of a [[Zakho (Chaldean Diocese)|large Chaldean Catholic diocese]] up until the middle of the nineteenth century, when it was divided into three dioceses: Amadia, Zakho, and [[Aqrah|Akra-Zehbar]]. The historic diocese of Zakho corresponded with the ancient Diocese of Malta, formerly a suffragan of [[Erbil|Arbela]], and it had many Chaldean Catholic villages and parishes in the mountains to the north of the city.<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = Chaldean Parishes around the world\n |publisher   = St Peter the Apostle Catholic Diocese for Chaldeans and Assyrians USA\n |url         = http://www.kaldu.org/1_chandean_church/parishes_and_priests.html\n |accessdate  = 2009-09-06\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090814120922/http://www.kaldu.org/1_chandean_church/parishes_and_priests.html\n |archivedate = 2009-08-14\n}}</ref> However, the diocese was recently merged(or in religious terminology, suppressed) back into the [[Chaldean Catholic Eparchy of Amadiya]] in 2013 due to becoming vacant after the death of its Bishop in 2010. Prior to merging with [[Amadiya]], The diocese comprised 3500 Assyrian Catholics, ten resident priests, fifteen parishes or stations, twenty churches and chapels, and one primary school. In regards to the city of Zakho itself, there is a large Assyrian population. The Assyrians of Zakho are primarily [[Chaldean Catholic Church|Chaldean Catholic Christians]] and have a large church which lies in the center of the city which once functioned as the Cathedral of the Diocese,<ref>{{cite web |title=Maryam Alazra church \u2013 Zakho |url=http://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35631.html |website=www.ishtartv.com}}</ref> in addition to a smaller Church as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maryam Alazra church \u2013 Zakho-Abbaseya |url=http://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35633.html |website=www.ishtartv.com}}</ref>\n\n===Armenians of Zakho===\nThe Armenians of Zakho established their community after the [[Armenian Genocide]] from 1915\u20131923, with the first church Armenian church in the city being established in 1923.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maryam Alazra church \u2013Zakho \u2013 Kesta |url=http://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35632.html |website=www.ishtartv.com}}</ref> Some of the Armenians of Zakho left in 1932 to found the village of [[Avzrog]] Miri in the plains west of the city of [[Simele]].<ref>kurdisharmenian.blogspot.com/2008/10/avzrok-armenian-village-in-southern.html</ref>\n\n===Jews of Zakho===\nZakho was formerly known for its [[Synagogue]]<nowiki/>s and large, ancient Jewish community and was known as \"The Jerusalem of Mesopotamia\". The banks of the nearby [[Khabur (Tigris)|Khabur River]] are mentioned in the Bible as one of the places to which the Israelites were exiled (1 Chronicles, 5:26,<ref>[http://usccb.org/nab/bible/1chronicles/1chronicles5.htm 1 Chronicles 5]</ref> 2 Kings 17:6, 2 Kings 18:11).\n\nThe Jews spoke the [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] of their ancestors and were also fluent in kurmanji, the language spoken by non-Jewish Kurds.<ref>{{cite web|title= Unwitting Zionists: The Jewish Community of Zakho in Iraqi Kurdistan p.48|publisher=Wayne State University Press|year=2009|last=Gavish|first=Haya|url= http://wsupress.wayne.edu/books/937/Unwitting-Zionists|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> \n\nKurdish society was primarily a tribal one. Jews of Zalho bore arms like Kurdish Muslims.<ref>{{cite web|title= Unwitting Zionists: The Jewish Community of Zakho in Iraqi Kurdistan p.28|publisher=Wayne State University Press|year=2009|last=Gavish|first=Haya|url= http://wsupress.wayne.edu/books/937/Unwitting-Zionists|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> There was an attack on the Jews in 1891, when one of the synagogues was burnt down. The troubles intensified in 1892. \n\nMost of the Jews relocated to Israel in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|title= Unwitting Zionists: The Jewish Community of Zakho in Iraqi Kurdistan |publisher=Wayne State University Press|year=2009|last=Gavish|first=Haya|url= http://wsupress.wayne.edu/books/937/Unwitting-Zionists|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nWhile the Jews of Zakho were among the least literate in the Jewish diaspora, they had a unique and rich oral tradition, known for its legends, epics and ballads, whose heroes came from both Jewish and Muslim traditions.<ref>{{cite web |title= Changes in the oral tradition among the jews of kurdistan |publisher=Contemporary Jewry - Springer Netherlands|date=2008-10-09\n|last=Shai|first=Donna\n|url= https://doi.org/10.1007%2FBF02965657\n|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nZakho has a hot-summer [[Mediterranean climate]] (''Csa'') with very hot and dry summers, and cool winters with abundant winter rainfall.\n\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Zakho\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan high C = 10.2\n|Feb high C = 12.2\n|Mar high C = 16.5\n|Apr high C = 21.8\n|May high C = 29.1\n|Jun high C = 36.2\n|Jul high C = 40.4\n|Aug high C = 40.0\n|Sep high C = 35.7\n|Oct high C = 27.9\n|Nov high C = 19.4\n|Dec high C = 12.3\n|year high C =\n|Jan low C = 1.9\n|Feb low C = 3.1\n|Mar low C = 6.1\n|Apr low C = 10.1\n|May low C = 15.0\n|Jun low C = 20.1\n|Jul low C = 23.7\n|Aug low C = 23.2\n|Sep low C = 19.2\n|Oct low C = 13.7\n|Nov low C = 8.4\n|Dec low C = 3.9\n|year low C = \n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 144\n|Feb precipitation mm = 136\n|Mar precipitation mm = 129\n|Apr precipitation mm = 109\n|May precipitation mm = 43\n|Jun precipitation mm = 0\n|Jul precipitation mm = 0\n|Aug precipitation mm = 0\n|Sep precipitation mm = 1\n|Oct precipitation mm = 27\n|Nov precipitation mm = 83\n|Dec precipitation mm = 127\n|year precipitation mm =\n|humidity colour=green\n|source 1 = <ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://en.climate-data.org/location/934497/\n| publisher = Climate-Data |title = CLIMATE: ZAKHO |accessdate = 21 January 2017}}</ref>\n|date= 2017\n}}\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:C (201).JPG|thumbnail|Delal Bridge|280px]]\nOne of Zakho's famous landmarks is the [[Delal|Delal Bridge]]. It is made with large stones which adds to the aesthetic value of the bridge and makes it a source of many theories as to how it was built. (The stones are very large, and there was no machinery available at that time.) Delal\n\nZakho castle lies in the city centre on the western bank of Khabir river. It served as the governor's house in the reign of the [[Badinan Emirate]] and was extended by prince Ali Khan. It was built on the ruins of an older castle. Today, only the tower remains.\n[[File:Harrry111111.JPG|thumb|Sharansh waterfall]]\nQubad Pasha castle, in Zakho cemetery, is hexagonal, with six windows and an entrance gate.<ref name=kurdawary>{{cite web\n |title       = Zaxo\n |publisher   = Kurdawary\n |year        = 2004\n |url         = http://www.geocities.com/kurdawarypictures/zaxo.htm\n |accessdate  = 2009-09-06\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20091025204329/http://geocities.com/kurdawarypictures/zaxo.htm\n |archivedate = October 25, 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n== Population displacements ==\nMany [[Assyrian people]] living in the [[diaspora]], notably from American cities such as Nashville, Detroit, San Diego, Houston, and Phoenix, trace their origins to Zakho.{{cn|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn 2007, the UNHCR reported that there were still 10,000 [[internally displaced person]]s in the Zakho district as a result of the [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{cite web\n|title= GOVERNORATE ASSESSMENT REPORT: DAHUK GOVERNORATE\n|publisher=UNHCR\n|date=September 2007\n|url= http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/pdfid/471f4c9ba.pdf\n|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\n== Sports ==\n[[Zakho FC|Zakho Football Club]] (Zakho FC) is a sports club in [[Kurdistan Region]], which was founded in 1987. The sports club plays in the [[Iraqi Premier League]], where only the top 16 Iraqi football clubs play. Zakho FC has its own stadium with a capacity of 20,000 seats.\n[[File:Football Stadium of Zakho.jpg|thumbnail|Football Stadium of Zakho]]\nZakho Basketball Club ([[Zakho SC]]) is a team based in Zakho, [[Kurdistan Region]]. In 2011 Zakho SC won the Kurdistan Basketball Super Cup and beat [[Duhok SC (basketball)|Duhok SC]] in [[Erbil]].<ref>[http://www.kurdishglobe.net/article/35414131C83363E6262B94DC0300AD09/Zakho-wins-Kurdistan-basketball-Super-Cup.html \"Zakho wins Kurdistan basketball Super Cup] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307172438/http://www.kurdishglobe.net/article/35414131C83363E6262B94DC0300AD09/Zakho-wins-Kurdistan-basketball-Super-Cup.html |date=2014-03-07 }},\" ''Kurdish Globe'', retrieved 2014-01-30</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Zakho (Chaldean Diocese)]]\n* [[Erdewan Zaxoyi]]\n* [[Eyaz Zaxoy\u00ee]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Chabot|first=Jean-Baptiste|authorlink=Jean-Baptiste Chabot|title=Synodicon orientale ou recueil de synodes nestoriens|year=1902|location=Paris|publisher=Imprimerie Nationale|url=https://archive.org/download/ChabotSynodiconOrientale/chabot%20synodicon%20orientale.pdf}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.today/20130103232446/http://www.iraqimage.com/pages/browse/Zakho.html Iraq Image - Zakho Satellite Observation]\n\n{{coord|37|09|N|42|41|E|region:IQ_type:city|display=title}}\n\n{{Commons category|Zakho|position=left}}\n\n{{Assyrian topics}}\n{{Districts of Iraq}}\n\n[[Category:Zakho| ]]\n[[Category:District capitals of Iraq]]\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Assyria]]\n[[Category:Assyrian geography]]\n[[Category:Cities in Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dohuk Province]]\n[[Category:Jewish Iraqi history]]\n[[Category:Kurdish settlements]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|a city in northern Iraq}}{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name            = Zakho\n| native_name              = {{lang|ku|\u0632\u0627\u062e\u06c6 ,Zaxo}}<br>{{lang|syr|\u0719\u0735\u071f\u0742\u0718\u073f}}\n| other_name               =\n|image_skyline          = Pira.delal.zaxo.jpg\n|imagesize              =\n|image_caption          = The Little Khabur flowing through Zakho\n|image_flag =\n|image_seal =\n|image_map =\n|map_caption =\n|pushpin_map = Iraqi Kurdistan#Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position =bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location in Iraq\n|coordinates            = {{coord|37|08|37.00|N|42|40|54.88|E|region:IQ|display=inline}}\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      =Region\n|subdivision_type2      = Governorate\n|subdivision_type3      = District\n|subdivision_name1      ={{flag|Kurdistan Region}}\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Dohuk Governorate]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Zakho District]]\n|established_title =\n|established_date =\n|government_type =\n|leader_title =\n|leader_name =\n|area_magnitude =\n|area_total_km2 =\n|area_total_sq_mi =\n|area_land_km2 =\n|area_land_sq_mi =\n|area_urban_km2 =\n|area_urban_sq_mi =\n|area_metro_km2 =\n|area_metro_sq_mi =\n|elevation_footnotes=\n|elevation_m = 440\n|elevation_ft =\n|population_total = 212,000+\n|population_as_of= 2018\n|population_density_km2 =\n|population_density_sq_mi =\n|population_urban =\n|population_metro =\n|postal_code_type =\n|postal_code =\n|area_code =\n|website =\n|footnotes =\n|timezone = UTC+3\n|utc_offset =\n|timezone_DST = not observed\n|utc_offset_DST =\n}}\n\n'''Zakho''' ({{lang-ku|\u0632\u0627\u062e\u06c6 ,Zaxo}},<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0632\u0627\u062e\u06c6 |url=http://bot.gov.krd/kurdish/duhok-province/zakho |accessdate=18 December 2019 |language=ku}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=Celil\u00ea Celil, Dzhalile Dzhalil |title=Jiyana rew\u015fenb\u00eer\u00ee \u00fb s\u00eeyas\u00ee ya Kurdan: di daw\u00eeya sedsala 19'a \u00fb destp\u00eaka sedsala 20'a da |date=1985 |page=154 |language=ku}}</ref> {{lang-ar|\u0632\u0627\u062e\u0648}};<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0632\u0627\u062e\u0648 {{!}} \u0643\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0647\u0634\u0629 - \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0633\u0645\u064a \u0644\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0627\u062d\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 |url=http://bot.gov.krd/arabic/duhok-province/zakho |website=bot.gov.krd |accessdate=19 December 2019 |language=ar}}</ref> {{lang-syr|\u0719\u0735\u071f\u0323\u0718\u0307|Z\u0101kh\u014d}}),<ref>{{cite web |title=List of all entries |url=http://www.assyrianlanguages.org/sureth/list.php?initial=z |website=Assyrian Languages |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> {{lang-he-n|\u05d6\u05d0\u05db\u05d5}};<ref>{{cite web |title=\u05e7\u05d4\u05d9\u05dc\u05d5\u05ea - \u05d6\u05d0\u05db\u05d5 |url=http://www.kurdishjewry.org.il/kehil/Zako.htm |website=www.kurdishjewry.org.il |accessdate=19 December 2019 |language=he}}</ref> {{Lang-hy|\u0536\u0561\u056d\u0578}}<ref>{{cite news |title=\u053b\u0550\u0531\u0554\u0545\u0531\u0546 \u0554\u0548\u0552\u0550\u0534\u053b\u054d\u054f\u0531\u0546 |url=https://akunq.net/am/?p=5093 |accessdate=19 December 2019 |work=\u0531\u0580\u0565\u0582\u0574\u057f\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0565\u0582 \u0531\u0580\u0565\u0582\u0574\u057f\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u0540\u0561\u0580\u0581\u0565\u0580\u0578\u0582 \u0548\u0582\u057d\u0578\u0582\u0574\u0576\u0561\u057d\u056b\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0565\u0561\u0576 \u053f\u0565\u0564\u0580\u0578\u0576 |date=19 October 2010 |language=hy}}</ref>) is a city in the [[Kurdistan Region]] of [[Iraq]], at the centre of the eponymous [[Zakho District]] of the [[Dohuk Governorate]], located a few kilometers from the [[Iraq\u2013Turkey border]]. The city has a population of 212,000.\n\nThe original settlement may have been on a small island in the [[Khabur (Tigris)|Little Khabur]] river, which flows through the modern city. The Khabur flows west from Zakho to form the border between Iraq and Turkey, continuing into the [[Tigris]]. The most important rivers in the area are the Zeriza, Seerkotik and the aforementioned Little Khabur.<ref>http://www.zaxo.at/index.php?page=32 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706095721/http://www.zaxo.at/index.php?page=32 |date=2011-07-06 }} retrieved the 15th of May 2011</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Zakho became the seat of the [[University of Zakho]], one of only eleven public universities in the Kurdistan Region.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe derivation of the name \"Zakho\" is from the [[Aramaic]] word ''z\u0101\u1e35\u016b'' (\u05d6\u05b8\u05db\u05d5\u05bc, \"victory\"), after the battle fought between the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] and the [[Persian Empire|Persians]] near the city, which resulted in a Roman victory.\n\n==History==\n{{Further|1991 uprising in Zakho}}\nAccording to an oral tradition transmitted by a Jewish informant from Zakho, Me'allim Levi, Zakho was established in 1568 by Slivani tribesmen, whose territory was streached south of the location of the town. The family of Shamdin Agha came originally from the Slivani tribe, settled in Zakho, and became the most prominent family in Zakho. From the late 19th century onwards, the family of Shamdin Agha ruled \u201call the Muslims, Jews and Christians of Zakho and its surroundings.\u201d<ref>Mordcechai Zaken, Jewish Subjects and their Tribal Vhieftains in Kurdistan, 2007: 33-35.</ref> Zakho was known to the ancient Greeks. In 1844, the traveller [[William Francis Ainsworth]] commented: \"The appearance of Zakho in the present day coincides in a remarkable manner with what it was described to be in the time of Xenophon.\"\n\n[[Gertrude Bell]] was convinced that Zakho was same place as the ancient town of Hasaniyeh. She also reported that the first Christian missionary to the region, the Dominican friar Poldo Soldini, was buried there in 1779. His grave was still a pilgrimage destination in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite book |title= Amurath to Amurath |publisher=Macmillan |last=Bell |first=Gertrude Lothian\n|year=1924 |url= https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.106098\n|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref><ref name=\"Campanile 1953\">{{cite web |title= Histoire du Kurdistan\n|publisher=Le Kr\u00e9y\u00e9|last=Campanile|first=Giuseppe|year=1953|url= http://www.institutkurde.org/publications/etude_kurdes/pdf/Campanile.pdf\n|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nZakho has served as a checkpoint for many decades. It is a major marketplace with its goods and merchandise serving the Kurdish controlled area and most of north and middle Iraq. Writing in 1818, Campanile described the town as a great trading centre, famous for its gallnuts as well as rice, oil, sesame, wax, lentils and many fruits.<ref name=\"Campanile 1953\" />\n\n=== Recent history ===\nDue to its strategic location and the abundance of job opportunities, Zakho has attracted many workers and job seekers from different parts of [[Iraq]] and even from [[Syria]] and [[Turkey]]. Trade with Turkey is now the major element of the economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/topic,45a5199f2,45a519d32,4a697dee1e,0.html|title=KDP Flexes Muscles in Dohuk|date=2009-07-21|publisher=Institute for War and Peace Reporting|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> Oil drilling began in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.institutkurde.org/en/info/foreign-oil-deal-renews-debate-on-kurd-autonomy--1134220944.html|title=Foreign oil deal renews debate on Kurd autonomy|date=2005-12-09|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991 Zakho was the centre of the [[:wikt:safe haven|haven]] established by the British and the Americans in [[Operation Provide Comfort]] to protect the Iraqi Kurds from being massacred by [[Saddam Hussein]] when he responded brutally to the Kurdish rebellion. Most of the inhabitants of the city had fled to the mountains. When the American forces arrived, they described the town as a ghost city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA254123&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf|title=Operation Provide Comfort: a model for future operations|last=Cavanaugh|first=John P.|year=1992|publisher=School of advanced military studies, Fort Leavenworth, Kansas|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nWhen the American Army closed its military base in Zakho in 1996, they evacuated several thousand Kurds who had connections to the base and who feared reprisals. Many of them were given asylum in the USA. According to McDowall, this constituted a sudden and brutal brain-drain, with Zakho losing many of its most educated citizens.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dgDi9qFT41oC&dq=a+modern+history+of+the+kurds&printsec=frontcover&source=bl&ots=C9A7a3YbKQ&sig=Ln-V06XexCrcuOsCNAcMjNajTT8|title=A modern history of the Kurds|last=McDowall|first=David|publisher=Tauris|year=2004|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 it was reported that the Turkish army maintained four bases in the Zakho district, under an agreement concluded with the Iraqi government in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.istockanalyst.com/article/viewiStockNews/articleid/2462785|title=Iraqi Kurdish Paper Says Turkish Military Bases Inside Kurdistan Region|date=2008-08-01|publisher=iStockAnalyst|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004135848/http://www.istockanalyst.com/article/viewiStockNews/articleid/2462785|archivedate=2011-10-04|accessdate=2009-09-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2011 Dohuk riots]] which targeted Assyrian-owned businesses were sparked by Muslim clerics in the town.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/12/03/world/meast/iraq-kurdistan-attack/|title=Kurdish leader: Clerics 'instigated ... acts of sabotage,' wounding 25|last=Tawfeeq|first=Mohammed|date=3 December 2011|newspaper=[[CNN]]|accessdate=4 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n===Assyrians of Zakho===\n[[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] have lived in Zakho since at least the 5th century, with some Assyrian bishops being mentioned from the fifth to the seventh century, which indicates its long history (Chabot, \"Synodicon orientale\", 676). Additionally, The city was the center of a [[Zakho (Chaldean Diocese)|large Chaldean Catholic diocese]] up until the middle of the nineteenth century, when it was divided into three dioceses: Amadia, Zakho, and [[Aqrah|Akra-Zehbar]]. The historic diocese of Zakho corresponded with the ancient Diocese of Malta, formerly a suffragan of [[Erbil|Arbela]], and it had many Chaldean Catholic villages and parishes in the mountains to the north of the city.<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = Chaldean Parishes around the world\n |publisher   = St Peter the Apostle Catholic Diocese for Chaldeans and Assyrians USA\n |url         = http://www.kaldu.org/1_chandean_church/parishes_and_priests.html\n |accessdate  = 2009-09-06\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090814120922/http://www.kaldu.org/1_chandean_church/parishes_and_priests.html\n |archivedate = 2009-08-14\n}}</ref> However, the diocese was recently merged(or in religious terminology, suppressed) back into the [[Chaldean Catholic Eparchy of Amadiya]] in 2013 due to becoming vacant after the death of its Bishop in 2010. Prior to merging with [[Amadiya]], The diocese comprised 3500 Assyrian Catholics, ten resident priests, fifteen parishes or stations, twenty churches and chapels, and one primary school. In regards to the city of Zakho itself, there is a large Assyrian population. The Assyrians of Zakho are primarily [[Chaldean Catholic Church|Chaldean Catholic Christians]] and have a large church which lies in the center of the city which once functioned as the Cathedral of the Diocese,<ref>{{cite web |title=Maryam Alazra church \u2013 Zakho |url=http://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35631.html |website=www.ishtartv.com}}</ref> in addition to a smaller Church as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maryam Alazra church \u2013 Zakho-Abbaseya |url=http://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35633.html |website=www.ishtartv.com}}</ref>\n\n===Armenians of Zakho===\nThe Armenians of Zakho established their community after the [[Armenian Genocide]] from 1915\u20131923, with the first church Armenian church in the city being established in 1923.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maryam Alazra church \u2013Zakho \u2013 Kesta |url=http://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35632.html |website=www.ishtartv.com}}</ref> Some of the Armenians of Zakho left in 1932 to found the village of [[Avzrog]] Miri in the plains west of the city of [[Simele]].<ref>kurdisharmenian.blogspot.com/2008/10/avzrok-armenian-village-in-southern.html</ref>\n\n===Jews of Zakho===\nZakho was formerly known for its [[Synagogue]]<nowiki/>s and large, ancient Jewish community and was known as \"The Jerusalem of Mesopotamia\". The banks of the nearby [[Khabur (Tigris)|Khabur River]] are mentioned in the Bible as one of the places to which the Israelites were exiled (1 Chronicles, 5:26,<ref>[http://usccb.org/nab/bible/1chronicles/1chronicles5.htm 1 Chronicles 5]</ref> 2 Kings 17:6, 2 Kings 18:11).\n\nThe Jews spoke the [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] of their ancestors and were also fluent in kurmanji, the language spoken by non-Jewish Kurds.<ref>{{cite web|title= Unwitting Zionists: The Jewish Community of Zakho in Iraqi Kurdistan p.48|publisher=Wayne State University Press|year=2009|last=Gavish|first=Haya|url= http://wsupress.wayne.edu/books/937/Unwitting-Zionists|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> \n\nKurdish society was primarily a tribal one. Jews of Zalho bore arms like Kurdish Muslims.<ref>{{cite web|title= Unwitting Zionists: The Jewish Community of Zakho in Iraqi Kurdistan p.28|publisher=Wayne State University Press|year=2009|last=Gavish|first=Haya|url= http://wsupress.wayne.edu/books/937/Unwitting-Zionists|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> There was an attack on the Jews in 1891, when one of the synagogues was burnt down. The troubles intensified in 1892. \n\nMost of the Jews relocated to Israel in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|title= Unwitting Zionists: The Jewish Community of Zakho in Iraqi Kurdistan |publisher=Wayne State University Press|year=2009|last=Gavish|first=Haya|url= http://wsupress.wayne.edu/books/937/Unwitting-Zionists|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nWhile the Jews of Zakho were among the least literate in the Jewish diaspora, they had a unique and rich oral tradition, known for its legends, epics and ballads, whose heroes came from both Jewish and Muslim traditions.<ref>{{cite web |title= Changes in the oral tradition among the jews of kurdistan |publisher=Contemporary Jewry - Springer Netherlands|date=2008-10-09\n|last=Shai|first=Donna\n|url= https://doi.org/10.1007%2FBF02965657\n|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nZakho has a hot-summer [[Mediterranean climate]] (''Csa'') with very hot and dry summers, and cool winters with abundant winter rainfall.\n\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Zakho\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan high C = 10.2\n|Feb high C = 12.2\n|Mar high C = 16.5\n|Apr high C = 21.8\n|May high C = 29.1\n|Jun high C = 36.2\n|Jul high C = 40.4\n|Aug high C = 40.0\n|Sep high C = 35.7\n|Oct high C = 27.9\n|Nov high C = 19.4\n|Dec high C = 12.3\n|year high C =\n|Jan low C = 1.9\n|Feb low C = 3.1\n|Mar low C = 6.1\n|Apr low C = 10.1\n|May low C = 15.0\n|Jun low C = 20.1\n|Jul low C = 23.7\n|Aug low C = 23.2\n|Sep low C = 19.2\n|Oct low C = 13.7\n|Nov low C = 8.4\n|Dec low C = 3.9\n|year low C = \n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 144\n|Feb precipitation mm = 136\n|Mar precipitation mm = 129\n|Apr precipitation mm = 109\n|May precipitation mm = 43\n|Jun precipitation mm = 0\n|Jul precipitation mm = 0\n|Aug precipitation mm = 0\n|Sep precipitation mm = 1\n|Oct precipitation mm = 27\n|Nov precipitation mm = 83\n|Dec precipitation mm = 127\n|year precipitation mm =\n|humidity colour=green\n|source 1 = <ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://en.climate-data.org/location/934497/\n| publisher = Climate-Data |title = CLIMATE: ZAKHO |accessdate = 21 January 2017}}</ref>\n|date= 2017\n}}\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:C (201).JPG|thumbnail|Delal Bridge|280px]]\nOne of Zakho's famous landmarks is the [[Delal|Delal Bridge]]. It is made with large stones which adds to the aesthetic value of the bridge and makes it a source of many theories as to how it was built. (The stones are very large, and there was no machinery available at that time.) Delal\n\nZakho castle lies in the city centre on the western bank of Khabir river. It served as the governor's house in the reign of the [[Badinan Emirate]] and was extended by prince Ali Khan. It was built on the ruins of an older castle. Today, only the tower remains.\n[[File:Harrry111111.JPG|thumb|Sharansh waterfall]]\nQubad Pasha castle, in Zakho cemetery, is hexagonal, with six windows and an entrance gate.<ref name=kurdawary>{{cite web\n |title       = Zaxo\n |publisher   = Kurdawary\n |year        = 2004\n |url         = http://www.geocities.com/kurdawarypictures/zaxo.htm\n |accessdate  = 2009-09-06\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20091025204329/http://geocities.com/kurdawarypictures/zaxo.htm\n |archivedate = October 25, 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n== Population displacements ==\nMany [[Assyrian people]] living in the [[diaspora]], notably from American cities such as Nashville, Detroit, San Diego, Houston, and Phoenix, trace their origins to Zakho.{{cn|date=June 2017}}\n\nIn 2007, the UNHCR reported that there were still 10,000 [[internally displaced person]]s in the Zakho district as a result of the [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{cite web\n|title= GOVERNORATE ASSESSMENT REPORT: DAHUK GOVERNORATE\n|publisher=UNHCR\n|date=September 2007\n|url= http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/pdfid/471f4c9ba.pdf\n|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\n== Sports ==\n[[Zakho FC|Zakho Football Club]] (Zakho FC) is a sports club in [[Kurdistan Region]], which was founded in 1987. The sports club plays in the [[Iraqi Premier League]], where only the top 16 Iraqi football clubs play. Zakho FC has its own stadium with a capacity of 20,000 seats.\n[[File:Football Stadium of Zakho.jpg|thumbnail|Football Stadium of Zakho]]\nZakho Basketball Club ([[Zakho SC]]) is a team based in Zakho, [[Kurdistan Region]]. In 2011 Zakho SC won the Kurdistan Basketball Super Cup and beat [[Duhok SC (basketball)|Duhok SC]] in [[Erbil]].<ref>[http://www.kurdishglobe.net/article/35414131C83363E6262B94DC0300AD09/Zakho-wins-Kurdistan-basketball-Super-Cup.html \"Zakho wins Kurdistan basketball Super Cup] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307172438/http://www.kurdishglobe.net/article/35414131C83363E6262B94DC0300AD09/Zakho-wins-Kurdistan-basketball-Super-Cup.html |date=2014-03-07 }},\" ''Kurdish Globe'', retrieved 2014-01-30</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Zakho (Chaldean Diocese)]]\n* [[Erdewan Zaxoyi]]\n* [[Eyaz Zaxoy\u00ee]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Chabot|first=Jean-Baptiste|authorlink=Jean-Baptiste Chabot|title=Synodicon orientale ou recueil de synodes nestoriens|year=1902|location=Paris|publisher=Imprimerie Nationale|url=https://archive.org/download/ChabotSynodiconOrientale/chabot%20synodicon%20orientale.pdf}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.today/20130103232446/http://www.iraqimage.com/pages/browse/Zakho.html Iraq Image - Zakho Satellite Observation]\n\n{{coord|37|09|N|42|41|E|region:IQ_type:city|display=title}}\n\n{{Commons category|Zakho|position=left}}\n\n{{Assyrian topics}}\n{{Districts of Iraq}}\n\n[[Category:Zakho| ]]\n[[Category:District capitals of Iraq]]\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Assyria]]\n[[Category:Assyrian geography]]\n[[Category:Cities in Iraqi Kurdistan]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dohuk Province]]\n[[Category:Jewish Iraqi history]]\n[[Category:Kurdish settlements]]\n", "name_user": "Heizellshock", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zakho"}
{"title_page": "Lakhta Center", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}{{Infobox building\n| name = Lakhta Center\n| native_name = \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\n| native_name_lang = ru\n| former_names = Gazprom Tower, [[Okhta Center]]\n| alternate_names = \n| status = {{Color|green|Completed}}\n| image = Saint Petersburg Lakhta center 06.jpg\n| image_alt = \n| image_size = 280px\n| caption = July 2018\n| location = [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]], [[Saint Petersburg]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|59|59|13.7|N|30|10|37.3|E|region:RU|display=inline,title}}\n| address = \n| location_town = \n| location_country = Russia\n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date = 2012\n| completion_date = 2019\n| opened_date = \n| inauguration_date = \n| demolition_date = \n| destruction_date = \n| architect = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT\n| landlord = \n| owner = [[Gazprom Neft]]\n| cost = US$1.77 billion<ref>[https://realty.rbc.ru/news/5bed46bd9a794728d6707196]</ref>\n| floor_area = \n| top_floor = \n| floor_count = 87\n| awards = \n| parking = \n| embedded = \n| references = \n| highest_region = \n| highest_reflabel = \n| highest_prev = \n| highest_start = \n| highest_end = \n| highest_next = \n| map_type = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| altitude = \n| building_type = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system = \n| current_tenants = \n| renovation_date = \n| height = {{convert|462|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| architectural = \n| tip = \n| antenna_spire = \n| roof = \n| observatory = \n| other_dimensions = \n| elevator_count = 40<ref>[https://habr.com/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371087/ Elevators in a skyscraper]</ref>\n| architecture_firm = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT<ref>[https://www.houseandgarden.co.uk/article/europes-tallest-skyscraper-lakhta-centre Europe's tallest skyscraper is nearing completion in St. Petersburg]</ref>\n| main_contractor = [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]\n| designations = \n| url = \n}}\nThe '''Lakhta Center''' ({{Lang-rus|\u041b\u0430\u0301\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0442\u0440|r=Lakhta tsentr}}) is an 87-story [[skyscraper]] built in the outskirts of [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]] in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]]. Standing {{convert|462|m|ft}} tall, the Lakhta Center is the [[List of tallest buildings in Russia|tallest building in Russia]], the [[List of tallest buildings in Europe|tallest building in Europe]], and the [[List of tallest buildings|16th-tallest building in the world]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title=Lakhta Center - The Skyscraper Center|website=skyscrapercenter.com|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/ru/about/project/ |title=Lakhta Center Website, \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043f\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/uploaded/file_list/ROSAVIA706(19.07.2011).pdf |title=Federal Air Transport Agency Authorization |date=2011-07-19 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title= Lakhta Center|accessdate= 22 January 2014|work= The Skyscraper Center|publisher= [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]]}}</ref> The Lakhta Center is also the second-tallest structure in Russia and Europe, behind [[Ostankino Tower]] in [[Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|title=Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat, '100 Future tallest buildings in the world'|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723110141/http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|archivedate=2012-07-23|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of Lakhta Center started on 30 October 2012; it was topped out on 29 January 2018.<ref name=\"installation\" >[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1295 The installation of the spire of the Lakhta Center], Press release of 29 January 2018.</ref> The Lakhta Center surpassed Vostok Tower of the [[Federation Tower|Federation Towers]] in Moscow as the tallest building in Russia and Europe on 5 October 2017. The center is designed for large-scale [[mixed-use development]], consisting of public facilities and offices.  The building was designed by [[RMJM]]. The project was then continued by GORPROJECT (2011-2017) based on the RMJM Concept (2011) under the main contractor, [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]. The Lakhta Center is intended to become the new headquarters of Russian energy company [[Gazprom]].\n\nOn December 24, 2018, Lakhta Center was certified according to the criteria of ecological efficiency at [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Platinum<ref>[https://www.usgbc.org/projects/lakhta-centertower Lakhta Center-Tower]</ref> \u2013 it is one of the five most eco-friendly skyscrapers in the world.<ref>[https://realty.ria.ru/20191220/1562593482.html The Chronicles of the stone of greens, as buildings become energy efficient]</ref> The concrete pouring of the bottom slab of Lakhta Center's foundation was registered by [[Guinness World Records]] as the largest continuous concrete pour; 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were used, which is approximately 3,000 cubic meters more than in the previous record registered at [[Wilshire Grand Tower]].<ref>[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-continuous-concrete-pour/ Largest Continuous Concrete Pour]</ref> The tower's [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain wall]] is also the world\u2019s largest cold-bent facade by area.\n\nThe opening date of the complex will be determined after the completion of finishing and landscaping. The improvement of the embankments is planned to be completed at the end of 2020.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2019/08/08/Vozle_Lahti-centra_pojav Near the \"Lakhta center\" will be a public space with \" glass wings\"]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Planning ===\n\nOn, 26 January 2012, it became known that [[Gazprom]] was planning to build a new harbor for yachts near Lakhta Center and Krestovsky Island. A new company for managing these sea assets was to be created.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/01/26/157/#comments \u0413\u0430\u0437\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0438\u0437 \"\u041b\u0435\u043d\u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u043e\" \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u044f\u0445\u0442]</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2012, it was announced that a new metro station was to be constructed near Lakhta Center. This metro station's building was included in the City development plan of [[Leningrad]] in 1980 but only with the construction of the Lakhta Center did it again enter the agenda. The plan of the metro station's construction was to be finalized by the end of 2012.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/03/16/074/ \u0412\u044b\u0445\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0413\u0418\u0411\u0414\u0414 16.03.2012 13:26]</ref>\n\nOn 17 August 2012 the permit for construction of the first stage of Lakhta Center, which included a skyscraper and stylobate, was obtained.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/08/20/114/ \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e]</ref>\nOn 31 August 2012, a public hearing on the topic of the layout and surveying of the site of the Lakhta Center was held in the administration of the Primorsky district of Saint Petersburg. Objects planned for placing in the area of construction, scheme of communications and transportation infrastructure were presented to the public.<ref>[http://izvestia.ru/news/534256 \u041d\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433]</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\nApproximately 3000 people will be employed in the construction, mostly from professions relating to design and construction. After construction, a few thousand workers of different occupations were expected to be employed in the complex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2235582|title=\"\u0421\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u043c\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\"|date=2013-07-17|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref>\n\nGeodesic, ecologic and soil investigations and design documentation for the project were prepared by GORPROJECT (Russia), NIIOSP (Russia), Petrochim-technologiya LLC (Russia) and Trest GRII JSC (Russia). In planning and executing works at the underground cycle, piling and producing construction materials such companies as [[Arabtec]] (UAE), [[Bauer Group]] (Germany), Geostroy CJSC (Russia), Inforsproekt CJSC (Russia) and Renaissance Construction (Turkey) take part. Verification calculations, working documentation development, optimisation of processes and technical supervision are performed by [[Arup Group Limited]] (Great Britain), [[Samsung C&T]] (Korea) and [[Lend Lease Project Management & Construction]] (Great Britain). Project management is being done by [[AECOM]] (USA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/|title=Key Contractors|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n[http://www.exclusivadesign.com Exclusiva Design] (Italy) is key contractor for the interior design of public spaces.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/exclusiva/ Exclusiva Design]</ref><ref>[http://www.exclusivadesign.com/lakhta-center-exclusiva-wins-the-bid-to-design-the-public-spaces/?lang=en/ Lakhta Center: Exclusiva Design wins the Bid to Design the Public Spaces]</ref> German company Josef Gartner is in charge for the glazing of the skyscraper.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2015/09/16/Nemeckaja_Gartner_otkroet/ \u041d\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f Gartner \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043a\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref> Glazed facades of Entrance Arch as well as parts of Multi-functional building are done by [[Waagner-Biro]].\n\nOn 30 October 2012 the zero cycle works started. Zero cycle consists of the pit excavation, installation of the disk system, piling under the tower, multifunctional building and stylobate and construction of the foundation itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/current/|title= Lakhta Center. Project status|accessdate=2014-08-09}}</ref>\n\n22 April 2014 the main potential general contractor for the construction of Lakhta Center was selected. It was Turkish Renaissance Construction company.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/news/?id=237 Potential general constructor selected]</ref> 22 May 2014 the contract for the construction of the foundation of one of the buildings in Lakhta Center was finally signed.\n\n<div>Lakhta Center Construction Time Schedule:</div>\n\n* March 2013 \u2013 zero cycle works are in process. Piles are being installed. According to the schedule of construction a [[diaphragm wall]] is to be completed by the end of April while piling works will continue until 15 August 2013.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=390991 \u0418\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u041e\u0414\u0426 \"\u041e\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0410.\u0411\u043e\u0431\u043a\u043e\u0432: \"\u0412 \u201e\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\u201c \u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0435\u0439\"]</ref>\n* July 2013 \u2013 mounting of the 264 piles under the box-type foundation has been finished. Excavation of the foundation pit is in progress.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413160601/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php |date=13 April 2015 }}</ref>\n* September 2013 \u2013 total area of the site is announced to be increased from 330 to 400 thousand square meters due to a 700 parking space expansion to the planned parking spaces.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |title=\u0421\u0422\u0420\u041e\u0418\u0422\u0415\u041b\u042c\u0421\u0422\u0412\u041e \u041d\u0423\u041b\u0415\u0412\u041e\u0413\u041e \u0426\u0418\u041a\u041b\u0410 \"\u041b\u0410\u0425\u0422\u0410 \u0426\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0420\u0410\" \u041e\u0426\u0415\u041d\u0418\u041b\u0418 \u0412 $100 \u041c\u041b\u041d |access-date=26 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128003246/http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |archive-date=28 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* October 2013 \u2013 construction of box-type foundation has been started. According to the plan this part of the work is to be finished in 2014.<ref>[http://advis.ru/php/view_news.php?id=763315EE-9CD4-6040-80D4-FA160CE9C441 \u0420\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u044b \u043d\u0443\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0435 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\".]</ref>\n\n* December 2013 \u2013 mounting of the concrete disks to the [[diaphragm wall]] has started. Disks are to provide the diaphragm wall with more resistance to outside ground pressure.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |title=\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431 \u0443 \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430. |access-date=10 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317210545/http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |archive-date=17 March 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* April 2014 \u2013 construction of foundation pit for the skyscraper is over.<ref>[http://karpovka.net/2014/04/02/137579/ \u0413\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref>\n* June 2014 \u2013 piling is completed. 264 piles were mounted for the tower of Lakhta Center, 848 piles were mounted for the mixed-use building and entrance arch and 968 piles were mounted for the stylobate (undergroung parking). All in all 2080 piles were dug in.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=892 All 2080 Piles in Lakhta Center Foundation]</ref>\n* September 2014 \u2013 excavation of the foundation pit for the mixed-use building has been finished. Foundation concreting has started.\n* February and March 2015 \u2013 the pouring of the bottom slab of the skyscraper's box shaped foundation over. 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were cast in the foundation.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2015/03/02/169/ Alexey Miller: First floors of the skyscraper in Lakhta will appear this year]</ref>\n* June 2015 \u2013 construction of the underground floors has finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 pouring of the 2m thick upper box foundation slab has been completed, which means that all works below zero elevation are finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 the construction of the first floors of the tower core is underway.<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=1087 Pouring of the Upper Slab of the Lakhta Center Tower Foundation]</ref>\n* January 2016 \u2013 construction of the succeeding ten floors of the tower; works on stylobate complex.\n* April 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 22-26. Installation of the metal farm in the 18-22nd floors of the tower.\n* May 2016 \u2013 glazing of the facade of the Tower has started.\n* September 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 46-50.<ref>[https://www.liebherr.com/en/deu/latest-news/news-press-releases/detail/liebherr-tower-cranes-in-action-erecting-the-highest-building-in-europe.html?news.type=press/ Liebherr tower cranes in action erecting the highest building in Europe]</ref>\n* December 2016 \u2013 installation of facade at floors 16-18; construction of the tower core at floors 57-61 \n* February 2017 \u2013 Lahkta Center's tower reaches height of 260 metres; floors 61-64 are under construction.\n* April 2017 -  height exceeds 300 meters, making Lakhta Center a [[supertall]] building (international classification), work is being done on the 67 floor.\n* May 2017 - the skyscraper reached the height 327,6 meters, working on the 78th floor.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2017/05/13/034/ Lakhta Center outgrew the tower]</ref>\n* August 2017 - Installation of the spire starts at 83 floors.\n* 5 October 2017 - Lakhta center became the tallest building in Europe when it reached a height of 374 meters.<ref>[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1280 European altitude record broken]</ref><ref>[http://www.euronews.com/2017/10/06/russian-skyscraper-becomes-europe-s-tallest-building# Russian skyscraper \u2018becomes Europe\u2019s tallest building]</ref>\n* 29 January 2018 - the height of Lakhta center project reached a height of 462 meters, the assembly of structures of the spire is completed. The glazing of the tower continues at floor 70.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Y-0SYU5sJU Lakhta Center reached the design height]</ref>\n* 20 June 2018 - The last tower crane was removed. The developers were motivated to finish work requiring tower cranes before the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] semi finals in order to make the building look architecturally complete. <ref>{{cite web |title=The last tower crane has been removed at the Lakhta Center construction site |url=https://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1311 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=English |date=20 June 2018}}</ref>\n* On 27 June 2018, the initial commissioning of the building was carried out. Technical documentation, building plan and technical passport were prepared.<ref>[https://www.archdaily.com/898132/europes-tallest-skyscraper-approaches-completion-in-st-petersburg Europe's Tallest Skyscraper Approaches Completion in St Petersburg]</ref>\n* On 16 October 2018, Lakhta Center MFC JSC received authorization for commissioning of the facility. The relevant document was officially published by the State Construction Supervision and Inspection Service of Saint Petersburg, Russia. There is about a year to go until the opening of Lakhta Center Multifunctional Complex, its dominant being the tallest skyscraper of Europe.<ref>[https://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1321 Lakhta Center Officially Commissioned]</ref>\n\nNext to the already commissioned Lakhta Center, construction continues. To the four objects of the complex (tower, multi-purpose building, arch, stylobate) will be added one more. According to official documents, it takes place under the name \"Complex of buildings and structures\", or simply KZS.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/03/28/111/ \"Complex of buildings and structures\"]</ref>\n\nThe complex of buildings and structures is a single building consisting of two buildings connected by a courtyard. The authors of the project suggest that it will not only strengthen the office function of the Lakhta Center, but also complete the formation of the architectural ensemble, balancing the skyscraper in the horizontal.<ref>[https://www.the-village.ru/village/city/news-city/345989-kzs-lahta \"Complex of buildings and structures\". It will be built at the \"Lakhta center\" in 2021]</ref> The total area of the Lakhta center is 400 000 m\u00b2. With the addition of the KZS, the total area of the complex is 570 000 m\u00b2.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=924846&sec=1679 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442 Renaissance Construction]</ref>\n\n== Multi-functional building ==\nMulti-functional building (MFZ) - an object divided into two buildings - North and South, which are United by a common Foundation, stylobate and roof. The building resembles a boomerang. It has a variable number of storeys with a height difference from 7 to 17 floors, with the peak height being a little more than 80 meters. The building is approximately 300 meters long.  Feature - negative angle of the end facades due to the removal of the console on 25 m. Facades - glass, with a total area of more than 60 thousand m2.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371535/ Horizontal versus vertical. Or for? Why Lakhta Center \"recumbent\" dominant]</ref>\n\nConstructive scheme of the building - frame. More than 24 thousand tons of metal structures were used for the construction of this facility.\n\nThe main load-bearing elements are 4 reinforced concrete cores which perceive horizontal and vertical loadings, transferring them to the base executed in the form of the plate grillage leaning against piles. Between the Southern and Northern buildings of the MFZ along the entire height of the atrium, with a roof of translucent polymer membranes ETFE. In the space of the atrium, transitional bridges are spanned, which serve as observation points. Atrium is a pedestrian area from which you can get to any of the objects of the building.\n\nThe MFZ will house a number of public spaces - for example, a planetarium in the shape of a ball or a seven-storey hall-transformer, which can take different configurations: from the classical parquet to the amphitheater.\n\n== Design ==\n\n=== Facilities ===\nLakhta Center will contain offices, a [[co-working]] center, a sports center, a children's science center, and a conference center. The project includes 1,500 square meters of indoor exhibition space. Part of the open area will be used to demonstrate art, installations and sculptures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/ru/press/gallery/presentation/?id=445|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044b {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> There will be a free public observation deck at the top of the skyscraper at a height of 357m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/objects/viewpoint/|title=Observation deck {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/08/19/122/|script-title=ru:\u0421\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0443\u044e \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0443 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u0446\u0438\u0444\u0440\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=2014-08-19|accessdate=2018-07-30|language=ru}}</ref> A Planetarium, which includes a 19-meter sparkling ball on the surface of which are 1223 curved triangular stainless steel sheets, polished to a shine. A very accurate projection of the starry sky is formed by a star machine (Japanese projector - Ohira Tech Megastar-IIA ). Larger objects, artificial aircraft, visual effects and much more are created by a projection system with a resolution of 8K at the meridian, which uses 10 Sony GTZ280 laser projectors. Five projectors illuminate the lower tier of the dome, four the top, and one forms an image at the [[zenith]]. Thus, a total resolution of 48 483 533 pixels is achieved.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/447764/ \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441! \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430]</ref>\n\n=== Features ===\n\n* The main entrance of Lakhta Center is designed to be an [[arch]]. The height of the arch is almost 24m while its length is 98m.\n* There will be 34 elevators in the tower, but not all of them will travel to the top floor. The mixed-use building will contain 62 elevators. Besides these elevators there will be special firefighter lifts constructed to be used in case of emergency. The total capacity of all elevators is up to 1,280 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nvspb.ru/stories/neboskreby-menyayut-soznanie-sociuma-52309|title=\"\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0451\u0431\u044b \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u044e\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0443\u043c\u0430\" {{!}} \u041d\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f|website=www.nvspb.ru|language=ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* Lakhta Center's foundation is going to be concreted continuously in round-the-clock mode. Constructors plan to pour 24,000 cubic metres in 48 hours. The volume of concrete to be poured under the mixed-use building near the tower is 48,000 cubic metres. This volume is large enough to be included in the [[Guinness Book of Records]].<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=447425 Construction director of Lakhta Center Elena Morozova: \"We will become record-holders due to the volume of concrete poured\"]</ref>\n* Around 400,000 cubic meters of concrete will be used for Lakhta Center's construction. During the first stage of foundation concreting 8,500 cubic meters of concrete will be used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dp.ru/a/2014/12/08/Beton_dlja_Lahta_Centra/|title=\u0412 \u0441\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0447\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0444\u0443\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"|website=www.dp.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* The area of glazing of the Tower totals 72,500 square meters as the area of the glazing for the complex in the whole makes up 130,000 square meters.<ref>[http://www.megapolis-online.ru/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440. 462 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0435\u043c \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f]</ref>\n* Lakhta Center is designed to a high safety standard, which allows it to stand on one core even if all ten supportive columns collapse. The core structure is up to the highest fire rating. The building is designed to be able to withstand a four-hour fire without any structural damage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.popmech.ru/technologies/48791-kak-stroitsya-lakhta-tsentr-v-sankt-peterburge/#full|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u00ab\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u00bb \u0432 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435|work=Popmech.ru|access-date=2018-07-30|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n* On December 31, 2018 [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qlwYShApM9U Green Christmas lights] were lit on the skyscraper, thus turning the building into the highest Christmas tree in Europe<ref>[https://forpost-sz.ru/a/2018-12-31/lakhta-centr-prevratili-v-samuyu-vysokuyu-yolku-evropy The tallest Christmas tree in Europe]</ref>\n* On June 28, 2019, an automatic weather station was installed at the highest point of the spire (462 meters), which monitors temperature, humidity, wind direction and speed.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/06/28/053/ From Lakhta Center will now monitor the weather. On the spire of the St. Petersburg skyscraper appeared weather station]</ref>\n* 2019 - the Lakhta center complex became the leader in the number of nominations for the Award of Excellence and Urban Habitat.<ref>[https://tallinnovation.com/program/projects-featured/ Award of Excellence Winners]</ref> It was a finalist in five categories: Best high-rise building of 400 meters and higher; Construction award; Award in the field of construction engineering; award in the field of geotechnical engineering; award for facade engineering.\n\n=== Innovations ===\nIn order to provide more effective fire-fighting, a HI-FOG water mist suppression system will be used. When the temperature exceeds 57&nbsp;\u00b0C, sprinklers creating a water mist will start working automatically. Along with the sprinklers, there will be drenchers which can be switched on manually or with remote control in order to create a water curtain in an emergency.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e \u041e\u0431 \u0438\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0432 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193513/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> Lakhta Center is also set to be the first skyscraper in St. Petersburg where an ice formation control system will be used. Heating of the glass at high floors will prevent ice accumulation and help maintain good visibility. The spire of the Tower will be made from metal gauze to prevent a layer of ice forming in winter.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e. \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440: \u043b\u0435\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043c] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193302/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> The consumption of material and energy resources will be decreased due to conversion of kinetic energy of the Center's workers and visitors' steps to electric energy.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.regnum.ru/news/realestate/1784199.html \"\u0417\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\" \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435: \u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u044f \u0448\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\"]</ref>\nDuring migration periods of birds special illumination will be used to light the tower.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2015/05/06_a_6668381.shtml Lakhta Center Skyscraper Continues to Surprise with its Technologies]</ref>\n\n=== Environmental technologies ===\nWhile designing Lakhta Center several \"green\" and energy-saving technologies were planned for further application. They are\n\n* Double facade. Usage of double glazing will help to increase the level of thermal insulation, which allowed the designers to reduce costs for heating and conditioning.\n* Usage of the excess heat generated by working technical equipment for the heating of premises.\n* Usage of equipment with reduced noise level along with noise suppressors, sound-proof curtain walls and [[floating floor]]s.\n* Usage of economical infrared radiators.\n* Usage of contactless sensors or [[motion detectors]] for economizing electric energy and water.\n* Mounting of the systems supporting the optimal level of temperature and humidity inside the building.\n* Smart waste disposal system which improves hygiene and reduces CO2 emissions. Also wastes are sorted, which is one of the essential principles of green construction. Waste disposal is required by 20 times less frequent than in a conventional system.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html Lakhta Center: 462 meters above the sea level] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208073228/http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html |date=8 February 2017 }}</ref>\n* Constructing of the ice storages which will accumulate up to 1000 tons of ice at night for air conditioning during the daytime. It will help to reduce the differences in the usage of electricity during the night and day periods. It also allows reducing expenditures on electric power on the account of the differences in tariffs for day and night usage of electricity. As the cooling of the building is to be made using accumulative ice generators it will be possible to save on electricity expenditures up to 13 thousand rubles a day.\n* In support to the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] and FLAP's (Fatal Light Awareness Program) \"Bird - Friendly Building Program\", Lakhta Center's illumination will be designed so to make the building bird-safe especially in the periods of migration of birds (autumn, winter). The system of the illumination intensity and color change is under development at the moment.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami Lakhta Center is eager to make friends with birds] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428052153/http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami |date=28 April 2017 }}</ref>\n* Due to the peculiarities of the highly humid and windy climate in the North Western region of Russia the possibility of icing up of buildings is relatively high. In order to prevent complete icing up of the spire of the Lakhta Center's tower engineers changed glassing to the metal gauze.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=544242&sec=1671 \u0421\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0437\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044f\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0434\u043e 13 \u0442\u044b\u0441. \u0440\u0443\u0431. \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n* In order to provide Lakhta Center and adjoining areas with electricity without making any extra burden on existing infrastructure a new standalone power substation \"Nevskaya guba\" will be constructed.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://asninfo.ru/news/v-lahte-postroyat-podstanciyu-nevskaya-guba \"Nevskaya guba\" power substation will be built in Lakhta]</ref>\n\nAll in all, while constructing Lakhta Center approximately 100 [[innovation]]s are to be used. It lets increase the indexes of energy saving by 40% compared to the buildings where standard technologies are in use.\n\nIn experts' opinion, period of recoupment of using green and energy-saving technologies in Lakhta Center may be at about 20 years though Lakhta Center's Projection department's specialists think that this figure is a bit overestimated.\n\n===Transportation development===\nLakhta Center's construction raises a problem of transportation development because of the expected growth of the traffic flow in the region. Two traffic circles are to be built near Lakhta Center. These will become part of the \u041c32\u0410 highway in the future.<ref>[http://www.spbdnevnik.ru/news/2014-07-10/dva-razvorotnykh-koltsa-poyavyatsya-v-primorskom-rayone/]</ref>\nA light rail service from [[Finland Railway Station]] and a new tram line from [[Primorskaya (Saint Petersburg Metro)|Primorskaya underground station]] will be built to serve Lakhta Center. Plans are ongoing to build a new underground station with the working title of \"Lakhta\".<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/transport/ Transport Infrastructure Development]</ref> Bicycle lanes near Lakhta Center with 90 parking places for bicycles are also planned.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/07/15/138/ \u0412 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u044f\u0437\u043a\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u044b \u041c-32 \u0438 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0448\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043a\u0443]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f |access-date=18 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413143303/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |archive-date=13 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\nAs the [[Historic Centre of Saint Petersburg and Related Groups of Monuments|historical center of St. Petersburg]] has become a [[World Heritage Site]] since 1990; The [[World Heritage Committee]] opposed the construction of the 400-metre tower of [[Okhta Center]] as it would affect the cityscape of historic Saint Petersburg.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/612 UNESCO welcomes backing by President of Russian Federation for the preservation of St Petersburg]</ref> In December 2006 [[UNESCO]] World Heritage Centre Director Francesco Bandarin reminded Russia about its obligations to preserve it and expressed concern over the project.<ref>[http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article.shtml?2006/12/05/117081 UNESCO is worried] by Elena Ragozina, [[Vedomosti]] #229 (1756), 5 December 2006 (in Russian).</ref> In 2007, the [[World Monuments Fund]] placed the historic skyline of St. Petersburg on its 2008 Watch List of 100 Most Endangered Sites due to the potential construction of the building, and in 2009 reported that the tower \"would damage the image of Russia.\"<ref name=BBCUNESCO>{{Cite news |title=Russian tower plans cause alarm |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8272401.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=2009-09-23 |accessdate=2009-10-12}}</ref> During the 36 session of the World Heritage Committee of UNESCO held in Saint Petersburg in 2012 it was stated that a large area of Saint-Petersburg falls within preservation and buffer zones provided for UNESCO World Heritage Sites. That is why it is good for the city that the Okhta Center, which had been planned by Gazprom in front of Smolny Cathedral was moved to Lakhta.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/sessions/36COM 36th session of the Committee of the World Heritage Committee]</ref> Eleonora Mitrofanova, Permanent Representative of the Russian Federation to UNESCO noticed that the approved construction project for Lakhta Center is located far from the buffer zone and the historical center, so in theory Gazprom is not even obliged to ask UNESCO. However, the government authorities will definitely have consultations for the project with UNESCO. Now we are working to clarify the boundaries of the World Heritage zone and the boundaries of the buffer zone.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=326845&sec=1671 \u0412\u044b\u0441\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0442 \u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0443 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0420\u0424 \u0432 \u042e\u041d\u0415\u0421\u041a\u041e]</ref>\n\nThe project being moved to Lakhta didn't stop the discussions. On 11 April 2012, ex-governor of St. Petersburg and now Federation Council chairwoman Valentina Matvienko said to journalists that the \"Lakhta center could become a new symbol of the city and attract the businessmen from all over the world to St. Petersburg.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo.msk.ru/programs/sorokina/876139-echo/ |title=\"In the light circle\", the interview with Ms.Matvienko at \"Echo Moskvy\" |publisher=Echo.msk.ru |date= |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\nDuring his visit to Russia in 2011 the Chairman of the [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]] Professor Sang-Dae Kim was treated to a presentation of a project of Lakhta Center. Professor Kim commented on the \"modern shape\" of the proposed Lakhta Center, which according to him had \"nothing in common with ordinary boxes\".<ref>[http://www.ctbuh.org/Events/ToursVisits/ProfKimVisitstoSEAsiaRussia/ProfKimvisitRussia/tabid/2778/language/en-US/Default.aspx CTBUH Meeting: Russia]</ref> He also stated that something new ought to be created, which can be shown to new generations in 200\u2013300 years as for them what is created nowadays will be the same history as the architecture of the 18-19th centuries for us today. Professor also noticed that the project reminds him of an oriental concept [[Yin Yang]]: on the one hand, the historic part of the city with horizontal buildings and water, and on the other hand, a vertical which will add additional charm to the city. Lakhta Center combines an interesting form and modern technologies, so up to Mr. Kim, with the lapse of time the Center can become a new symbol of Saint Petersburg.<ref>[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2011/09/07_a_3759709.shtml Without skyscrapers Russia is the Kremlin and the Red Army]</ref>\n\nOn 16 May 2012, St. Petersburg governor Georgiy Poltavchenko emphasized in his annual report for House of Assembly the necessity of building a new \"city\" in St. Petersburg. According to Mr Poltavchenko, there are three appropriate districts for that: Lakhta center, Pulkovo and [[aggradation|aggradated]] territories near Waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/05/15/056/ |title=Poltavchenko: Petersburg needs a new business center and town-planning dictation |publisher=Fontanka.ru |date=2012-05-15 |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Construction gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Site's view prior to construction.jpg|Site's view prior to construction, July 2012.\nFile:Aerial view of the construction site of Lakhta Center in Saint Petersburg, November 2014.jpg|Panoramic view of the construction site, November 2014.\nFile:Piling process.jpg|Piling process\nFile:Construction of the foundation under the Tower.jpg|Construction of the foundation under the Tower\nFile:Foundations of the Tower and mixed-use building are ready.jpg|Foundations of the tower and mixed-use building are ready\nFile:Lakhta Center.jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2015\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Feb, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0438\u044e\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Jul, 2016\nFile:Lakhta_Center_Oktober_2016.jpg|The state of the construction as of October, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Skyscraper at the end of 2016. Height is 245 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044c 2017).jpg|Skyscraper in April 2017. Height is 310 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u0439 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2017. Height is 323 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in September 2017. Height is 365 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440, \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430.jpg|Lakhta Center in January 2018. Installation of the spire, height of about 450 meters\nFile:Lakhta Center orig.jpg|Skyscraper at the end of February 2018. Installation of the spire is complete, glazing of the tower and spire continues.\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u044f\u043a).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2018.\nFile:Das Lachta Zentr- \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 2H1A5980WI.jpg| June 2018\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2018).jpg|Lakhta Center in November 2018\nFile:2-\u044f \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u044c \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Construction of the 2nd stage (November 2018)\nFile:Lakhta Center at night in april 2019.jpg|April 2019\nFile:\u041d\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u044b \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Skyscraper lighting\nFile:Lakhta Center, spire.jpg|The spire of the skyscraper (General view).\nFile:\u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445 \u0448\u043f\u0438\u043b\u044f \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|The top of the spire. Floodlight projectors are integrated in it\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Russia]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Europe]]\n* [[List of twisted buildings]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/ Official site of Lakhta Center]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070401024640/http://www.ohta-center.ru/ Official Site of the Okhta Center project]\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/future/view/ Visual Analysis projecting the appearance of the tower at the Lakhta site, from various points in St. Petersburg]\n* [https://ru-ru.facebook.com/lakhtacenter.ru/ Official social media page]\n\n{{Supertall skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Saint Petersburg culture]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Architecture of Russia]]\n[[Category:Gazprom]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Russia]]\n[[Category:Twisted buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}{{Infobox building\n| name = Lakhta Center\n| native_name = \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\n| native_name_lang = ru\n| former_names = Gazprom Tower, [[Okhta Center]]\n| alternate_names = \n| status = {{Color|green|Completed}}\n| image = Saint Petersburg Lakhta center 06.jpg\n| image_alt = \n| image_size = 280px\n| caption = July 2018\n| location = [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]], [[Saint Petersburg]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|59|59|13.7|N|30|10|37.3|E|region:RU|display=inline,title}}\n| address = \n| location_town = \n| location_country = Russia\n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date = 2012\n| completion_date = 2019\n| opened_date = \n| inauguration_date = \n| demolition_date = \n| destruction_date = \n| architect = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT\n| landlord = \n| owner = [[Gazprom Neft]]\n| cost = US$1.77 billion<ref>[https://realty.rbc.ru/news/5bed46bd9a794728d6707196]</ref>\n| floor_area = \n| top_floor = \n| floor_count = 87\n| awards = \n| parking = \n| embedded = \n| references = \n| highest_region = \n| highest_reflabel = \n| highest_prev = \n| highest_start = \n| highest_end = \n| highest_next = \n| map_type = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| altitude = \n| building_type = \n| architectural_style = \n| structural_system = \n| current_tenants = \n| renovation_date = \n| height = {{convert|462|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| architectural = \n| tip = \n| antenna_spire = \n| roof = \n| observatory = \n| other_dimensions = \n| elevator_count = 40<ref>[https://habr.com/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371087/ Elevators in a skyscraper]</ref>\n| architecture_firm = RMJM (until 2011), GORPROJECT<ref>[https://www.houseandgarden.co.uk/article/europes-tallest-skyscraper-lakhta-centre Europe's tallest skyscraper is nearing completion in St. Petersburg]</ref>\n| main_contractor = [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]\n| designations = \n| url = \n}}\nThe '''Lakhta Center''' ({{Lang-rus|\u041b\u0430\u0301\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0442\u0440|r=Lakhta tsentr}}) is an 87-story [[skyscraper]] built in the outskirts of [[Lakhta, Saint Petersburg|Lakhta]] in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]]. Standing {{convert|462|m|ft}} tall, the Lakhta Center is the [[List of tallest buildings in Russia|tallest building in Russia]], the [[List of tallest buildings in Europe|tallest building in Europe]], and the [[List of tallest buildings|16th-tallest building in the world]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title=Lakhta Center - The Skyscraper Center|website=skyscrapercenter.com|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/ru/about/project/ |title=Lakhta Center Website, \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043f\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proektvlahte.ru/uploaded/file_list/ROSAVIA706(19.07.2011).pdf |title=Federal Air Transport Agency Authorization |date=2011-07-19 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://skyscrapercenter.com/st.-petersburg/lakhta-center/12575/|title= Lakhta Center|accessdate= 22 January 2014|work= The Skyscraper Center|publisher= [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]]}}</ref> The Lakhta Center is also the second-tallest structure in Russia and Europe, behind [[Ostankino Tower]] in [[Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|title=Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat, '100 Future tallest buildings in the world'|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723110141/http://skyscrapercenter.com/List/future-tallest-100-buildings|archivedate=2012-07-23|url-status=dead|accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of Lakhta Center started on 30 October 2012; it was topped out on 29 January 2018.<ref name=\"installation\" >[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1295 The installation of the spire of the Lakhta Center], Press release of 29 January 2018.</ref> The Lakhta Center surpassed Vostok Tower of the [[Federation Tower|Federation Towers]] in Moscow as the tallest building in Russia and Europe on 5 October 2017. The center is designed for large-scale [[mixed-use development]], consisting of public facilities and offices.  The building was designed by [[RMJM]]. The project was then continued by GORPROJECT (2011-2017) based on the RMJM Concept (2011) under the main contractor, [[R\u00f6nesans Holding]]. The Lakhta Center is intended to become the new headquarters of Russian energy company [[Gazprom]].\n\nOn December 24, 2018, Lakhta Center was certified according to the criteria of ecological efficiency at [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Platinum<ref>[https://www.usgbc.org/projects/lakhta-centertower Lakhta Center-Tower]</ref> \u2013 it is one of the five most eco-friendly skyscrapers in the world.<ref>[https://realty.ria.ru/20191220/1562593482.html The Chronicles of the stone of greens, as buildings become energy efficient]</ref> The concrete pouring of the bottom slab of Lakhta Center's foundation was registered by [[Guinness World Records]] as the largest continuous concrete pour; 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were used, which is approximately 3,000 cubic meters more than in the previous record registered at [[Wilshire Grand Tower]].<ref>[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/largest-continuous-concrete-pour/ Largest Continuous Concrete Pour]</ref> The tower's [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain wall]] is also the world\u2019s largest cold-bent facade by area.\n\nThe opening date of the complex will be determined after the completion of finishing and landscaping. The improvement of the embankments is planned to be completed at the end of 2020.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2019/08/08/Vozle_Lahti-centra_pojav Near the \"Lakhta center\" will be a public space with \" glass wings\"]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n=== Planning ===\n\nOn, 26 January 2012, it became known that [[Gazprom]] was planning to build a new harbor for yachts near Lakhta Center and Krestovsky Island. A new company for managing these sea assets was to be created.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/01/26/157/#comments \u0413\u0430\u0437\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0438\u0437 \"\u041b\u0435\u043d\u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u043e\" \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u044f\u0445\u0442]</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2012, it was announced that a new metro station was to be constructed near Lakhta Center. This metro station's building was included in the City development plan of [[Leningrad]] in 1980 but only with the construction of the Lakhta Center did it again enter the agenda. The plan of the metro station's construction was to be finalized by the end of 2012.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/03/16/074/ \u0412\u044b\u0445\u043e\u0434 \u0438\u0437 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0413\u0418\u0411\u0414\u0414 16.03.2012 13:26]</ref>\n\nOn 17 August 2012 the permit for construction of the first stage of Lakhta Center, which included a skyscraper and stylobate, was obtained.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/08/20/114/ \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e]</ref>\nOn 31 August 2012, a public hearing on the topic of the layout and surveying of the site of the Lakhta Center was held in the administration of the Primorsky district of Saint Petersburg. Objects planned for placing in the area of construction, scheme of communications and transportation infrastructure were presented to the public.<ref>[http://izvestia.ru/news/534256 \u041d\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433]</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\nApproximately 3000 people will be employed in the construction, mostly from professions relating to design and construction. After construction, a few thousand workers of different occupations were expected to be employed in the complex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2235582|title=\"\u0421\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u043c\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432\"|date=2013-07-17|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref>\n\nGeodesic, ecologic and soil investigations and design documentation for the project were prepared by GORPROJECT (Russia), NIIOSP (Russia), Petrochim-technologiya LLC (Russia) and Trest GRII JSC (Russia). In planning and executing works at the underground cycle, piling and producing construction materials such companies as [[Arabtec]] (UAE), [[Bauer Group]] (Germany), Geostroy CJSC (Russia), Inforsproekt CJSC (Russia) and Renaissance Construction (Turkey) take part. Verification calculations, working documentation development, optimisation of processes and technical supervision are performed by [[Arup Group Limited]] (Great Britain), [[Samsung C&T]] (Korea) and [[Lend Lease Project Management & Construction]] (Great Britain). Project management is being done by [[AECOM]] (USA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/|title=Key Contractors|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n[http://www.exclusivadesign.com Exclusiva Design] (Italy) is key contractor for the interior design of public spaces.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/status/contractors/exclusiva/ Exclusiva Design]</ref><ref>[http://www.exclusivadesign.com/lakhta-center-exclusiva-wins-the-bid-to-design-the-public-spaces/?lang=en/ Lakhta Center: Exclusiva Design wins the Bid to Design the Public Spaces]</ref> German company Josef Gartner is in charge for the glazing of the skyscraper.<ref>[https://www.dp.ru/a/2015/09/16/Nemeckaja_Gartner_otkroet/ \u041d\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f Gartner \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043a\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref> Glazed facades of Entrance Arch as well as parts of Multi-functional building are done by [[Waagner-Biro]].\n\nOn 30 October 2012 the zero cycle works started. Zero cycle consists of the pit excavation, installation of the disk system, piling under the tower, multifunctional building and stylobate and construction of the foundation itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/status/current/|title= Lakhta Center. Project status|accessdate=2014-08-09}}</ref>\n\n22 April 2014 the main potential general contractor for the construction of Lakhta Center was selected. It was Turkish Renaissance Construction company.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/news/?id=237 Potential general constructor selected]</ref> 22 May 2014 the contract for the construction of the foundation of one of the buildings in Lakhta Center was finally signed.\n\n<div>Lakhta Center Construction Time Schedule:</div>\n\n* March 2013 \u2013 zero cycle works are in process. Piles are being installed. According to the schedule of construction a [[diaphragm wall]] is to be completed by the end of April while piling works will continue until 15 August 2013.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=390991 \u0418\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u041e\u0414\u0426 \"\u041e\u0445\u0442\u0430\" \u0410.\u0411\u043e\u0431\u043a\u043e\u0432: \"\u0412 \u201e\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\u201c \u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0435\u0439\"]</ref>\n* July 2013 \u2013 mounting of the 264 piles under the box-type foundation has been finished. Excavation of the foundation pit is in progress.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u043e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413160601/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php |date=13 April 2015 }}</ref>\n* September 2013 \u2013 total area of the site is announced to be increased from 330 to 400 thousand square meters due to a 700 parking space expansion to the planned parking spaces.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |title=\u0421\u0422\u0420\u041e\u0418\u0422\u0415\u041b\u042c\u0421\u0422\u0412\u041e \u041d\u0423\u041b\u0415\u0412\u041e\u0413\u041e \u0426\u0418\u041a\u041b\u0410 \"\u041b\u0410\u0425\u0422\u0410 \u0426\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0420\u0410\" \u041e\u0426\u0415\u041d\u0418\u041b\u0418 \u0412 $100 \u041c\u041b\u041d |access-date=26 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128003246/http://restate.ru/material/152481.html |archive-date=28 January 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* October 2013 \u2013 construction of box-type foundation has been started. According to the plan this part of the work is to be finished in 2014.<ref>[http://advis.ru/php/view_news.php?id=763315EE-9CD4-6040-80D4-FA160CE9C441 \u0420\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u044b \u043d\u0443\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0435 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\".]</ref>\n\n* December 2013 \u2013 mounting of the concrete disks to the [[diaphragm wall]] has started. Disks are to provide the diaphragm wall with more resistance to outside ground pressure.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |title=\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431 \u0443 \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430. |access-date=10 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317210545/http://rcmm.ru/content/topics/428.html |archive-date=17 March 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* April 2014 \u2013 construction of foundation pit for the skyscraper is over.<ref>[http://karpovka.net/2014/04/02/137579/ \u0413\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"]</ref>\n* June 2014 \u2013 piling is completed. 264 piles were mounted for the tower of Lakhta Center, 848 piles were mounted for the mixed-use building and entrance arch and 968 piles were mounted for the stylobate (undergroung parking). All in all 2080 piles were dug in.<ref>[http://proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=892 All 2080 Piles in Lakhta Center Foundation]</ref>\n* September 2014 \u2013 excavation of the foundation pit for the mixed-use building has been finished. Foundation concreting has started.\n* February and March 2015 \u2013 the pouring of the bottom slab of the skyscraper's box shaped foundation over. 19,624 cubic meters of concrete were cast in the foundation.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.fontanka.ru/2015/03/02/169/ Alexey Miller: First floors of the skyscraper in Lakhta will appear this year]</ref>\n* June 2015 \u2013 construction of the underground floors has finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 pouring of the 2m thick upper box foundation slab has been completed, which means that all works below zero elevation are finished.\n* September 2015 \u2013 the construction of the first floors of the tower core is underway.<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/article/?id=1087 Pouring of the Upper Slab of the Lakhta Center Tower Foundation]</ref>\n* January 2016 \u2013 construction of the succeeding ten floors of the tower; works on stylobate complex.\n* April 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 22-26. Installation of the metal farm in the 18-22nd floors of the tower.\n* May 2016 \u2013 glazing of the facade of the Tower has started.\n* September 2016 \u2013 construction of the tower core at floors 46-50.<ref>[https://www.liebherr.com/en/deu/latest-news/news-press-releases/detail/liebherr-tower-cranes-in-action-erecting-the-highest-building-in-europe.html?news.type=press/ Liebherr tower cranes in action erecting the highest building in Europe]</ref>\n* December 2016 \u2013 installation of facade at floors 16-18; construction of the tower core at floors 57-61 \n* February 2017 \u2013 Lahkta Center's tower reaches height of 260 metres; floors 61-64 are under construction.\n* April 2017 -  height exceeds 300 meters, making Lakhta Center a [[supertall]] building (international classification), work is being done on the 67 floor.\n* May 2017 - the skyscraper reached the height 327,6 meters, working on the 78th floor.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2017/05/13/034/ Lakhta Center outgrew the tower]</ref>\n* August 2017 - Installation of the spire starts at 83 floors.\n* 5 October 2017 - Lakhta center became the tallest building in Europe when it reached a height of 374 meters.<ref>[http://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1280 European altitude record broken]</ref><ref>[http://www.euronews.com/2017/10/06/russian-skyscraper-becomes-europe-s-tallest-building# Russian skyscraper \u2018becomes Europe\u2019s tallest building]</ref>\n* 29 January 2018 - the height of Lakhta center project reached a height of 462 meters, the assembly of structures of the spire is completed. The glazing of the tower continues at floor 70.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6Y-0SYU5sJU Lakhta Center reached the design height]</ref>\n* 20 June 2018 - The last tower crane was removed. The developers were motivated to finish work requiring tower cranes before the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] semi finals in order to make the building look architecturally complete. <ref>{{cite web |title=The last tower crane has been removed at the Lakhta Center construction site |url=https://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1311 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=English |date=20 June 2018}}</ref>\n* On 27 June 2018, the initial commissioning of the building was carried out. Technical documentation, building plan and technical passport were prepared.<ref>[https://www.archdaily.com/898132/europes-tallest-skyscraper-approaches-completion-in-st-petersburg Europe's Tallest Skyscraper Approaches Completion in St Petersburg]</ref>\n* On 16 October 2018, Lakhta Center MFC JSC received authorization for commissioning of the facility. The relevant document was officially published by the State Construction Supervision and Inspection Service of Saint Petersburg, Russia. There is about a year to go until the opening of Lakhta Center Multifunctional Complex, its dominant being the tallest skyscraper of Europe.<ref>[https://lakhta.center/en/article/?id=1321 Lakhta Center Officially Commissioned]</ref>\n\nNext to the already commissioned Lakhta Center, construction continues. To the four objects of the complex (tower, multi-purpose building, arch, stylobate) will be added one more. According to official documents, it takes place under the name \"Complex of buildings and structures\", or simply KZS.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/03/28/111/ \"Complex of buildings and structures\"]</ref>\n\nThe complex of buildings and structures is a single building consisting of two buildings connected by a courtyard. The authors of the project suggest that it will not only strengthen the office function of the Lakhta Center, but also complete the formation of the architectural ensemble, balancing the skyscraper in the horizontal.<ref>[https://www.the-village.ru/village/city/news-city/345989-kzs-lahta \"Complex of buildings and structures\". It will be built at the \"Lakhta center\" in 2021]</ref> The total area of the Lakhta center is 400 000 m\u00b2. With the addition of the KZS, the total area of the complex is 570 000 m\u00b2.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=924846&sec=1679 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442 Renaissance Construction]</ref>\n\n== Multi-functional building ==\nMulti-functional building (MFZ) - an object divided into two buildings - North and South, which are United by a common Foundation, stylobate and roof. The building resembles a boomerang. It has a variable number of storeys with a height difference from 7 to 17 floors, with the peak height being a little more than 80 meters. The building is approximately 300 meters long.  Feature - negative angle of the end facades due to the removal of the console on 25 m. Facades - glass, with a total area of more than 60 thousand m2.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/371535/ Horizontal versus vertical. Or for? Why Lakhta Center \"recumbent\" dominant]</ref>\n\nConstructive scheme of the building - frame. More than 24 thousand tons of metal structures were used for the construction of this facility.\n\nThe main load-bearing elements are 4 reinforced concrete cores which perceive horizontal and vertical loadings, transferring them to the base executed in the form of the plate grillage leaning against piles. Between the Southern and Northern buildings of the MFZ along the entire height of the atrium, with a roof of translucent polymer membranes ETFE. In the space of the atrium, transitional bridges are spanned, which serve as observation points. Atrium is a pedestrian area from which you can get to any of the objects of the building.\n\nThe MFZ will house a number of public spaces - for example, a planetarium in the shape of a ball or a seven-storey hall-transformer, which can take different configurations: from the classical parquet to the amphitheater.\n\n== Design ==\n\n=== Facilities ===\nLakhta Center will contain offices, a [[co-working]] center, a sports center, a children's science center, and a conference center. The project includes 1,500 square meters of indoor exhibition space. Part of the open area will be used to demonstrate art, installations and sculptures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/ru/press/gallery/presentation/?id=445|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044b {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> There will be a free public observation deck at the top of the skyscraper at a height of 357m.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/objects/viewpoint/|title=Observation deck {{!}} \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 \u2013 \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0444\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430|website=www.proektvlahte.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/08/19/122/|script-title=ru:\u0421\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0443\u044e \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0443 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u0446\u0438\u0444\u0440\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=2014-08-19|accessdate=2018-07-30|language=ru}}</ref> A Planetarium, which includes a 19-meter sparkling ball on the surface of which are 1223 curved triangular stainless steel sheets, polished to a shine. A very accurate projection of the starry sky is formed by a star machine (Japanese projector - Ohira Tech Megastar-IIA ). Larger objects, artificial aircraft, visual effects and much more are created by a projection system with a resolution of 8K at the meridian, which uses 10 Sony GTZ280 laser projectors. Five projectors illuminate the lower tier of the dome, four the top, and one forms an image at the [[zenith]]. Thus, a total resolution of 48 483 533 pixels is achieved.<ref>[https://habr.com/ru/company/lakhtacenter/blog/447764/ \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043a\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0441! \u041a\u0430\u043a \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430]</ref>\n\n=== Features ===\n\n* The main entrance of Lakhta Center is designed to be an [[arch]]. The height of the arch is almost 24m while its length is 98m.\n* There will be 34 elevators in the tower, but not all of them will travel to the top floor. The mixed-use building will contain 62 elevators. Besides these elevators there will be special firefighter lifts constructed to be used in case of emergency. The total capacity of all elevators is up to 1,280 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nvspb.ru/stories/neboskreby-menyayut-soznanie-sociuma-52309|title=\"\u041d\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0451\u0431\u044b \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u044e\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u043e\u0446\u0438\u0443\u043c\u0430\" {{!}} \u041d\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f|website=www.nvspb.ru|language=ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* Lakhta Center's foundation is going to be concreted continuously in round-the-clock mode. Constructors plan to pour 24,000 cubic metres in 48 hours. The volume of concrete to be poured under the mixed-use building near the tower is 48,000 cubic metres. This volume is large enough to be included in the [[Guinness Book of Records]].<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/exclusives.asp?id=447425 Construction director of Lakhta Center Elena Morozova: \"We will become record-holders due to the volume of concrete poured\"]</ref>\n* Around 400,000 cubic meters of concrete will be used for Lakhta Center's construction. During the first stage of foundation concreting 8,500 cubic meters of concrete will be used.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dp.ru/a/2014/12/08/Beton_dlja_Lahta_Centra/|title=\u0412 \u0441\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0447\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0444\u0443\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\"|website=www.dp.ru|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>\n* The area of glazing of the Tower totals 72,500 square meters as the area of the glazing for the complex in the whole makes up 130,000 square meters.<ref>[http://www.megapolis-online.ru/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440. 462 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0435\u043c \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f]</ref>\n* Lakhta Center is designed to a high safety standard, which allows it to stand on one core even if all ten supportive columns collapse. The core structure is up to the highest fire rating. The building is designed to be able to withstand a four-hour fire without any structural damage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.popmech.ru/technologies/48791-kak-stroitsya-lakhta-tsentr-v-sankt-peterburge/#full|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u00ab\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u00bb \u0432 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442-\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435|work=Popmech.ru|access-date=2018-07-30|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n* On December 31, 2018 [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qlwYShApM9U Green Christmas lights] were lit on the skyscraper, thus turning the building into the highest Christmas tree in Europe<ref>[https://forpost-sz.ru/a/2018-12-31/lakhta-centr-prevratili-v-samuyu-vysokuyu-yolku-evropy The tallest Christmas tree in Europe]</ref>\n* On June 28, 2019, an automatic weather station was installed at the highest point of the spire (462 meters), which monitors temperature, humidity, wind direction and speed.<ref>[https://www.fontanka.ru/2019/06/28/053/ From Lakhta Center will now monitor the weather. On the spire of the St. Petersburg skyscraper appeared weather station]</ref>\n* 2019 - the Lakhta center complex became the leader in the number of nominations for the Award of Excellence and Urban Habitat.<ref>[https://tallinnovation.com/program/projects-featured/ Award of Excellence Winners]</ref> It was a finalist in five categories: Best high-rise building of 400 meters and higher; Construction award; Award in the field of construction engineering; award in the field of geotechnical engineering; award for facade engineering.\n\n=== Innovations ===\nIn order to provide more effective fire-fighting, a HI-FOG water mist suppression system will be used. When the temperature exceeds 57&nbsp;\u00b0C, sprinklers creating a water mist will start working automatically. Along with the sprinklers, there will be drenchers which could be switched on manually or by the means of remote control in order to create a water curtain in an emergency.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e \u041e\u0431 \u0438\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0432 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0435\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193513/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/novosti-o-lahta-centre.php#101 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> Lakhta Center is also set to be the first skyscraper in St. Petersburg where an ice formation control system will be used. Heating of the glass at high floors will prevent ice accumulation and help maintain good visibility. The spire of the Tower will be made from metal gauze to prevent a layer of ice forming in winter.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 \u041c\u041e \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0438\u043d\u043e. \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440: \u043b\u0435\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043c] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170427193302/http://www.old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=6 |date=27 April 2017 }}</ref> The consumption of material and energy resources will be decreased due to conversion of kinetic energy of the Center's workers and visitors' steps to electric energy.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.regnum.ru/news/realestate/1784199.html \"\u0417\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\" \u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435: \u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u044f \u0448\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\"]</ref>\nDuring migration periods of birds special illumination will be used to light the tower.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2015/05/06_a_6668381.shtml Lakhta Center Skyscraper Continues to Surprise with its Technologies]</ref>\n\n=== Environmental technologies ===\nWhile designing Lakhta Center several \"green\" and energy-saving technologies were planned for further application. They are\n\n* Double facade. Usage of double glazing will help to increase the level of thermal insulation, which allowed the designers to reduce costs for heating and conditioning.\n* Usage of the excess heat generated by working technical equipment for the heating of premises.\n* Usage of equipment with reduced noise level along with noise suppressors, sound-proof curtain walls and [[floating floor]]s.\n* Usage of economical infrared radiators.\n* Usage of contactless sensors or [[motion detectors]] for economizing electric energy and water.\n* Mounting of the systems supporting the optimal level of temperature and humidity inside the building.\n* Smart waste disposal system which improves hygiene and reduces CO2 emissions. Also wastes are sorted, which is one of the essential principles of green construction. Waste disposal is required by 20 times less frequent than in a conventional system.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html Lakhta Center: 462 meters above the sea level] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208073228/http://www.megapolis-online.com/articles/intervyu/lahta-centr-462-metra-nad-urovnem-morya-1.html |date=8 February 2017 }}</ref>\n* Constructing of the ice storages which will accumulate up to 1000 tons of ice at night for air conditioning during the daytime. It will help to reduce the differences in the usage of electricity during the night and day periods. It also allows reducing expenditures on electric power on the account of the differences in tariffs for day and night usage of electricity. As the cooling of the building is to be made using accumulative ice generators it will be possible to save on electricity expenditures up to 13 thousand rubles a day.\n* In support to the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] and FLAP's (Fatal Light Awareness Program) \"Bird - Friendly Building Program\", Lakhta Center's illumination will be designed so to make the building bird-safe especially in the periods of migration of birds (autumn, winter). The system of the illumination intensity and color change is under development at the moment.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami Lakhta Center is eager to make friends with birds] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428052153/http://old.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/news/?page=post&blog=news-lahta-center&post_id=lakhta-tsentr-stremitsya-podruzhitsya-s-ptitsami |date=28 April 2017 }}</ref>\n* Due to the peculiarities of the highly humid and windy climate in the North Western region of Russia the possibility of icing up of buildings is relatively high. In order to prevent complete icing up of the spire of the Lakhta Center's tower engineers changed glassing to the metal gauze.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=544242&sec=1671 \u0421\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0437\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044f\u0442 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0443\" \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0434\u043e 13 \u0442\u044b\u0441. \u0440\u0443\u0431. \u0432 \u0441\u0443\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u044d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u043e\u044d\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0438]</ref>\n* In order to provide Lakhta Center and adjoining areas with electricity without making any extra burden on existing infrastructure a new standalone power substation \"Nevskaya guba\" will be constructed.<ref>{{in lang|ru}}[http://asninfo.ru/news/v-lahte-postroyat-podstanciyu-nevskaya-guba \"Nevskaya guba\" power substation will be built in Lakhta]</ref>\n\nAll in all, while constructing Lakhta Center approximately 100 [[innovation]]s are to be used. It lets increase the indexes of energy saving by 40% compared to the buildings where standard technologies are in use.\n\nIn experts' opinion, period of recoupment of using green and energy-saving technologies in Lakhta Center may be at about 20 years though Lakhta Center's Projection department's specialists think that this figure is a bit overestimated.\n\n===Transportation development===\nLakhta Center's construction raises a problem of transportation development because of the expected growth of the traffic flow in the region. Two traffic circles are to be built near Lakhta Center. These will become part of the \u041c32\u0410 highway in the future.<ref>[http://www.spbdnevnik.ru/news/2014-07-10/dva-razvorotnykh-koltsa-poyavyatsya-v-primorskom-rayone/]</ref>\nA light rail service from [[Finland Railway Station]] and a new tram line from [[Primorskaya (Saint Petersburg Metro)|Primorskaya underground station]] will be built to serve Lakhta Center. Plans are ongoing to build a new underground station with the working title of \"Lakhta\".<ref>[http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/about/transport/ Transport Infrastructure Development]</ref> Bicycle lanes near Lakhta Center with 90 parking places for bicycles are also planned.<ref>[http://www.fontanka.ru/2014/07/15/138/ \u0412 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u044f\u0437\u043a\u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0441\u044b \u041c-32 \u0438 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0448\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043a\u0443]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f |access-date=18 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413143303/http://lahta-olgino.ru/lahta-center/obshchestvennye-slushaniya-.php |archive-date=13 April 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\nAs the [[Historic Centre of Saint Petersburg and Related Groups of Monuments|historical center of St. Petersburg]] has become a [[World Heritage Site]] since 1990; The [[World Heritage Committee]] opposed the construction of the 400-metre tower of [[Okhta Center]] as it would affect the cityscape of historic Saint Petersburg.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/612 UNESCO welcomes backing by President of Russian Federation for the preservation of St Petersburg]</ref> In December 2006 [[UNESCO]] World Heritage Centre Director Francesco Bandarin reminded Russia about its obligations to preserve it and expressed concern over the project.<ref>[http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article.shtml?2006/12/05/117081 UNESCO is worried] by Elena Ragozina, [[Vedomosti]] #229 (1756), 5 December 2006 (in Russian).</ref> In 2007, the [[World Monuments Fund]] placed the historic skyline of St. Petersburg on its 2008 Watch List of 100 Most Endangered Sites due to the potential construction of the building, and in 2009 reported that the tower \"would damage the image of Russia.\"<ref name=BBCUNESCO>{{Cite news |title=Russian tower plans cause alarm |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8272401.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=2009-09-23 |accessdate=2009-10-12}}</ref> During the 36 session of the World Heritage Committee of UNESCO held in Saint Petersburg in 2012 it was stated that a large area of Saint-Petersburg falls within preservation and buffer zones provided for UNESCO World Heritage Sites. That is why it is good for the city that the Okhta Center, which had been planned by Gazprom in front of Smolny Cathedral was moved to Lakhta.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/sessions/36COM 36th session of the Committee of the World Heritage Committee]</ref> Eleonora Mitrofanova, Permanent Representative of the Russian Federation to UNESCO noticed that the approved construction project for Lakhta Center is located far from the buffer zone and the historical center, so in theory Gazprom is not even obliged to ask UNESCO. However, the government authorities will definitely have consultations for the project with UNESCO. Now we are working to clarify the boundaries of the World Heritage zone and the boundaries of the buffer zone.<ref>[http://www.interfax-russia.ru/NorthWest/news.asp?id=326845&sec=1671 \u0412\u044b\u0441\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0430 \"\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\" \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0442 \u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0443 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0420\u0424 \u0432 \u042e\u041d\u0415\u0421\u041a\u041e]</ref>\n\nThe project being moved to Lakhta didn't stop the discussions. On 11 April 2012, ex-governor of St. Petersburg and now Federation Council chairwoman Valentina Matvienko said to journalists that the \"Lakhta center could become a new symbol of the city and attract the businessmen from all over the world to St. Petersburg.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo.msk.ru/programs/sorokina/876139-echo/ |title=\"In the light circle\", the interview with Ms.Matvienko at \"Echo Moskvy\" |publisher=Echo.msk.ru |date= |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\nDuring his visit to Russia in 2011 the Chairman of the [[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]] Professor Sang-Dae Kim was treated to a presentation of a project of Lakhta Center. Professor Kim commented on the \"modern shape\" of the proposed Lakhta Center, which according to him had \"nothing in common with ordinary boxes\".<ref>[http://www.ctbuh.org/Events/ToursVisits/ProfKimVisitstoSEAsiaRussia/ProfKimvisitRussia/tabid/2778/language/en-US/Default.aspx CTBUH Meeting: Russia]</ref> He also stated that something new ought to be created, which can be shown to new generations in 200\u2013300 years as for them what is created nowadays will be the same history as the architecture of the 18-19th centuries for us today. Professor also noticed that the project reminds him of an oriental concept [[Yin Yang]]: on the one hand, the historic part of the city with horizontal buildings and water, and on the other hand, a vertical which will add additional charm to the city. Lakhta Center combines an interesting form and modern technologies, so up to Mr. Kim, with the lapse of time the Center can become a new symbol of Saint Petersburg.<ref>[http://www.gazeta.ru/realty/2011/09/07_a_3759709.shtml Without skyscrapers Russia is the Kremlin and the Red Army]</ref>\n\nOn 16 May 2012, St. Petersburg governor Georgiy Poltavchenko emphasized in his annual report for House of Assembly the necessity of building a new \"city\" in St. Petersburg. According to Mr Poltavchenko, there are three appropriate districts for that: Lakhta center, Pulkovo and [[aggradation|aggradated]] territories near Waterfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fontanka.ru/2012/05/15/056/ |title=Poltavchenko: Petersburg needs a new business center and town-planning dictation |publisher=Fontanka.ru |date=2012-05-15 |accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Construction gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Site's view prior to construction.jpg|Site's view prior to construction, July 2012.\nFile:Aerial view of the construction site of Lakhta Center in Saint Petersburg, November 2014.jpg|Panoramic view of the construction site, November 2014.\nFile:Piling process.jpg|Piling process\nFile:Construction of the foundation under the Tower.jpg|Construction of the foundation under the Tower\nFile:Foundations of the Tower and mixed-use building are ready.jpg|Foundations of the tower and mixed-use building are ready\nFile:Lakhta Center.jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2015\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Feb, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0438\u044e\u043b\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Jul, 2016\nFile:Lakhta_Center_Oktober_2016.jpg|The state of the construction as of October, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Lakhta Center. Nov, 2016\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044c 2016).jpg|Skyscraper at the end of 2016. Height is 245 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044c 2017).jpg|Skyscraper in April 2017. Height is 310 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u0439 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2017. Height is 323 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2017).jpg|Lakhta Center in September 2017. Height is 365 meters\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440, \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c 2018 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430.jpg|Lakhta Center in January 2018. Installation of the spire, height of about 450 meters\nFile:Lakhta Center orig.jpg|Skyscraper at the end of February 2018. Installation of the spire is complete, glazing of the tower and spire continues.\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043c\u0430\u044f\u043a).jpg|Lakhta Center in May 2018.\nFile:Das Lachta Zentr- \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 2H1A5980WI.jpg| June 2018\nFile:\u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440 (\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044c 2018).jpg|Lakhta Center in November 2018\nFile:2-\u044f \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u044c \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Construction of the 2nd stage (November 2018)\nFile:Lakhta Center at night in april 2019.jpg|April 2019\nFile:\u041d\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u044b \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Skyscraper lighting\nFile:Lakhta Center, spire.jpg|The spire of the skyscraper (General view).\nFile:\u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445 \u0448\u043f\u0438\u043b\u044f \u041b\u0430\u0445\u0442\u0430-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|The top of the spire. Floodlight projectors are integrated in it\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Russia]]\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Europe]]\n* [[List of twisted buildings]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/ Official site of Lakhta Center]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070401024640/http://www.ohta-center.ru/ Official Site of the Okhta Center project]\n* [http://www.proektvlahte.ru/en/future/view/ Visual Analysis projecting the appearance of the tower at the Lakhta site, from various points in St. Petersburg]\n* [https://ru-ru.facebook.com/lakhtacenter.ru/ Official social media page]\n\n{{Supertall skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Saint Petersburg culture]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[Category:Architecture of Russia]]\n[[Category:Gazprom]]\n[[Category:Skyscrapers in Russia]]\n[[Category:Twisted buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Galebazz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInnovations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakhta_Center"}
{"title_page": "Colo River", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}{{Use Australian English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Colo\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = King Rapids, Colo River, NSW, Australia.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| image_caption      = King Rapids on the Colo River in [[Wollemi National Park]], 2010.\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Australia]]\n| subdivision_type2  = [[States and territories of Australia|State]]\n| subdivision_name2  = [[New South Wales]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Sydney Basin]] ([[Interim Biogeographic Regionalisation for Australia|IBRA]]), [[Central Tablelands]], [[Blue Mountains (New South Wales)|Blue Mountains]]\n| subdivision_type4  = \n| subdivision_name4  = \n| subdivision_type5  = Municipalities\n| subdivision_name5  = [[City of Lithgow|Lithgow]], [[Hawkesbury Shire|Hawkesbury]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|86|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = [[Capertee River]]\n| source1_location   = \n| source1_coordinates= \n| source1_elevation  = \n| source2            = [[Wolgan River]] \n| source2_location   = \n| source2_coordinates= \n| source2_elevation  = \n| source_confluence            = \n| source_confluence_location   = northeast of [[Newnes, New South Wales|Newnes]]\n| source_confluence_coordinates= {{coord|-33.205392|150.465187|format=dms}}\n| source_confluence_elevation  = {{convert|218|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = [[confluence]] with the [[Hawkesbury River]]\n| mouth_location     = near [[Lower Portland, New South Wales|Lower Portland]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|-33.437452|150.886294|format=dms}}\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|4|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = [[Hawkesbury River|Hawkesbury]]-[[Nepean River|Nepean]] catchment\n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   = [[Wollemi Creek]], Dooli Creek, Angorawa Creek\n| tributaries_right  = Tambo Creek, Main Creek (New South Wales), [[Wollangambe River]], Blacksmiths Creek (New South Wales), Gospers Creek\n| custom_label       = [[National park]]s\n| custom_data        = [[Blue Mountains National Park|Blue Mountains NP]], [[Wollemi National Park|Wollemi NP]]\n| extra              = <ref name=bonzle>{{cite web |url=http://www.bonzle.com/c/a?a=p&cmd=sp&p=206977&st=&s=colo%20river |title=Colo River, NSW |work=Bonzle Digital Atlas of Australia |accessdate=27 February 2013 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Colo River''', a [[perennial stream]]<ref name=gnb>{{NSW GNR |id=JPIOwpWAKW |title=Colo River (13347) |date=30 October 1970 |accessdate=27 February 2013 }}</ref><ref name=gnb1>{{NSW GNR |id=JPIOwpUlMa |title=Colo River (13372) |date=30 October 1970 |accessdate=27 February 2013 }}</ref> that is part of the [[Hawkesbury River|Hawkesbury]]-[[Nepean River|Nepean]] catchment, is located in the [[Central Tablelands]] of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]. \n\n==Course==\nThe Colo River rises on the [[Great Dividing Range]], northeast of [[Newnes, New South Wales|Newnes]], formed by the [[confluence]] of the [[Wolgan River]] and the [[Capertee River]], which respectively drain the [[Wolgan Valley|Wolgan]] and [[Capertee Valley|Capertee]] Valleys north of [[Lithgow, New South Wales|Lithgow]]. Colo River flows eastwards and then south through a deep gorge in the northern section of the [[Blue Mountains (Australia)|Blue Mountains]].  The majority of the river lies in [[Wollemi National Park]]. The middle Colo is inaccessible, rugged and remote. The wilderness was saved from development, logging and damming in the late 1970s by the Colo Wilderness Preservation Society and other environmentalists. Emerging from the wilderness region, the lower part of the Colo River flows through a scenic, narrow agricultural valley and reaches the [[Hawkesbury River]] at [[Lower Portland]] north of [[Windsor, New South Wales|Windsor]]. Tributaries of the Colo include the [[Wollangambe River]] and [[Wollemi Creek]]. The river descends {{convert|214|m}} over its {{convert|86|km|adj=on}} [[watercourse|course]].<ref name=bonzle/>\n\nAt {{NSWcity|Colo}}, the river is crossed by the [[Putty Road]] (B84).\n\nParts of the area surrounding the river, including both the [[Blue Mountains National Park]] and the Wollemi National Park have received [[List of World Heritage Sites in Oceania|World Heritage listing]], due in part to the discovery of the [[Wollemia|Wollemi Pine]], often described as a 'living fossil' from the age of the dinosaurs. The Colo River gorge contains many boulder-rapids that alternate with deep pools. Even though this area is relatively close to the [[Sydney]] metropolitan area, the Colo River flows through the largest wilderness area in New South Wales. Local volunteer bush regeneration groups such as the \"Friends of the Colo\" have been helping eradicate invasive exotic weeds in the area surrounding the river.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\n[[Image:Colo river upper colo.JPG|thumb|750px|center|The Colo River under low-water conditions at [[Upper Colo, New South Wales|Upper Colo]].]]\n\n==History==\nThe traditional custodians of the land surrounding the Colo River are the [[Indigenous Australians|Australian Aboriginal]] peoples of the [[Darug people|Darug]] nation.<ref name=crhistory>{{cite web |url=http://coloriver.com.au/history.htm |title=History Colo River |work=Colo River NSW |year= |accessdate=27 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe area of the lower Colo River was first explored by Europeans in June 1789 by [[Arthur Phillip|Governor Phillip]] and settlement commenced from the early 1800s via [[land grant]]s, that were significantly expanded from 1833. The Colo River was an important transport corridor in the period before motor vehicles, with produce and goods transported down the Hawkesbury River to Sydney.<ref name=crhistory/>\n\n==Recreation==\nBushwalking, canoeing, fishing, and accommodation retreats are all popular recreation activities along various parts of the Colo River.\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{portal|New South Wales|Environment|Water}}}}\n* [[List of rivers of Australia]]\n* [[List of rivers in New South Wales (A-K)]]\n* [[Rivers of New South Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.hawkesbury.nsw.gov.au/community/parks-and-recreation/upper-colo-camping |title=Camping at Upper Colo Reserve |work=Parks & Recreation |publisher=Hawkesbury City Council |year=2012 |access-date=27 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304030445/http://www.hawkesbury.nsw.gov.au/community/parks-and-recreation/upper-colo-camping |archive-date=4 March 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n* [http://www.friendsofthecolo.org.au/ Friends of the Colo]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://www.hn.cma.nsw.gov.au/topics/2058.html Colo River Subcatchment] at the Hawkesbury-Nepean Catchment Management Authority website\n* [http://www.hn.cma.nsw.gov.au/multiversions/3392/FileName/Vol2_Colo%2023-24.pdf Colo River Subcatchment]\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book  |title=Colo River passes and routes |author1=Corlis, Brian |year=2005 |publisher=B. Corlis |location=Glenmore Park, NSW |isbn=0-6464-4721-1 |pages=31 }}\n\n{{Rivers of the Sydney Basin |state=autocollapse}}\