{"title_page": "Lost in Translation (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2003 film directed by Sofia Coppola}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Lost in Translation\n| image          = Lost in Translation poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| alt            = <!-- description needed see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| director       = [[Sofia Coppola]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ross Katz]]\n* Sofia Coppola}}\n| writer         = Sofia Coppola\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Bill Murray]]\n* [[Scarlett Johansson]]\n* [[Giovanni Ribisi]]\n* [[Anna Faris]]\n* Fumihiro Hayashi\n}}<!-- per poster billing block -->\n| music          = See [[#Music|music]]\n| cinematography = [[Lance Acord]]\n| editing        = [[Sarah Flack]]\n| production_companies =  {{Plainlist|\n* [[American Zoetrope]]\n* Elemental Films}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| distributor    =  {{Plainlist|\n* [[Focus Features]] (United States)\n* [[Tohokushinsha Film]] (Japan)}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2003|8|29|[[Telluride Film Festival]]|2003|9|12|United States|2004|4|17|Japan}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes<ref>{{cite news | title=''Lost in Translation'' | publisher=Australian Classification | url=http://www.classification.gov.au/Pages/View.aspx?sid=yYswbmSEc6366pg9JjpWng%253d%253d&ncdctx=sHsnaZV38NRshMiU2dzq3nwXWCWJQQkDMMcyOxhF5ce1lVHM9d1FDUiNxfrfQhHHscURO7bmfpScHgp1PojiNw%253d%253d | accessdate=March 14, 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web |url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/54274 |title=Lost in Translation (2003) |format=select \"Details\" tab |work=[[American Film Institute]] |accessdate=September 9, 2018}}</ref>\n* Japan<ref name=\"afi\"/>}}\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n*English\n*Japanese\n}}\n| budget         = $4 million<ref name=\"boxoffice\">{{cite news | title=''Lost in Translation'' | work=Box Office Mojo |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lostintranslation.htm | accessdate=March 13, 2009}}</ref>\n| gross          = $119.7 million<ref name=\"boxoffice\" />\n}}\n'''''Lost in Translation''''' is a 2003 [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Sofia Coppola]]. It stars [[Bill Murray]] as middle-aged actor Bob Harris, who befriends college graduate Charlotte ([[Scarlett Johansson]]) in a [[Tokyo]] hotel. The movie explores themes of [[loneliness]], [[insomnia]], [[Existentialism|existential]] [[ennui]], and [[culture shock]] against the backdrop of a modern Japanese city.\n\n''Lost in Translation'' was nominated for four [[Academy Awards]], including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Bill Murray, and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Coppola; Coppola won for [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]. Murray and Johansson each won a [[BAFTA]] award for [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]] and [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress in a Leading Role]] respectively. The film grossed $119 million on a budget of $4 million.\n\n==Plot==\nBob Harris, an aging American movie star, arrives in Tokyo to film an advertisement for [[Suntory]] whiskey. Charlotte, a young college graduate, sits bored in her hotel room while her husband John, a celebrity photographer, is on assignment in Tokyo. Charlotte is unsure of her future with John, feeling detached from his lifestyle and disillusioned about their relationship. Bob's 25-year marriage is also strained as he goes through a [[midlife crisis]].\n\nEach day, Bob and Charlotte encounter each other in the hotel and after both experience insomnia, they sit and chat at the hotel bar one night. Eventually, Charlotte invites Bob to meet with some local friends of hers. The two bond through a fun night in Tokyo with Charlotte's friends, experiencing Japanese nightlife and culture. In the days that follow, Bob and Charlotte's friendship develops as they spend more time together. One night, each unable to sleep, the two share an intimate conversation about Charlotte's personal troubles and Bob's married life.\n\nOn the penultimate night of his stay, Bob sleeps with the hotel bar's female jazz singer. The next morning Charlotte arrives at his room to invite him for lunch and overhears the woman in his room, leading to a difficult lunch. Later that night, outside the hotel during a fire alarm, Bob and Charlotte reconcile and express how they will miss each other as they make a final visit to the hotel bar.\n\nThe following morning, Bob is set to return to the United States. He tells Charlotte goodbye at the hotel lobby and sadly watches her walk back to the elevator. In a taxi to the airport, Bob sees Charlotte on a crowded street, leaves the car and walks to her. He embraces the tearful Charlotte and whispers something in her ear. The two share a brief kiss, say goodbye and Bob departs.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Bill Murray]] as Bob Harris\n* [[Scarlett Johansson]] as Charlotte\n* [[Giovanni Ribisi]] as John\n* [[Anna Faris]] as Kelly\n* Fumihiro Hayashi as Charlie Brown\n* Akiko Takeshita as Ms. Kawasaki\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Du Bois]] as the Pianist\n* [[Takashi Fujii (comedian)|Takashi Fujii]] as TV host\n* [[Hiromix]] as herself\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Analysis==\nOver the course of the film, several things are \"lost in translation\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A03E6DD103AF932A1575AC0A9659C8B63 |title=What Else Was Lost in Translation |accessdate=May 2, 2012 |last=Rich |first=Motoko |date=September 21, 2003 |work=[[The New York Times]]|quote= It doesn't take much to figure out that 'Lost in Translation,' the title of Sofia Coppola's elegiac new film about two lonely American souls in Tokyo, means more than one thing. There is the cultural dislocation felt by Bob Harris (Bill Murray), a washed-up movie actor, and Charlotte (Scarlett Johansson), a young wife trying to find herself. They are also lost in their marriages, lost in their lives. As Charlotte says, 'I just feel so alone, even with people around.' Then, of course, there is the simple matter of language.}}</ref> Bob (Murray), a Japanese director ([[Diamond Yukai|Yutaka Tadokoro]]), and an interpreter (Takeshita) are on a set, filming a commercial for [[Suntory]] whisky (specifically, 17-year-old [[Hibiki (whisky)|Hibiki]]). In several exchanges, the director gives lengthy, impassioned directives in Japanese. These are invariably followed by brief, incomplete translations from the interpreter.\n\n::{{dialogue|Director|The translation is very important, O.K.? The translation.|mood1=in Japanese, to the interpreter|Interpreter|Yes, of course. I understand.|mood2=in Japanese, to the director|Director|Mr. Bob. You are sitting quietly in your study. And then there is a bottle of Suntory whisky on top of the table. You understand, right? With wholehearted feeling, slowly, look at the camera, tenderly, and as if you are meeting old friends, say the words. As if you are [[Humphrey Bogart|Bogie]] in ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'', saying, 'Here's looking at you, kid,'\u2014Suntory time!|mood3=in Japanese, to Bob|Interpreter|He wants you to turn, look in camera. O.K.?|mood4=In English, to Bob|Bob|...Is that all he said?}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/21/style/what-else-was-lost-in-translation.html |title=What Else Was Lost in Translation |accessdate=November 4, 2007 |last=Rich |first=Motoko |date=September 21, 2003 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the meaning and detail lost in the translation of the director's words, the two central characters in the film\u2014Bob and Charlotte\u2014are also lost in other ways. On a basic level, they are lost in the alien [[culture of Japan|Japanese culture]]. But in addition, they are lost in their own lives and relationships, a feeling, amplified by their displaced location, that leads to their blossoming friendship and growing connection with one another.<ref name=\"Gehring2004\">{{cite journal |last=Gehring |first=Wes D. |date=January 2004 |title=Along Comes Another Coppola |journal=[[USA Today (magazine)|USA Today]] |volume=132 |page=59|publisher=The Society for the Advancement of Education |issn=0161-7389}}</ref>\n\nBy her own admission, Coppola wanted to create a romantic movie about two characters that have a moment of connection. The story's timeline was intentionally shortened to emphasize this moment.<ref>{{cite journal|date=October 2003|title=The Co-Conspirators|journal=Interview|volume=33|issue=9|page=56|publisher=Interview, Inc.|location=New York|issn=0149-8932}}</ref> Additionally, Coppola has said that since \"there's not much happening in the story besides [Bob and Charlotte's relationship]\", the filmmakers tried to keep an ongoing tension.<ref name=\"Carter\">{{cite news|title=Famous lost words|first=Kelly|last=Carter|date=September 21, 2003|work=[[South China Morning Post]]}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box|quote=As an actor, and as a writer/director, the question is: is it going to be very noble here? [Is] this guy going to say, \"I just can't call you. We can't share room service anymore?\" Is it going to be like that sort of thing, or is it going to be a little more real where they actually get really close to it?|align=right|width=30em|style=padding:8px|source=\u2014Bill Murray<ref name=\"Murray 1\">{{cite web|title=Interview with 'Lost in Translation' Star Bill Murray|url=http://movies.about.com/cs/lostintranslation/a/lostbillint.htm|first=Rebecca|last=Murray|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=Feb 19, 2014|page=1}}</ref>}}\nMurray has described his biggest challenge in portraying Bob as managing the character's conflicted feelings. On one hand, Murray said, Bob knows that it could be dangerous to become too close to Charlotte, but on the other, he is lonely and knows that having an affair would be easy. Murray worked to portray a balance between being affectionate and being \"respectable\".<ref name=\"Murray 1\"/>\n\nThe academic Marco Abel lists ''Lost in Translation'' as one of many films that belong to the category of \"postromance\" cinema, which he says offers a negative perspective of love, sex, romance, and dating. According to Abel, the characters in such films reject the idealized notion of lifelong monogamy.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Abel|first=Marco|year=2010|title=Failing to Connect: Itinerations of Desire in Oskar Roehler's Postromance Films|journal=New German Critique|volume=37|issue=1|series=109|page=77|publisher=New German Critique, Inc.|doi=10.1215/0094033X-2009-018}}</ref>\n\nUniversity of Vermont professor Todd McGowan interprets the film from a [[Jacques Lacan|Lacanian]] psychoanalytic perspective, arguing that it encourages us to embrace \"absence\" in our lives and relationships.<ref name=mcgowan>{{cite journal |last1=McGowan |first1=Todd |title=There is Nothing Lost in Translation |journal=Quarterly Review of Film and Video |date=2007 |volume=24 |issue=1}}</ref>{{rp|62}} He describes Coppola's depiction of Tokyo \"as a city bubbling over with excess\", which offers an empty promise of gratification.{{r|mcgowan|p=54}} Both Bob and Charlotte recognize that they cannot find meaning in Tokyo's bounties, so they bond over their shared sense of emptiness and failure.{{r|mcgowan|p=54}} The author and filmmaker Anita Schillhorn van Veen interprets the film as a criticism of [[modernity]], in which Tokyo is a contemporary \"[[Ukiyo|floating world]]\" of fleeting pleasures that are too alienating and amoral to facilitate meaningful relationships.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schillhorn van Veen|first=Anita|date=March 1, 2006|title=The Floating World: Representations of Japan in ''Lost in Translation'' and ''Demonlover''|journal=Asian Cinema|volume=17|issue=1|pages=190\u2013193|issn=1059-440X}}</ref> Tessa Dwyer, writing for ''Linguistica Antverpiensia, New Series \u2013 Themes in Translation Studies'', called ''Lost in Translation'' a [[Polyglotism|polyglot]] film that challenges the film industry's \"more usual tendency to ignore or deny issues of language difference\" by highlighting Bob and Charlotte's difficult contact with the Japanese language.<ref name=\"Dwyer\">{{cite journal|last=Dwyer|first=Tessa|year=2005|title=Universally speaking: Lost in Translation and polyglot cinema |url=https://lans-tts.uantwerpen.be/index.php/LANS-TTS/article/view/143 |journal=Linguistica Antverpiensia, New Series \u2013 Themes in Translation Studies |issue=4 |pages=297\u2013300 |publisher=Department of Translators and Interpreters, Antwerp University |accessdate=February 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Aesthetics===\nThe author and lecturer Maria San Filippo contends that the film's setting, Tokyo, is an audiovisual metaphor for Bob and Charlotte's world views. She explains that the calm ambience of the city's hotel represents Bob's desire to be secure and undisturbed, while the energetic atmosphere of the city streets represents Charlotte's willingness to engage with the world.<ref>{{cite journal|last=San Filippo|first=Maria|year=2003|title=Lost in Translation|journal=Cineaste|volume=29|issue=1|page=28|publisher=Cineaste|location=New York|issn=0009-7004}}</ref> Coppola and [[Lance Acord]], the film's cinematographer, agreed that ''Lost in Translation'' needed to rely heavily on visual expression to support the characters' romance.\n\nRobert Hahn, an essayist writing for ''[[The Southern Review]]'', suggested that the filmmakers deliberately used [[chiaroscuro]], the art of using strong contrasts between light and dark to support the story. He wrote that the film's dominant light tones symbolize feelings of humor and romance, and they are contrasted with dark tones that symbolize underlying feelings of despondency. He compared this to the technique of the painter [[John Singer Sargent]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hahn|first=Robert|year=2006|title=Dancing in the Dark|journal=The Southern Review|volume=42|issue=1|pages=153\u2013154|issn=0038-4534}}</ref>\n\nThe film's opening shot, which features a close shot of Charlotte lying down in translucent pink underwear, has interested various commentators. In particular, it has been compared to the portraitures of the painter [[John Kacere]] and the image of [[Brigitte Bardot]] in the opening scene of the 1963 film ''[[Contempt (film)|Contempt]]''. Dwyer wrote that when the two shots are compared, they reveal the importance of language difference, as both films highlight the complexities involved with characters speaking multiple languages.<ref name=\"Dwyer\"/> Filippo wrote that while the image in ''Contempt'' is used to remark on [[sexual objectification]], Coppola \"doesn't seem to be making a statement at all beyond a sort of endorsement of beauty for beauty's sake\".<ref name=\"San2003\">{{cite journal|last=San Filippo|first=Maria|year=2003|title=Lost in Translation |journal=Cineaste |volume=29 |issue=1 |page=26 |publisher=Cineaste |location=New York |issn=0009-7004}}</ref>\n\nCoppola revealed in a 2013 interview that the shot is indeed based on the art of Kacere.<ref name=\"Stern\">{{cite web|title=Sofia Coppola Discusses 'Lost in Translation' on Its 10th Anniversary |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/09/12/sofia-coppola-discusses-lost-in-translation-on-its-10th-anniversary.html |first=Marlow|last=Stern |date=September 12, 2013 |work=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=February 20, 2014}}</ref> [[Geoff King]], a professor of film at [[Brunel University]] (who published a book on the film, under the same name in a series titled \"American indies\", in 2010), contends that the shot is marked by an \"obvious\" appeal in its potential eroticism, and a \"subtle\" appeal in its artistic qualities. He used the shot as an example of the film's obvious attractions, which are characteristic of [[Major film studio|mainstream film]], and its subtle ones, which are typified by [[Independent film#The \"Indie Film\" Movement|\"indie\" film]].<ref>{{cite book|last=King|first=Geoff|editor=Gary Needham and Yannis Tzioumakis|title=Lost in Translation|series=American Indies|year=2010|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|location=Edinburgh|isbn=9780748637461|pages=1\u20132|chapter=Introduction}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n{{Quote box|quote=I remember having these weeks there that were sort of enchanting and weird{{nbsp}}... Tokyo is so disorienting, and there's a loneliness and isolation. Everything is so crazy, and the jet lag is torture. I liked the idea of juxtaposing a midlife crisis with that time in your early 20s when you're, like, What should I do with my life?|align=right|width=30em|style=padding:8px|source=\u2014Sofia Coppola, 2003<ref name=\"Betts\">{{cite news|last=Betts |first=Kate |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1005674-2,00.html |title=Sofia's Choice |publisher=TIME |date=September 15, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref>}}\nCoppola devised the idea of ''Lost in Translation'' after many visits to Tokyo in her twenties, basing much of the story on her experiences there.<ref name=\"Stern\"/><ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/sofia_coppola_talks_about_lost_in_translation_her_love_story_thats_not_nerd |title=Sofia Coppola Talks About \"Lost In Translation,\" Her Love Story That's Not \"Nerdy\" &#124; Filmmakers, Film Industry, Film Festivals, Awards & Movie Reviews |publisher=Indiewire |date=November 8, 2011 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=http://www.lost-in-translation.com/qaPopup.html |title=Lost In Translation |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724175933/http://www.lost-in-translation.com/qaPopup.html |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> Coppola was attracted to the [[Neon lighting|neon lights]] of [[Tokyo]] and has described the [[Park Hyatt Tokyo]], where most of the film's interior sequences take place, as one of her \"favorite places in the world\".<ref name=\"indiewire\" /> Particularly, she was attracted to its quietness, design, and \"combination of different cultures\", which include a New York bar and French restaurant.<ref name=\"indiewire\" />\n\nCoppola spent six months writing the film, beginning with \"short stories\" and \"impressions\" that culminated in a 70-page script.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenwritersutopia.com/modules.php?name=Content&pa=showpage&pid=57 |title=Sofia Coppola on LOST IN TRANSLATION |publisher=Screenwritersutopia.com |date=March 11, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216010832/http://www.screenwritersutopia.com/modules.php?name=Content&pa=showpage&pid=57 |archivedate=February 16, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.filmmakermagazine.com/issues/fall2003/features/tokyo_story.php |title=Sofia Coppola's Lost in Translation - Filmmaker Magazine - Fall 2003 |publisher=Filmmaker Magazine |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414022213/http://www.filmmakermagazine.com/issues/fall2003/features/tokyo_story.php |archivedate=April 14, 2012 }}</ref> She wanted to create a story that was \"a little more funny and romantic\" than her previous feature, ''[[The Virgin Suicides (film)|The Virgin Suicides]]'', and she spent little time planning or rewriting it.<ref name=\"Carter\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|page=58|issn=1084-8665}}</ref> Coppola has called the film a \"valentine\" to Tokyo,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Calhoun|first=Dave|year=2003|title=Watching Bill Murray Movies|journal=[[Another Magazine]]|issue=5|page=100|publisher=Dazed Group}}</ref> in which she has displayed the city in the way that it is meaningful to her.\n\nCoppola wrote the film with Murray in mind and said she would not have made it without him.<ref name=\"Stern\"/> She said that she had always wanted to work with Murray and that she was attracted to his \"sweet, lovable side\".<ref name=\"indiewire\" /> She pursued him for five months to a year, relentlessly sending telephone messages and letters.<ref name=\"Stern\"/><ref name=\"Betts\" /><ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|last=Hirschberg |first=Lynn |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/31/magazine/31COPPOLA.html |title=The Coppola Smart Mob |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=August 31, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref> She enlisted help from [[Wes Anderson]], who had directed Murray in two films, and screenwriter [[Mitch Glazer]], who was a mutual friend.<ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\" /><ref name=\"nytimes\" /> Coppola went so far as to ask for help from actor [[Al Pacino]], who at the time lived in the same town as Murray.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=97jYhz7tmcg|title=Sofia Coppola On Getting Bill Murray To Do LOST IN TRANSLATION|first=|last=American Film Institute|date=December 12, 2008|publisher=|accessdate=August 29, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> In July 2002, Coppola and Murray finally met in a restaurant, and he agreed to participate because he \"couldn't let her down\".<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> Despite this, Murray did not sign a contract; when he finally arrived in Tokyo, Coppola described it as \"a huge relief\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elle.com/Pop-Culture/Cover-Shoots/Our-Own-Private-Hollywood/Our-Own-Private-Hollywood/%28imageIndex%29/23/%28play%29/false#mode=base;slide=23; |title=26 EL1110 WLWIHSofia 001 |publisher=Elle.com |date=October 7, 2010 |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503064033/http://www.elle.com/Pop-Culture/Cover-Shoots/Our-Own-Private-Hollywood/Our-Own-Private-Hollywood/(imageIndex)/23/(play)/false#mode=base;slide=23; |archive-date=May 3, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCoppola first noticed Scarlett Johansson in ''[[Manny & Lo]]'', where she related to her \"understated\" and \"subtle\" demeanor,<ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\" /><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://movies.about.com/cs/lostintranslation/a/lostsofia_2.htm|title=Interview with \"Lost in Translation\" Star Bill Murray|publisher=|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> envisioning her as a \"young [[Lauren Bacall]]-type girl\".<ref name=\"Stern\"/> Johansson, who was 17 years old at the time, immediately accepted the part and Coppola was happy with the maturity she brought to the character.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /><ref name=autogenerated1 /> In writing the story, Coppola said she was influenced by the relationship between Humphrey Bogart and [[Lauren Bacall]] in Howard Hawks' ''[[The Big Sleep (1946 film)|The Big Sleep]]''.<ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\" /> Murray and Johansson did not do any auditions before filming.<ref name=\"Stern\"/>\n\n===Filming===\nLance Acord, the film's director of photography, has written that the cinematographic style of ''Lost in Translation'' is largely based on \"daily experiences, memories and impressions\" of his time in Japan.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Acord|first=Lance|authorlink=Lance Acord|date=January 2004|title=Channeling Tokyo for ''Lost in Translation''|journal=American Cinematographer|volume=85|issue=1|pages=123\u2013124|publisher=American Society of Cinematographers|issn=0002-7928}}</ref> He worked closely with Coppola to visualize the film, relying on multiple experiences he shared with her in Tokyo before production took place. [[Location scouting]] was carried out by Coppola, Acord, and Ross Katz; and Coppola created 40 pages of photographs for the crew so that they would understand her visual intentions.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|page=57|issn=1084-8665}}</ref>\n\nAcord sought to maximize [[available light]] during shooting and use [[Stage lighting instrument|artificial lights]] as little as possible. He described this approach as conservative compared to \"the more conventional Hollywood system\", for which some of the crew's Japanese electricians thought he was \"out of his mind\".<ref name=\"Ballinger2004\">{{cite book|first=Alex|last=Ballinger|title=New Cinematographers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=10kR9a9SYnMC&pg=PA16|accessdate=April 6, 2012|date=October 12, 2004|publisher=Laurence King Publishing|isbn=978-1-85669-334-9}}</ref> In particular, Acord did not use any artificial lights to photograph the film's night-time exteriors.<ref name=\"Ballinger2004\" /> ''Lost in Translation'' was largely shot in an improvised, \"free-form\" manner, which Coppola described as \"stealthy\" and \"almost documentary-style\".<ref name=\"indiewire\" /><ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite video|title=Lost in Translation|date=2004|publisher= Focus Features/Universal Studios|medium= DVD}}</ref> The crew shot in some locations without permits, including Tokyo's subways and [[Shibuya, Tokyo#Shibuya Crossing|Shibuya Crossing]]; they avoided police by keeping a minimal crew.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> Acord avoided grandiose camera movements in favor of still shots to avoid taking away from the loneliness of the characters.<ref name=\"Ballinger2004\" />\n\nMost of the film was shot on an [[Aaton]] camera with [[35mm movie film|35 mm film stock]], using [[List of motion picture film stocks#VISION color negative (ECN-2 process 1996\u20132002)|Kodak Vision 500T 5263]] stock for nightlight exteriors and Kodak Vision 320T 5277 stock in daylight. A smaller [[Moviecam Compact]] was used in confined locations. Coppola said that her father, [[Francis Ford Coppola]], tried to convince her to shoot on video, but she ultimately decided on film, describing its \"fragmented, dislocated, melancholic, romantic feeling\", in contrast with video, which is \"more immediate, in the present\".<ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\" /> In interviews, she said she wanted to shoot Tokyo with a spontaneous \"informality\", similar to the \"way a snapshot looks\", and she chose to shoot on high-speed film stocks to evoke a \"homemade intimacy\".<ref name=\"Betts\" /><ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\" /> Some scenes were shot wholly for mood and were captured without sound.<ref name=\"Betts\" />\n\n''Lost in Translation'' was shot six days per week in September and October 2002, over the course of 27 days.<ref name=\"Betts\" /> During this time, videotape footage was mailed to editor Sarah Flack in [[New York City]], where she began editing the film in a Red Car office.<ref name=\"Crabtree\">{{cite journal|last=Crabtree|first=Sheigh|date=September 10, 2003|title=Editor Flack in Fashion for Coppola's \"Lost\" Pic|journal=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> The scenes with Bob and Charlotte together were largely shot in order.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|page=64|issn=1084-8665}}</ref> Many of the interior scenes were shot overnight, because the hotel did not allow the crew to shoot in much of its public space until after 1{{nbsp}}a.m.<ref name=\"Ballinger2004\" />\n[[File:New York Bar Unplugged, Park Hyatt Tokyo (8376387540).jpg|thumb|The bar at the Park Hyatt was used as a filming location]]\nVarious locations were used during production; in particular, the bar featured prominently in the film is the New York Bar, which is situated on the 52nd floor of the [[Shinjuku Park Tower]] and part of the Park Hyatt in [[Shinjuku, Tokyo]]. Other locations include the [[Heian Jingu]] shrine in [[Kyoto]] and the steps of the San-mon gate at [[Nanzen-ji]], as well as the club Air in the [[Daikanyama]] district of Tokyo. All the locations mentioned in the film are the names of actual places that existed in Tokyo at the time of filming. Murray described the first few weeks of the shoot as like \"being held prisoner\", since he was affected by [[jet lag]], and Johansson said the shoot made her \"busy, vulnerable and tired\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jan/01/1 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Geoffrey | last=MacNab | title=Geoffrey Macnab talks to Bill Murray | date=January 1, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2003/dec/28/features.magazine | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Polly | last=Vernon | title=Polly Vernon meets Scarlett Johansson | date=January 5, 2004}}</ref>\n\nCoppola spoke of the challenges of directing the movie with a Japanese crew, since she had to rely on her assistant director to make translations.<ref name=\"indiewire\" /> Much of the performances were improvised, and Coppola openly allowed modifications to dialogue during shooting. For example, the dialogue in the scene with Harris and the still photographer was unrehearsed.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|pages=58\u201359|issn=1084-8665}}</ref> Coppola has said that she was attracted to the idea of Bob and Charlotte going through stages of a romantic relationship all in one week\u2014in which they have met, courted, hurt each other, and discussed intimate life. To conclude this relationship, Coppola wanted a special ending even though she thought the concluding scene in the script was mundane. Coppola instructed Murray to perform the kiss in that scene without telling Johansson, to which she reacted without preparation. The whisper was also unscripted, but too quiet to be recorded. While Coppola initially considered having audible dialogue dubbed into the moment, she later decided that it was better to keep it \"between the two of\nthem.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|pages=63\u201364|issn=1084-8665}}</ref>\n\nAfter filming, Coppola and Flack spent approximately 10 weeks editing the film.<ref name=\"Crabtree\" /> In the bonus features of the film's DVD, Murray called ''Lost in Translation'' his favorite film that he has worked on,<ref name=autogenerated2 /> and Coppola described the film as her most \"personal\", since much of the story is based on her own experiences.<ref name=\"Stern\"/> For example, Charlotte's relationship with her husband is based on Coppola's relationship with her husband, [[Spike Jonze]], when they first married, and the \"Suntory\" commercial is based on a commercial Coppola's father, [[Francis Ford Coppola]], shot with [[Akira Kurosawa]].<ref name=\"Stern\"/><ref><!-- WP:FU as link for criticism. -->{{cite AV media\n| title = Suntory Whiskey commercials Coppola & Kurosawa\n| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v-A2EH0vyd4\n}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{main|Lost in Translation (soundtrack)}}\nThe film's [[Lost in Translation (soundtrack)|soundtrack]], supervised by [[Brian Reitzell]], was released on September 9, 2003 by [[Emperor Norton Records]]. It contains five songs by [[Kevin Shields]], including one from his group [[My Bloody Valentine (band)|My Bloody Valentine]]. Coppola said much of the soundtrack consisted of songs that she \"liked and had been listening to\", and she worked with Reitzell to make Tokyo [[dream pop]] mixes.<ref name=\"Stern\"/> The soundtrack also included [[The Jesus and Mary Chain]] hit \"[[Just Like Honey]]\". [[Allmusic]] gave the soundtrack four out of five stars, saying \"Coppola's impressionistic romance ''Lost in Translation'' features an equally impressionistic and romantic soundtrack that plays almost as big a role in the film as Bill Murray and Scarlett Johansson do.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Phares |first=Heather |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/lost-in-translation-mw0000316244 |title=Lost in Translation \u2013 Original Soundtrack |publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=October 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAgathi Glezakos, an academic writing a review of ''Lost in Translation'' shortly after its release, wrote that the music in the film's karaoke scene constitutes a common \"language\" that allows Bob and Charlotte to connect with some of the Japanese people amidst their alienation.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Glezakos|first=Agathi|date=October 15, 2003|title=Movie Review: ''Lost in Translation''|journal=Reflections: Narratives of Professional Helping|volume=9|issue=4|pages=71\u201372|publisher=[[California State University, Long Beach]]|issn=1080-0220}}</ref> In that scene, the rendition of the [[Pretenders (band)|Pretenders]]' \"[[Brass in Pocket]]\" was selected to showcase a lively side of Charlotte, and \"[[(What's So Funny 'Bout) Peace, Love, and Understanding]]\" was chosen to establish that Bob is from a different generation. Both Coppola and Murray finally selected [[Roxy Music]]'s \"[[More Than This (Roxy Music song)|More Than This]]\" during the shoot itself because they liked the band and thought the lyrics fit the story.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|pages=60\u201361|issn=1084-8665}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Lost in Translation'' was screened at the 2003 [[Telluride Film Festival]].<ref name=\"mitchell2\">{{cite news | last = Mitchell | first = Elvis | authorlink= Elvis Mitchell | title = Telluride Marks Its 30th Year With a Passing of Torches | work = [[The New York Times]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 1, 2003 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/01/movies/critic-s-notebook-telluride-marks-its-30th-year-with-a-passing-of-torches.html | accessdate = March 25, 2009 }}</ref> It was given a limited release on September 12, 2003 in 23 theaters where it grossed $925,087 on its opening weekend with an average of $40,221 per theater and ranking 15th at the box office.<ref name=\"boxoffice\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2003/LSTNT.php |title=Lost in Translation - Box Office Data, Movie News, Cast Information |publisher=The Numbers |accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref> It was given a wider release on October 3, 2003 in 864 theaters where it grossed $4,163,333 with an average of $4,818 per theater and ranking 7th. The film went on to make $44,585,453 in [[North America]] and $75,138,403 in the rest of the world for a worldwide total of $119,723,856.<ref name=\"boxoffice\" />\n\n===Critical response===\n''Lost in Translation'' received critical acclaim, particularly for Coppola's direction and screenplay and Murray and Johansson's performances. It has a score of 95% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with an average rating of 8.4/10 based on 228 reviews. The site's critical consensus states: \"Effectively balancing humor and subtle pathos, Sofia Coppola crafts a moving, melancholy story that serves as a showcase for both Bill Murray and Scarlett Johansson\".<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">{{cite web|title = Lost in Translation|work = Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate = March 19, 2010|url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lost_in_translation/}}</ref> The film also holds a score of 89 out of 100 based on 43 reviews on [[Metacritic]], indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web|title=Lost in Translation|work=Metacritic|accessdate=May 25, 2011|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/lost-in-translation}}</ref>\n\nCritic [[Roger Ebert]] gave ''Lost in Translation'' four out of four stars and named it the second best film of the year, describing it as \"sweet and sad at the same time as it is sardonic and funny\".<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite news | last = Ebert | first = Roger | authorlink= Roger Ebert | title = ''Lost in Translation'' | work = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 12, 2003 | url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20030912/REVIEWS/309120302/1023 | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref> In his review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Elvis Mitchell]] wrote: \"At 18, [Johansson] gets away with playing a 25-year-old woman by using her husky voice to test the level of acidity in the air{{nbsp}}... Ms. Johansson is not nearly as accomplished a performer as Mr. Murray, but Ms. Coppola gets around this by using Charlotte's simplicity and curiosity as keys to her character.\"<ref name=\"elvis\">{{cite news | last = Mitchell | first = Elvis | authorlink= Elvis Mitchell | title = An American in Japan, Making a Connection | work = [[The New York Times]] | publisher = | date = September 12, 2003 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/12/movies/film-review-an-american-in-japan-making-a-connection.html | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film an \"A\" rating and [[Lisa Schwarzbaum]] wrote: \"Working opposite the embracing, restful serenity of Johansson, Murray reveals something more commanding in his repose than we have ever seen before. Trimmed to a newly muscular, rangy handsomeness and in complete rapport with his character's hard-earned acceptance of life's limitations, Murray turns in a great performance.\"<ref name=\"schwarzbaum\u2212\">{{cite news | last = Schwarzbaum | first = Lisa | title = ''Lost in Translation'' | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 10, 2003 | url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,479937,00.html | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn his review for ''[[The New York Observer]]'', [[Andrew Sarris]] called the film \"that rarity of rarities, a grown-up romance based on the deliberate repression of sexual gratification{{nbsp}}... when independent films are exploding with erotic images edging ever closer to outright pornography, Ms. Coppola and her colleagues have replaced sexual facility with emotional longing, without being too coy or self-congratulatory in the process.\"<ref name=\"sarris\">{{cite news | last = Sarris | first = Andrew | title = Lonely Souls in a Strange Land: ''Lost in Translation'' Maps the Way | work = [[New York Observer]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 28, 2003 | url = http://www.observer.com/node/48113 | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the film three and a half stars out of four and wrote that it \"offers quiet humor in lieu of the bludgeoning direct assaults most comedies these days inflict\".<ref name=\"clark\">{{cite news | last = Clark | first = Mike | title = Comedy doesn't get lost in ''Translation'' | work = [[USA Today]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 12, 2003 | url = https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2003-09-11-translation_x.htm | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s [[Richard Corliss]] praised Murray's performance: \"You won't find a subtler, funnier or more poignant performance this year than this quietly astonishing turn.\"<ref name=\"corliss\">{{cite news | last = Corliss | first = Richard | title = A Victory for Lonely Hearts | work = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 15, 2003 | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1005675,00.html | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref> His performance has been likened to the sardonic persona of [[W. C. Fields]].<ref name=\"Gehring2004\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Alleva|first=Richard|date=December 5, 2003|title=About a Boy: Kill Bill-Volume 1 and Lost in Translation|journal=[[Commonweal (magazine)|Commonweal]]|volume=130|issue=21|page=14|publisher=Commonweal Foundation|issn=0010-3330}}</ref>\n\nIn his review for ''[[The Observer]]'', [[Philip French]] wrote: \"While ''Lost in Translation'' is deeply sad and has a strongly [[Michelangelo Antonioni|Antonioniesque]] flavour, it's also a wispy romantic comedy with little plot and some well-observed comic moments.\"<ref name=\"french\">{{cite news | last = French | first = Philip | authorlink= Philip French | title = The odd Coppola | work = [[The Observer]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = January 11, 2004 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jan/11/philipfrench | accessdate = March 16, 2009 | location=London}}</ref> In ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Joe Queenan (author)|Joe Queenan]] praised Coppola's film as \"one of the few Hollywood films I have seen this year that has a brain; but more than that, it has a soul.\"<ref name=\"queenan\">{{cite news | last = Queenan | first = Joe | authorlink= Joe Queenan (author) | title = A yen for romance | work = [[The Guardian]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = January 10, 2004 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jan/10/features.joequeenan | accessdate = March 16, 2009 | location=London}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s [[Peter Travers]] gave it four out of four stars and wrote: \"Before saying goodbye, they whisper something to each other that the audience can't hear. Coppola keeps her film as hushed and intimate as that whisper. ''Lost in Translation'' is found gold. Funny how a wisp of a movie from a wisp of a girl can wipe you out.\"<ref name=\"travers\">{{cite news | last = Travers | first = Peter | title = ''Lost in Translation'' | work = [[Rolling Stone]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 8, 2003 | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/lost-in-translation-20030908 | accessdate = March 10, 2011 }}</ref> [[J. Hoberman]], in his review for the ''[[Village Voice]]'', wrote: \"''Lost in Translation'' is as bittersweet a brief encounter as any in American movies since [[Richard Linklater]]'s equally romantic ''[[Before Sunrise]]''. But ''Lost in Translation'' is the more poignant reverie. Coppola evokes the emotional intensity of a one-night stand far from home\u2014but what she really gets is the magic of movies\".<ref name=\"hoberman\">{{cite news | last = Hoberman | first = J | title = After Sunset | work = [[Village Voice]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 9, 2003 | url = http://www.villagevoice.com/2003-09-09/film/after-sunset/1 | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association]] and [[National Society of Film Critics]] voted Bill Murray best actor of the year.<ref name=\"Mitchell\">{{cite news | last = Mitchell | first = Wendy | title = LA Critics Choose ''Splendor'', ''Friedmans'' Follow-Up, Texas Picks, and More | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = January 9, 2004 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/la_critics_choose_splendor_friedmans_follow-up_texas_picks_and_more/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hernandez4\">{{cite news | last = Hernandez | first = Eugene | title = National Film Critics Group Names ''American Splendor'' Top Film of '03 | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = January 5, 2004 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/national_film_critics_group_names_american_splendor_top_film_of_03/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref> The [[New York Film Critics Circle]] also voted Murray best actor and Sofia Coppola best director.<ref name=\"Hernandez5\">{{cite news | last = Hernandez | first = Eugene | title = NY Critics Crown ''King'' Top Film of '03; SF & Boston Critics Also Weigh In | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = December 16, 2003 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/ny_critics_crown_king_top_film_of_03_sf_boston_critics_also_weigh_in/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref> Coppola received an award for special filmmaking achievement from the [[National Board of Review]].<ref name=\"Mitchell2\">{{cite news | last = Mitchell | first = Wendy | title = National Board of Review Says ''Mystic River'' is Tops For 2003 | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = December 4, 2003 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/national_board_of_review_says_mystic_river_is_tops_for_2003/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref> ''Lost in Translation'' also appeared on several critics' top ten lists for 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2003/toptens.shtml|title=Metacritic: 2003 Film Critic Top Ten Lists|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225093312/http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2003/toptens.shtml|archivedate=December 25, 2007|accessdate=March 25, 2009|publisher=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] added it to his \"great movies\" list on his website.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100804/REVIEWS08/100809996 | work=Chicago Sun-Times | title=Lost in Translation (2003)}}</ref> ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' named it one of the 50 Best Movies of the Decade (2000-2009), ranking it at #7.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Movies of the Decade (2000-2009)|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2009/11/50-best-movies-of-the-decade-2000-2009.html?p=5|work=[[Paste Magazine]]|accessdate=December 14, 2011|date=November 3, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' named it one of the best films of the decade, writing: \"Six years later, we still have no clue what Bill Murray whispered into Scarlett Johansson's ear. And we don't want to. Why spoil a perfect film?\"<ref>Geier, Thom; Jensen, Jeff; Jordan, Tina; Lyons, Margaret; Markovitz, Adam; Nashawaty, Chris; Pastorek, Whitney; Rice, Lynette; Rottenberg, Josh; Schwartz, Missy; Slezak, Michael; Snierson, Dan; Stack, Tim; Stroup, Kate; Tucker, Ken; Vary, Adam B.; Vozick-Levinson, Simon; Ward, Kate (December 11, 2009), \"THE 100 Greatest MOVIES, TV SHOWS, ALBUMS, BOOKS, CHARACTERS, SCENES, EPISODES, SONGS, DRESSES, MUSIC VIDEOS, AND TRENDS THAT ENTERTAINED US OVER THE PAST 10 YEARS\". Entertainment Weekly. (1079/1080):74-84</ref> Director [[Quentin Tarantino]] included ''Lost in Translation'' in his list of top 20 films released since 1992, when his career as a filmmaker began.<ref>{{cite web | title = Team America, Anything Else Among the Best Movies of the Past Seventeen Years, Claims Quentin Tarantino| last=Brown|first=Lane | work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] | publisher=New York Media LLC | url =http://www.vulture.com/2009/08/speed_and_team_america_among_q.html | accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2016 international critics' poll by the [[BBC]], ''Lost in Translation'' was voted the 22nd greatest film since 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films |title=The 21st century's 100 greatest films |publisher=BBC |date=August 23, 2016 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Criticism ===\nThe film received some negative reviews, many from Japanese critics. Japanese TV critic Osugi {{small|{{bracket|[[:ja:\u304a\u3059\u304e|ja]]}}}} of Osugi and [[Peeco|Piko]] fame said \"The core story is cute and not bad; however, the depiction of Japanese people is terrible!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2004/0419/p07s01-woap.html|title='Lost in Translation' doesn't translate well in Japan|first=Robert|last=Marquand|date=April 19, 2004|publisher=|accessdate=August 29, 2017|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> In a ''Guardian'' article about the film, Kiku Day, a musician specializing in the ''[[shakuhachi]]'' Japanese flute, wrote that she \"couldn't help wondering not only whether I had watched a different movie, but whether the plaudits had come from a parallel universe of values\"; according to Day, there is \"no scene where the Japanese are afforded a shred of dignity. The viewer is sledgehammered into laughing at these small, yellow people and their funny ways.\"<ref name=\"kikuguard\">{{cite news| url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/jan/24/japan.film | title= Totally lost in translation | date= January 24, 2004 | last= Day | first= Kiku | publisher=The Guardian | accessdate= October 10, 2010 | location=London}}</ref> Day also said \"while shoe-horning every possible caricature of modern Japan into her movie, Coppola is respectful of ancient Japan. It is depicted approvingly, though ancient traditions have very little to do with the contemporary Japanese. The good Japan, according to this director, is Buddhist monks chanting, ancient temples, [[Ikebana|flower arrangement]]; meanwhile she portrays the contemporary Japanese as ridiculous people who have lost contact with their own culture.\"<ref name=\"kikuguard\" /> Furthermore, the critic Inkoo Kang has criticized the film for its xenophobia, racism, and anti-Asian bias, in which the film expresses a dismissive attitude in aspects such as speech, sexuality, tastes, and contemporary culture.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kang |first1=Inkoo |title=Lost In Translation Is An Insufferable, Racist Mess \u2014 Why Would We Expect The Beguiled To Be Any Different? |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3021638/lost-in-translation-is-an-insufferable-racist-mess-why-would-we-expect-the-beguiled-to-be-any-different/ |website=MTV News |language=en |date=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHawaiian filmmaker and author E. Koohan Paik wrote that \"The Japanese are presented not as people, but as clowns\" and that \"''Lost in Translation'' relies wholly on the '[[Other (philosophy)|otherness]]' of the Japanese to give meaning to its protagonists, shape to its plot, and color to its scenery. The inaccessibility of Japan functions as an extension of the alienation and loneliness Bob and Charlotte feel in their personal lives, thus laying the perfect conditions for romance to germinate: they're the only ones who understand each other. Take away the cartooniness of the Japanese and the humor falls flat, the main characters' intense yearning is neutralized and the plot evaporates.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianamericanfilm.com/archives/000602.html|title=Asian American Film: Commentary|website=asianamericanfilm.com|accessdate=August 29, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017222616/http://www.asianamericanfilm.com/archives/000602.html|archive-date=October 17, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn another ''Guardian'' article, journalist David Stubbs described ''Lost in Translation'' as \"mopey, self-pitying drivel\", and its characters as \"spoiled, bored, rich, utterly unsympathetic Americans\".<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/dec/04/culture.features | title= No more heroes: film | date= December 4, 2004 | last= Stubbs | first= David | publisher=The Guardian | accessdate= June 19, 2012 | location=London}}</ref> In an article published in a 2004 issue of ''[[Maclean's]]'', Steve Burgess criticized the film as an ethnocentric \"compendium of unpleasant stereotypes{{nbsp}}... indicative of the way visitors and foreign workers often view Japan.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Burgess|first=Steve|date=April 26, 2004|title=Found in Translation|journal=[[Maclean's]]|volume=117|issue=17|pages=38\u201339|publisher=Rogers Communications|issn=0024-9262}}</ref> Robin Antepara, an educator writing for an issue of ''[[Commonweal (magazine)|Commonweal]]'', wrote that while the story embodies stereotypes, \"Charlotte is the personification of Japanese watchfulness,\" an often neglected virtue.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Antepara|first=Robin|date=April 8, 2005|title=Culture Matters: Americans through Japanese Eyes|journal=[[Commonweal (magazine)|Commonweal]]|volume=132|issue=7|pages=10\u201311|publisher=Commonweal Foundation|issn=0010-3330}}</ref> The academic Maria San Filippo wrote that the \"retreat into America-centrism would be disappointing if, again, it were not so truthful{{nbsp}}... Coppola knows firsthand that American tourists rarely get to know any Japanese well enough to discover their depth as sympathetic human beings.\"<ref name=\"San2003\" /> Producer Ross Katz responded to some of the criticism by saying \"Sofia's love of Japan and love of the people that she's met there is incredibly evident in the film,\" and said that none of the scenes were \"any slight to Japanese people.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Land Of the Rising Clich\u00e9|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/01/04/movies/land-of-the-rising-cliche.html|first=Motoko|last=Rich|date=January 4, 2004 |author2=Lukas Schwarzacher |author3=Fumie Tomita|publisher= [[The New York Times]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191018122521/https://www.nytimes.com/2004/01/04/movies/land-of-the-rising-cliche.html?pagewanted=all | archive-date= 2019-10-15 | url-status= live |accessdate= October 15, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of accolades received by Lost in Translation}}\n''Lost in Translation'' won an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] for [[Academy Award for Writing Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/bestscreenplays4.html |title=Academy Awards Best Screenplays and Writers |publisher=Filmsite.org |accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeprophets.com/awards/display.cfm?awardsaxID=16&awardsyear=2003 |title=Box Office Prophets Film Awards Database: Best Adapted Screenplay 2003 |publisher=Boxofficeprophets.com |accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref> It was also nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], but lost both to ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]''. Bill Murray was also nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]], but lost to [[Sean Penn]] for ''[[Mystic River (film)|Mystic River]]''.\n\nThe film won [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globes]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture - Musical or Comedy|Best Musical or Comedy Motion Picture]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]], and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy#2000s|Best Musical or Comedy Actor]]. It was also nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director - Motion Picture|Best Director]], and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Musical or Comedy Actress]].<ref name=\"Hernandez3\">{{cite news | last = Hernandez | first = Eugene | title = ''Lord of the Rings'' and ''Lost in Translation'' Big Winners at Golden Globes | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = January 26, 2004 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/lord_of_the_rings_and_lost_in_translation_big_winners_at_golden_globes/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] film awards, ''Lost in Translation'' won the Best Editing, [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor]] and [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role#Winners 1968-present|Best Actress]] awards. It was also nominated for best film, director, original screenplay, music and cinematography. It won four [[IFP Independent Spirit Awards]], for Best Feature, Director, Male Lead, and Screenplay.<ref name=\"Hernandez\">{{cite news | last = Hernandez | first = Eugene | title = ''Lost In Translation'' Tops Independent Spirit Awards, ''Station Agent'' Another Big Winner | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = February 28, 2004 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/lost_in_translation_tops_independent_spirit_awards_station_agent_another_bi/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref> The film was honored with the original screenplay award from the [[Writers Guild of America]].<ref name=\"Hernandez2\">{{cite news | last = Hernandez | first = Eugene | title = WGA Opts for ''Translation'' and ''Splendor'', While SAG Goes for ''Rings'' | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = February 23, 2004 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/wga_opts_for_translation_and_splendor_while_sag_goes_for_rings/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\n''Lost in Translation'' was released on DVD and VHS on February 3, 2004.<ref name=\"metacritic\" /><ref>{{cite web|first= Andy|last= Patrizio |url=http://dvd.ign.com/articles/489/489848p1.html |title=Lost in Translation - DVD Review at IGN |publisher=Dvd.ign.com |date=February 3, 2004 |accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it an \"A\" rating and criticized \"the disc's slim bonus features\", but praised the film for standing \"on its own as a valentine to the mysteries of attraction\".<ref name=\"fonseca\">{{cite news | last = Fonseca | first = Nicholas | title = ''Lost in Translation'' | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = February 13, 2004 | url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,588239,00.html | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n''Lost in Translation'' was also released in high definition on the now defunct [[HD DVD]] format. A [[Blu-ray]] edition was released on January 4, 2011.<ref>[http://www.highdefdigest.com/news/show/Disc_Announcements/Universal/Lost_in_Translation_Blu-ray_Detailed_and_Delayed/5513 'Lost in Translation' Blu-ray Detailed and Delayed], a September 30, 2010 article from High-Def Digest</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Lost in Translation (film)|Lost in Translation}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.lost-in-translation.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|0335266}}\n* {{AllMovie title|283628}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|lost_in_translation}}\n* {{metacritic film|lost-in-translation}}\n* {{mojo title|lostintranslation}}\n<!-- Do not add personal webpages offering opinions about perceived racism, they will be removed. -->\n\n{{Sofia Coppola|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= [[List of accolades received by Lost in Translation|Awards for ''Lost in Translation'']]|state=collapsed\n|list1=\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Foreign Film}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestMotionPictureMusicalComedy 2001-2020}}\n{{Independent Spirit Award for Best Film}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Motion Picture}}\n{{TFCA Award for Best Film}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2003 films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s independent films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American Zoetrope films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Film C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about language and translation]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sofia Coppola]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Musical or Comedy Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films set in hotels]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kyoto]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Kyoto Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Original Screenplay Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Film winners]]\n[[Category:Japan in non-Japanese culture]]\n[[Category:Japanese comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:Japanese independent films]]\n[[Category:Japanese romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Japanese romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language films]]\n[[Category:Midlife crisis films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Sofia Coppola]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2003 film directed by Sofia Coppola}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Lost in Translation\n| image          = Lost in Translation poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| alt            = <!-- description needed see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| director       = [[Sofia Coppola]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ross Katz]]\n* Sofia Coppola}}\n| writer         = Sofia Coppola\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Bill Murray]]\n* [[Scarlett Johansson]]\n* [[Giovanni Ribisi]]\n* [[Anna Faris]]\n* Fumihiro Hayashi\n}}<!-- per poster billing block -->\n| music          = See [[#Music|music]]\n| cinematography = [[Lance Acord]]\n| editing        = [[Sarah Flack]]\n| production_companies =  {{Plainlist|\n* [[American Zoetrope]]\n* Elemental Films}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| distributor    =  {{Plainlist|\n* [[Focus Features]] (United States)\n* [[Tohokushinsha Film]] (Japan)}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2003|8|29|[[Telluride Film Festival]]|2003|9|12|United States|2004|4|17|Japan}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes<ref>{{cite news | title=''Lost in Translation'' | publisher=Australian Classification | url=http://www.classification.gov.au/Pages/View.aspx?sid=yYswbmSEc6366pg9JjpWng%253d%253d&ncdctx=sHsnaZV38NRshMiU2dzq3nwXWCWJQQkDMMcyOxhF5ce1lVHM9d1FDUiNxfrfQhHHscURO7bmfpScHgp1PojiNw%253d%253d | accessdate=March 14, 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United States<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web |url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/54274 |title=Lost in Translation (2003) |format=select \"Details\" tab |work=[[American Film Institute]] |accessdate=September 9, 2018}}</ref>\n* Japan<ref name=\"afi\"/>}}\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n*English\n*Japanese\n}}\n| budget         = $4 million<ref name=\"boxoffice\">{{cite news | title=''Lost in Translation'' | work=Box Office Mojo |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lostintranslation.htm | accessdate=March 13, 2009}}</ref>\n| gross          = $119.7 million<ref name=\"boxoffice\" />\n}}\n'''''Lost in Translation''''' is a 2003 [[comedy-drama]] film written and directed by [[Sofia Coppola]]. It stars [[Bill Murray]] as midfle-aged actor Bob Harris, who befriends college graduate Charlotte ([[Scarlett Johansson]]) in a [[Tokyo]] hotel. The movie explores themes of [[loneliness]], [[insomnia]], [[Existentialism|existential]] [[ennui]], and [[culture shock]] against the backdrop of a modern Japanese city.\n\n''Lost in Translation'' was nominated for four [[Academy Awards]], including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Bill Murray, and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Coppola; Coppola won for [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]. Murray and Johansson each won a [[BAFTA]] award for [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]] and [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress in a Leading Role]] respectively. The film grossed $119 million on a budget of $4 million.\n\n==Plot==\nBob Harris, an aging American movie star, arrives in Tokyo to film an advertisement for [[Suntory]] whiskey. Charlotte, a young college graduate, sits bored in her hotel room while her husband John, a celebrity photographer, is on assignment in Tokyo. Charlotte is unsure of her future with John, feeling detached from his lifestyle and disillusioned about their relationship. Bob's 25-year marriage is also strained as he goes through a [[midlife crisis]].\n\nEach day, Bob and Charlotte encounter each other in the hotel and after both experience insomnia, they sit and chat at the hotel bar one night. Eventually, Charlotte invites Bob to meet with some local friends of hers. The two bond through a fun night in Tokyo with Charlotte's friends, experiencing Japanese nightlife and culture. In the days that follow, Bob and Charlotte's friendship develops as they spend more time together. One night, each unable to sleep, the two share an intimate conversation about Charlotte's personal troubles and Bob's married life.\n\nOn the penultimate night of his stay, Bob sleeps with the hotel bar's female jazz singer. The next morning Charlotte arrives at his room to invite him for lunch and overhears the woman in his room, leading to a difficult lunch. Later that night, outside the hotel during a fire alarm, Bob and Charlotte reconcile and express how they will miss each other as they make a final visit to the hotel bar.\n\nThe following morning, Bob is set to return to the United States. He tells Charlotte goodbye at the hotel lobby and sadly watches her walk back to the elevator. In a taxi to the airport, Bob sees Charlotte on a crowded street, leaves the car and walks to her. He embraces the tearful Charlotte and whispers something in her ear. The two share a brief kiss, say goodbye and Bob departs.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Bill Murray]] as Bob Harris\n* [[Scarlett Johansson]] as Charlotte\n* [[Giovanni Ribisi]] as John\n* [[Anna Faris]] as Kelly\n* Fumihiro Hayashi as Charlie Brown\n* Akiko Takeshita as Ms. Kawasaki\n* [[Fran\u00e7ois Du Bois]] as the Pianist\n* [[Takashi Fujii (comedian)|Takashi Fujii]] as TV host\n* [[Hiromix]] as herself\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Analysis==\nOver the course of the film, several things are \"lost in translation\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A03E6DD103AF932A1575AC0A9659C8B63 |title=What Else Was Lost in Translation |accessdate=May 2, 2012 |last=Rich |first=Motoko |date=September 21, 2003 |work=[[The New York Times]]|quote= It doesn't take much to figure out that 'Lost in Translation,' the title of Sofia Coppola's elegiac new film about two lonely American souls in Tokyo, means more than one thing. There is the cultural dislocation felt by Bob Harris (Bill Murray), a washed-up movie actor, and Charlotte (Scarlett Johansson), a young wife trying to find herself. They are also lost in their marriages, lost in their lives. As Charlotte says, 'I just feel so alone, even with people around.' Then, of course, there is the simple matter of language.}}</ref> Bob (Murray), a Japanese director ([[Diamond Yukai|Yutaka Tadokoro]]), and an interpreter (Takeshita) are on a set, filming a commercial for [[Suntory]] whisky (specifically, 17-year-old [[Hibiki (whisky)|Hibiki]]). In several exchanges, the director gives lengthy, impassioned directives in Japanese. These are invariably followed by brief, incomplete translations from the interpreter.\n\n::{{dialogue|Director|The translation is very important, O.K.? The translation.|mood1=in Japanese, to the interpreter|Interpreter|Yes, of course. I understand.|mood2=in Japanese, to the director|Director|Mr. Bob. You are sitting quietly in your study. And then there is a bottle of Suntory whisky on top of the table. You understand, right? With wholehearted feeling, slowly, look at the camera, tenderly, and as if you are meeting old friends, say the words. As if you are [[Humphrey Bogart|Bogie]] in ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'', saying, 'Here's looking at you, kid,'\u2014Suntory time!|mood3=in Japanese, to Bob|Interpreter|He wants you to turn, look in camera. O.K.?|mood4=In English, to Bob|Bob|...Is that all he said?}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/21/style/what-else-was-lost-in-translation.html |title=What Else Was Lost in Translation |accessdate=November 4, 2007 |last=Rich |first=Motoko |date=September 21, 2003 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the meaning and detail lost in the translation of the director's words, the two central characters in the film\u2014Bob and Charlotte\u2014are also lost in other ways. On a basic level, they are lost in the alien [[culture of Japan|Japanese culture]]. But in addition, they are lost in their own lives and relationships, a feeling, amplified by their displaced location, that leads to their blossoming friendship and growing connection with one another.<ref name=\"Gehring2004\">{{cite journal |last=Gehring |first=Wes D. |date=January 2004 |title=Along Comes Another Coppola |journal=[[USA Today (magazine)|USA Today]] |volume=132 |page=59|publisher=The Society for the Advancement of Education |issn=0161-7389}}</ref>\n\nBy her own admission, Coppola wanted to create a romantic movie about two characters that have a moment of connection. The story's timeline was intentionally shortened to emphasize this moment.<ref>{{cite journal|date=October 2003|title=The Co-Conspirators|journal=Interview|volume=33|issue=9|page=56|publisher=Interview, Inc.|location=New York|issn=0149-8932}}</ref> Additionally, Coppola has said that since \"there's not much happening in the story besides [Bob and Charlotte's relationship]\", the filmmakers tried to keep an ongoing tension.<ref name=\"Carter\">{{cite news|title=Famous lost words|first=Kelly|last=Carter|date=September 21, 2003|work=[[South China Morning Post]]}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box|quote=As an actor, and as a writer/director, the question is: is it going to be very noble here? [Is] this guy going to say, \"I just can't call you. We can't share room service anymore?\" Is it going to be like that sort of thing, or is it going to be a little more real where they actually get really close to it?|align=right|width=30em|style=padding:8px|source=\u2014Bill Murray<ref name=\"Murray 1\">{{cite web|title=Interview with 'Lost in Translation' Star Bill Murray|url=http://movies.about.com/cs/lostintranslation/a/lostbillint.htm|first=Rebecca|last=Murray|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=Feb 19, 2014|page=1}}</ref>}}\nMurray has described his biggest challenge in portraying Bob as managing the character's conflicted feelings. On one hand, Murray said, Bob knows that it could be dangerous to become too close to Charlotte, but on the other, he is lonely and knows that having an affair would be easy. Murray worked to portray a balance between being affectionate and being \"respectable\".<ref name=\"Murray 1\"/>\n\nThe academic Marco Abel lists ''Lost in Translation'' as one of many films that belong to the category of \"postromance\" cinema, which he says offers a negative perspective of love, sex, romance, and dating. According to Abel, the characters in such films reject the idealized notion of lifelong monogamy.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Abel|first=Marco|year=2010|title=Failing to Connect: Itinerations of Desire in Oskar Roehler's Postromance Films|journal=New German Critique|volume=37|issue=1|series=109|page=77|publisher=New German Critique, Inc.|doi=10.1215/0094033X-2009-018}}</ref>\n\nUniversity of Vermont professor Todd McGowan interprets the film from a [[Jacques Lacan|Lacanian]] psychoanalytic perspective, arguing that it encourages us to embrace \"absence\" in our lives and relationships.<ref name=mcgowan>{{cite journal |last1=McGowan |first1=Todd |title=There is Nothing Lost in Translation |journal=Quarterly Review of Film and Video |date=2007 |volume=24 |issue=1}}</ref>{{rp|62}} He describes Coppola's depiction of Tokyo \"as a city bubbling over with excess\", which offers an empty promise of gratification.{{r|mcgowan|p=54}} Both Bob and Charlotte recognize that they cannot find meaning in Tokyo's bounties, so they bond over their shared sense of emptiness and failure.{{r|mcgowan|p=54}} The author and filmmaker Anita Schillhorn van Veen interprets the film as a criticism of [[modernity]], in which Tokyo is a contemporary \"[[Ukiyo|floating world]]\" of fleeting pleasures that are too alienating and amoral to facilitate meaningful relationships.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schillhorn van Veen|first=Anita|date=March 1, 2006|title=The Floating World: Representations of Japan in ''Lost in Translation'' and ''Demonlover''|journal=Asian Cinema|volume=17|issue=1|pages=190\u2013193|issn=1059-440X}}</ref> Tessa Dwyer, writing for ''Linguistica Antverpiensia, New Series \u2013 Themes in Translation Studies'', called ''Lost in Translation'' a [[Polyglotism|polyglot]] film that challenges the film industry's \"more usual tendency to ignore or deny issues of language difference\" by highlighting Bob and Charlotte's difficult contact with the Japanese language.<ref name=\"Dwyer\">{{cite journal|last=Dwyer|first=Tessa|year=2005|title=Universally speaking: Lost in Translation and polyglot cinema |url=https://lans-tts.uantwerpen.be/index.php/LANS-TTS/article/view/143 |journal=Linguistica Antverpiensia, New Series \u2013 Themes in Translation Studies |issue=4 |pages=297\u2013300 |publisher=Department of Translators and Interpreters, Antwerp University |accessdate=February 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Aesthetics===\nThe author and lecturer Maria San Filippo contends that the film's setting, Tokyo, is an audiovisual metaphor for Bob and Charlotte's world views. She explains that the calm ambience of the city's hotel represents Bob's desire to be secure and undisturbed, while the energetic atmosphere of the city streets represents Charlotte's willingness to engage with the world.<ref>{{cite journal|last=San Filippo|first=Maria|year=2003|title=Lost in Translation|journal=Cineaste|volume=29|issue=1|page=28|publisher=Cineaste|location=New York|issn=0009-7004}}</ref> Coppola and [[Lance Acord]], the film's cinematographer, agreed that ''Lost in Translation'' needed to rely heavily on visual expression to support the characters' romance.\n\nRobert Hahn, an essayist writing for ''[[The Southern Review]]'', suggested that the filmmakers deliberately used [[chiaroscuro]], the art of using strong contrasts between light and dark to support the story. He wrote that the film's dominant light tones symbolize feelings of humor and romance, and they are contrasted with dark tones that symbolize underlying feelings of despondency. He compared this to the technique of the painter [[John Singer Sargent]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hahn|first=Robert|year=2006|title=Dancing in the Dark|journal=The Southern Review|volume=42|issue=1|pages=153\u2013154|issn=0038-4534}}</ref>\n\nThe film's opening shot, which features a close shot of Charlotte lying down in translucent pink underwear, has interested various commentators. In particular, it has been compared to the portraitures of the painter [[John Kacere]] and the image of [[Brigitte Bardot]] in the opening scene of the 1963 film ''[[Contempt (film)|Contempt]]''. Dwyer wrote that when the two shots are compared, they reveal the importance of language difference, as both films highlight the complexities involved with characters speaking multiple languages.<ref name=\"Dwyer\"/> Filippo wrote that while the image in ''Contempt'' is used to remark on [[sexual objectification]], Coppola \"doesn't seem to be making a statement at all beyond a sort of endorsement of beauty for beauty's sake\".<ref name=\"San2003\">{{cite journal|last=San Filippo|first=Maria|year=2003|title=Lost in Translation |journal=Cineaste |volume=29 |issue=1 |page=26 |publisher=Cineaste |location=New York |issn=0009-7004}}</ref>\n\nCoppola revealed in a 2013 interview that the shot is indeed based on the art of Kacere.<ref name=\"Stern\">{{cite web|title=Sofia Coppola Discusses 'Lost in Translation' on Its 10th Anniversary |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/09/12/sofia-coppola-discusses-lost-in-translation-on-its-10th-anniversary.html |first=Marlow|last=Stern |date=September 12, 2013 |work=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=February 20, 2014}}</ref> [[Geoff King]], a professor of film at [[Brunel University]] (who published a book on the film, under the same name in a series titled \"American indies\", in 2010), contends that the shot is marked by an \"obvious\" appeal in its potential eroticism, and a \"subtle\" appeal in its artistic qualities. He used the shot as an example of the film's obvious attractions, which are characteristic of [[Major film studio|mainstream film]], and its subtle ones, which are typified by [[Independent film#The \"Indie Film\" Movement|\"indie\" film]].<ref>{{cite book|last=King|first=Geoff|editor=Gary Needham and Yannis Tzioumakis|title=Lost in Translation|series=American Indies|year=2010|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|location=Edinburgh|isbn=9780748637461|pages=1\u20132|chapter=Introduction}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n{{Quote box|quote=I remember having these weeks there that were sort of enchanting and weird{{nbsp}}... Tokyo is so disorienting, and there's a loneliness and isolation. Everything is so crazy, and the jet lag is torture. I liked the idea of juxtaposing a midlife crisis with that time in your early 20s when you're, like, What should I do with my life?|align=right|width=30em|style=padding:8px|source=\u2014Sofia Coppola, 2003<ref name=\"Betts\">{{cite news|last=Betts |first=Kate |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1005674-2,00.html |title=Sofia's Choice |publisher=TIME |date=September 15, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref>}}\nCoppola devised the idea of ''Lost in Translation'' after many visits to Tokyo in her twenties, basing much of the story on her experiences there.<ref name=\"Stern\"/><ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/sofia_coppola_talks_about_lost_in_translation_her_love_story_thats_not_nerd |title=Sofia Coppola Talks About \"Lost In Translation,\" Her Love Story That's Not \"Nerdy\" &#124; Filmmakers, Film Industry, Film Festivals, Awards & Movie Reviews |publisher=Indiewire |date=November 8, 2011 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=http://www.lost-in-translation.com/qaPopup.html |title=Lost In Translation |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724175933/http://www.lost-in-translation.com/qaPopup.html |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> Coppola was attracted to the [[Neon lighting|neon lights]] of [[Tokyo]] and has described the [[Park Hyatt Tokyo]], where most of the film's interior sequences take place, as one of her \"favorite places in the world\".<ref name=\"indiewire\" /> Particularly, she was attracted to its quietness, design, and \"combination of different cultures\", which include a New York bar and French restaurant.<ref name=\"indiewire\" />\n\nCoppola spent six months writing the film, beginning with \"short stories\" and \"impressions\" that culminated in a 70-page script.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenwritersutopia.com/modules.php?name=Content&pa=showpage&pid=57 |title=Sofia Coppola on LOST IN TRANSLATION |publisher=Screenwritersutopia.com |date=March 11, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216010832/http://www.screenwritersutopia.com/modules.php?name=Content&pa=showpage&pid=57 |archivedate=February 16, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.filmmakermagazine.com/issues/fall2003/features/tokyo_story.php |title=Sofia Coppola's Lost in Translation - Filmmaker Magazine - Fall 2003 |publisher=Filmmaker Magazine |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414022213/http://www.filmmakermagazine.com/issues/fall2003/features/tokyo_story.php |archivedate=April 14, 2012 }}</ref> She wanted to create a story that was \"a little more funny and romantic\" than her previous feature, ''[[The Virgin Suicides (film)|The Virgin Suicides]]'', and she spent little time planning or rewriting it.<ref name=\"Carter\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|page=58|issn=1084-8665}}</ref> Coppola has called the film a \"valentine\" to Tokyo,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Calhoun|first=Dave|year=2003|title=Watching Bill Murray Movies|journal=[[Another Magazine]]|issue=5|page=100|publisher=Dazed Group}}</ref> in which she has displayed the city in the way that it is meaningful to her.\n\nCoppola wrote the film with Murray in mind and said she would not have made it without him.<ref name=\"Stern\"/> She said that she had always wanted to work with Murray and that she was attracted to his \"sweet, lovable side\".<ref name=\"indiewire\" /> She pursued him for five months to a year, relentlessly sending telephone messages and letters.<ref name=\"Stern\"/><ref name=\"Betts\" /><ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|last=Hirschberg |first=Lynn |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/31/magazine/31COPPOLA.html |title=The Coppola Smart Mob |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=August 31, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref> She enlisted help from [[Wes Anderson]], who had directed Murray in two films, and screenwriter [[Mitch Glazer]], who was a mutual friend.<ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\" /><ref name=\"nytimes\" /> Coppola went so far as to ask for help from actor [[Al Pacino]], who at the time lived in the same town as Murray.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=97jYhz7tmcg|title=Sofia Coppola On Getting Bill Murray To Do LOST IN TRANSLATION|first=|last=American Film Institute|date=December 12, 2008|publisher=|accessdate=August 29, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> In July 2002, Coppola and Murray finally met in a restaurant, and he agreed to participate because he \"couldn't let her down\".<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> Despite this, Murray did not sign a contract; when he finally arrived in Tokyo, Coppola described it as \"a huge relief\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elle.com/Pop-Culture/Cover-Shoots/Our-Own-Private-Hollywood/Our-Own-Private-Hollywood/%28imageIndex%29/23/%28play%29/false#mode=base;slide=23; |title=26 EL1110 WLWIHSofia 001 |publisher=Elle.com |date=October 7, 2010 |accessdate=April 7, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503064033/http://www.elle.com/Pop-Culture/Cover-Shoots/Our-Own-Private-Hollywood/Our-Own-Private-Hollywood/(imageIndex)/23/(play)/false#mode=base;slide=23; |archive-date=May 3, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCoppola first noticed Scarlett Johansson in ''[[Manny & Lo]]'', where she related to her \"understated\" and \"subtle\" demeanor,<ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\" /><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://movies.about.com/cs/lostintranslation/a/lostsofia_2.htm|title=Interview with \"Lost in Translation\" Star Bill Murray|publisher=|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> envisioning her as a \"young [[Lauren Bacall]]-type girl\".<ref name=\"Stern\"/> Johansson, who was 17 years old at the time, immediately accepted the part and Coppola was happy with the maturity she brought to the character.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /><ref name=autogenerated1 /> In writing the story, Coppola said she was influenced by the relationship between Humphrey Bogart and [[Lauren Bacall]] in Howard Hawks' ''[[The Big Sleep (1946 film)|The Big Sleep]]''.<ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\" /> Murray and Johansson did not do any auditions before filming.<ref name=\"Stern\"/>\n\n===Filming===\nLance Acord, the film's director of photography, has written that the cinematographic style of ''Lost in Translation'' is largely based on \"daily experiences, memories and impressions\" of his time in Japan.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Acord|first=Lance|authorlink=Lance Acord|date=January 2004|title=Channeling Tokyo for ''Lost in Translation''|journal=American Cinematographer|volume=85|issue=1|pages=123\u2013124|publisher=American Society of Cinematographers|issn=0002-7928}}</ref> He worked closely with Coppola to visualize the film, relying on multiple experiences he shared with her in Tokyo before production took place. [[Location scouting]] was carried out by Coppola, Acord, and Ross Katz; and Coppola created 40 pages of photographs for the crew so that they would understand her visual intentions.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|page=57|issn=1084-8665}}</ref>\n\nAcord sought to maximize [[available light]] during shooting and use [[Stage lighting instrument|artificial lights]] as little as possible. He described this approach as conservative compared to \"the more conventional Hollywood system\", for which some of the crew's Japanese electricians thought he was \"out of his mind\".<ref name=\"Ballinger2004\">{{cite book|first=Alex|last=Ballinger|title=New Cinematographers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=10kR9a9SYnMC&pg=PA16|accessdate=April 6, 2012|date=October 12, 2004|publisher=Laurence King Publishing|isbn=978-1-85669-334-9}}</ref> In particular, Acord did not use any artificial lights to photograph the film's night-time exteriors.<ref name=\"Ballinger2004\" /> ''Lost in Translation'' was largely shot in an improvised, \"free-form\" manner, which Coppola described as \"stealthy\" and \"almost documentary-style\".<ref name=\"indiewire\" /><ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite video|title=Lost in Translation|date=2004|publisher= Focus Features/Universal Studios|medium= DVD}}</ref> The crew shot in some locations without permits, including Tokyo's subways and [[Shibuya, Tokyo#Shibuya Crossing|Shibuya Crossing]]; they avoided police by keeping a minimal crew.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> Acord avoided grandiose camera movements in favor of still shots to avoid taking away from the loneliness of the characters.<ref name=\"Ballinger2004\" />\n\nMost of the film was shot on an [[Aaton]] camera with [[35mm movie film|35 mm film stock]], using [[List of motion picture film stocks#VISION color negative (ECN-2 process 1996\u20132002)|Kodak Vision 500T 5263]] stock for nightlight exteriors and Kodak Vision 320T 5277 stock in daylight. A smaller [[Moviecam Compact]] was used in confined locations. Coppola said that her father, [[Francis Ford Coppola]], tried to convince her to shoot on video, but she ultimately decided on film, describing its \"fragmented, dislocated, melancholic, romantic feeling\", in contrast with video, which is \"more immediate, in the present\".<ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\" /> In interviews, she said she wanted to shoot Tokyo with a spontaneous \"informality\", similar to the \"way a snapshot looks\", and she chose to shoot on high-speed film stocks to evoke a \"homemade intimacy\".<ref name=\"Betts\" /><ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref name=\"filmmakermagazine\" /> Some scenes were shot wholly for mood and were captured without sound.<ref name=\"Betts\" />\n\n''Lost in Translation'' was shot six days per week in September and October 2002, over the course of 27 days.<ref name=\"Betts\" /> During this time, videotape footage was mailed to editor Sarah Flack in [[New York City]], where she began editing the film in a Red Car office.<ref name=\"Crabtree\">{{cite journal|last=Crabtree|first=Sheigh|date=September 10, 2003|title=Editor Flack in Fashion for Coppola's \"Lost\" Pic|journal=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> The scenes with Bob and Charlotte together were largely shot in order.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|page=64|issn=1084-8665}}</ref> Many of the interior scenes were shot overnight, because the hotel did not allow the crew to shoot in much of its public space until after 1{{nbsp}}a.m.<ref name=\"Ballinger2004\" />\n[[File:New York Bar Unplugged, Park Hyatt Tokyo (8376387540).jpg|thumb|The bar at the Park Hyatt was used as a filming location]]\nVarious locations were used during production; in particular, the bar featured prominently in the film is the New York Bar, which is situated on the 52nd floor of the [[Shinjuku Park Tower]] and part of the Park Hyatt in [[Shinjuku, Tokyo]]. Other locations include the [[Heian Jingu]] shrine in [[Kyoto]] and the steps of the San-mon gate at [[Nanzen-ji]], as well as the club Air in the [[Daikanyama]] district of Tokyo. All the locations mentioned in the film are the names of actual places that existed in Tokyo at the time of filming. Murray described the first few weeks of the shoot as like \"being held prisoner\", since he was affected by [[jet lag]], and Johansson said the shoot made her \"busy, vulnerable and tired\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jan/01/1 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Geoffrey | last=MacNab | title=Geoffrey Macnab talks to Bill Murray | date=January 1, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2003/dec/28/features.magazine | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Polly | last=Vernon | title=Polly Vernon meets Scarlett Johansson | date=January 5, 2004}}</ref>\n\nCoppola spoke of the challenges of directing the movie with a Japanese crew, since she had to rely on her assistant director to make translations.<ref name=\"indiewire\" /> Much of the performances were improvised, and Coppola openly allowed modifications to dialogue during shooting. For example, the dialogue in the scene with Harris and the still photographer was unrehearsed.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|pages=58\u201359|issn=1084-8665}}</ref> Coppola has said that she was attracted to the idea of Bob and Charlotte going through stages of a romantic relationship all in one week\u2014in which they have met, courted, hurt each other, and discussed intimate life. To conclude this relationship, Coppola wanted a special ending even though she thought the concluding scene in the script was mundane. Coppola instructed Murray to perform the kiss in that scene without telling Johansson, to which she reacted without preparation. The whisper was also unscripted, but too quiet to be recorded. While Coppola initially considered having audible dialogue dubbed into the moment, she later decided that it was better to keep it \"between the two of\nthem.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|pages=63\u201364|issn=1084-8665}}</ref>\n\nAfter filming, Coppola and Flack spent approximately 10 weeks editing the film.<ref name=\"Crabtree\" /> In the bonus features of the film's DVD, Murray called ''Lost in Translation'' his favorite film that he has worked on,<ref name=autogenerated2 /> and Coppola described the film as her most \"personal\", since much of the story is based on her own experiences.<ref name=\"Stern\"/> For example, Charlotte's relationship with her husband is based on Coppola's relationship with her husband, [[Spike Jonze]], when they first married, and the \"Suntory\" commercial is based on a commercial Coppola's father, [[Francis Ford Coppola]], shot with [[Akira Kurosawa]].<ref name=\"Stern\"/><ref><!-- WP:FU as link for criticism. -->{{cite AV media\n| title = Suntory Whiskey commercials Coppola & Kurosawa\n| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v-A2EH0vyd4\n}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{main|Lost in Translation (soundtrack)}}\nThe film's [[Lost in Translation (soundtrack)|soundtrack]], supervised by [[Brian Reitzell]], was released on September 9, 2003 by [[Emperor Norton Records]]. It contains five songs by [[Kevin Shields]], including one from his group [[My Bloody Valentine (band)|My Bloody Valentine]]. Coppola said much of the soundtrack consisted of songs that she \"liked and had been listening to\", and she worked with Reitzell to make Tokyo [[dream pop]] mixes.<ref name=\"Stern\"/> The soundtrack also included [[The Jesus and Mary Chain]] hit \"[[Just Like Honey]]\". [[Allmusic]] gave the soundtrack four out of five stars, saying \"Coppola's impressionistic romance ''Lost in Translation'' features an equally impressionistic and romantic soundtrack that plays almost as big a role in the film as Bill Murray and Scarlett Johansson do.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Phares |first=Heather |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/lost-in-translation-mw0000316244 |title=Lost in Translation \u2013 Original Soundtrack |publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate=October 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAgathi Glezakos, an academic writing a review of ''Lost in Translation'' shortly after its release, wrote that the music in the film's karaoke scene constitutes a common \"language\" that allows Bob and Charlotte to connect with some of the Japanese people amidst their alienation.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Glezakos|first=Agathi|date=October 15, 2003|title=Movie Review: ''Lost in Translation''|journal=Reflections: Narratives of Professional Helping|volume=9|issue=4|pages=71\u201372|publisher=[[California State University, Long Beach]]|issn=1080-0220}}</ref> In that scene, the rendition of the [[Pretenders (band)|Pretenders]]' \"[[Brass in Pocket]]\" was selected to showcase a lively side of Charlotte, and \"[[(What's So Funny 'Bout) Peace, Love, and Understanding]]\" was chosen to establish that Bob is from a different generation. Both Coppola and Murray finally selected [[Roxy Music]]'s \"[[More Than This (Roxy Music song)|More Than This]]\" during the shoot itself because they liked the band and thought the lyrics fit the story.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Chumo|first=Peter N. II|date=January\u2013February 2004|title=Sofia Coppola|journal=Creative Screenwriting|volume=11|issue=1|pages=60\u201361|issn=1084-8665}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Lost in Translation'' was screened at the 2003 [[Telluride Film Festival]].<ref name=\"mitchell2\">{{cite news | last = Mitchell | first = Elvis | authorlink= Elvis Mitchell | title = Telluride Marks Its 30th Year With a Passing of Torches | work = [[The New York Times]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 1, 2003 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/01/movies/critic-s-notebook-telluride-marks-its-30th-year-with-a-passing-of-torches.html | accessdate = March 25, 2009 }}</ref> It was given a limited release on September 12, 2003 in 23 theaters where it grossed $925,087 on its opening weekend with an average of $40,221 per theater and ranking 15th at the box office.<ref name=\"boxoffice\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2003/LSTNT.php |title=Lost in Translation - Box Office Data, Movie News, Cast Information |publisher=The Numbers |accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref> It was given a wider release on October 3, 2003 in 864 theaters where it grossed $4,163,333 with an average of $4,818 per theater and ranking 7th. The film went on to make $44,585,453 in [[North America]] and $75,138,403 in the rest of the world for a worldwide total of $119,723,856.<ref name=\"boxoffice\" />\n\n===Critical response===\n''Lost in Translation'' received critical acclaim, particularly for Coppola's direction and screenplay and Murray and Johansson's performances. It has a score of 95% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with an average rating of 8.4/10 based on 228 reviews. The site's critical consensus states: \"Effectively balancing humor and subtle pathos, Sofia Coppola crafts a moving, melancholy story that serves as a showcase for both Bill Murray and Scarlett Johansson\".<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">{{cite web|title = Lost in Translation|work = Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate = March 19, 2010|url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lost_in_translation/}}</ref> The film also holds a score of 89 out of 100 based on 43 reviews on [[Metacritic]], indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web|title=Lost in Translation|work=Metacritic|accessdate=May 25, 2011|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/lost-in-translation}}</ref>\n\nCritic [[Roger Ebert]] gave ''Lost in Translation'' four out of four stars and named it the second best film of the year, describing it as \"sweet and sad at the same time as it is sardonic and funny\".<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite news | last = Ebert | first = Roger | authorlink= Roger Ebert | title = ''Lost in Translation'' | work = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 12, 2003 | url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20030912/REVIEWS/309120302/1023 | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref> In his review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Elvis Mitchell]] wrote: \"At 18, [Johansson] gets away with playing a 25-year-old woman by using her husky voice to test the level of acidity in the air{{nbsp}}... Ms. Johansson is not nearly as accomplished a performer as Mr. Murray, but Ms. Coppola gets around this by using Charlotte's simplicity and curiosity as keys to her character.\"<ref name=\"elvis\">{{cite news | last = Mitchell | first = Elvis | authorlink= Elvis Mitchell | title = An American in Japan, Making a Connection | work = [[The New York Times]] | publisher = | date = September 12, 2003 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/12/movies/film-review-an-american-in-japan-making-a-connection.html | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film an \"A\" rating and [[Lisa Schwarzbaum]] wrote: \"Working opposite the embracing, restful serenity of Johansson, Murray reveals something more commanding in his repose than we have ever seen before. Trimmed to a newly muscular, rangy handsomeness and in complete rapport with his character's hard-earned acceptance of life's limitations, Murray turns in a great performance.\"<ref name=\"schwarzbaum\u2212\">{{cite news | last = Schwarzbaum | first = Lisa | title = ''Lost in Translation'' | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 10, 2003 | url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,479937,00.html | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn his review for ''[[The New York Observer]]'', [[Andrew Sarris]] called the film \"that rarity of rarities, a grown-up romance based on the deliberate repression of sexual gratification{{nbsp}}... when independent films are exploding with erotic images edging ever closer to outright pornography, Ms. Coppola and her colleagues have replaced sexual facility with emotional longing, without being too coy or self-congratulatory in the process.\"<ref name=\"sarris\">{{cite news | last = Sarris | first = Andrew | title = Lonely Souls in a Strange Land: ''Lost in Translation'' Maps the Way | work = [[New York Observer]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 28, 2003 | url = http://www.observer.com/node/48113 | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the film three and a half stars out of four and wrote that it \"offers quiet humor in lieu of the bludgeoning direct assaults most comedies these days inflict\".<ref name=\"clark\">{{cite news | last = Clark | first = Mike | title = Comedy doesn't get lost in ''Translation'' | work = [[USA Today]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 12, 2003 | url = https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2003-09-11-translation_x.htm | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s [[Richard Corliss]] praised Murray's performance: \"You won't find a subtler, funnier or more poignant performance this year than this quietly astonishing turn.\"<ref name=\"corliss\">{{cite news | last = Corliss | first = Richard | title = A Victory for Lonely Hearts | work = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 15, 2003 | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1005675,00.html | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref> His performance has been likened to the sardonic persona of [[W. C. Fields]].<ref name=\"Gehring2004\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Alleva|first=Richard|date=December 5, 2003|title=About a Boy: Kill Bill-Volume 1 and Lost in Translation|journal=[[Commonweal (magazine)|Commonweal]]|volume=130|issue=21|page=14|publisher=Commonweal Foundation|issn=0010-3330}}</ref>\n\nIn his review for ''[[The Observer]]'', [[Philip French]] wrote: \"While ''Lost in Translation'' is deeply sad and has a strongly [[Michelangelo Antonioni|Antonioniesque]] flavour, it's also a wispy romantic comedy with little plot and some well-observed comic moments.\"<ref name=\"french\">{{cite news | last = French | first = Philip | authorlink= Philip French | title = The odd Coppola | work = [[The Observer]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = January 11, 2004 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jan/11/philipfrench | accessdate = March 16, 2009 | location=London}}</ref> In ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Joe Queenan (author)|Joe Queenan]] praised Coppola's film as \"one of the few Hollywood films I have seen this year that has a brain; but more than that, it has a soul.\"<ref name=\"queenan\">{{cite news | last = Queenan | first = Joe | authorlink= Joe Queenan (author) | title = A yen for romance | work = [[The Guardian]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = January 10, 2004 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jan/10/features.joequeenan | accessdate = March 16, 2009 | location=London}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s [[Peter Travers]] gave it four out of four stars and wrote: \"Before saying goodbye, they whisper something to each other that the audience can't hear. Coppola keeps her film as hushed and intimate as that whisper. ''Lost in Translation'' is found gold. Funny how a wisp of a movie from a wisp of a girl can wipe you out.\"<ref name=\"travers\">{{cite news | last = Travers | first = Peter | title = ''Lost in Translation'' | work = [[Rolling Stone]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 8, 2003 | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/lost-in-translation-20030908 | accessdate = March 10, 2011 }}</ref> [[J. Hoberman]], in his review for the ''[[Village Voice]]'', wrote: \"''Lost in Translation'' is as bittersweet a brief encounter as any in American movies since [[Richard Linklater]]'s equally romantic ''[[Before Sunrise]]''. But ''Lost in Translation'' is the more poignant reverie. Coppola evokes the emotional intensity of a one-night stand far from home\u2014but what she really gets is the magic of movies\".<ref name=\"hoberman\">{{cite news | last = Hoberman | first = J | title = After Sunset | work = [[Village Voice]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = September 9, 2003 | url = http://www.villagevoice.com/2003-09-09/film/after-sunset/1 | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association]] and [[National Society of Film Critics]] voted Bill Murray best actor of the year.<ref name=\"Mitchell\">{{cite news | last = Mitchell | first = Wendy | title = LA Critics Choose ''Splendor'', ''Friedmans'' Follow-Up, Texas Picks, and More | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = January 9, 2004 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/la_critics_choose_splendor_friedmans_follow-up_texas_picks_and_more/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hernandez4\">{{cite news | last = Hernandez | first = Eugene | title = National Film Critics Group Names ''American Splendor'' Top Film of '03 | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = January 5, 2004 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/national_film_critics_group_names_american_splendor_top_film_of_03/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref> The [[New York Film Critics Circle]] also voted Murray best actor and Sofia Coppola best director.<ref name=\"Hernandez5\">{{cite news | last = Hernandez | first = Eugene | title = NY Critics Crown ''King'' Top Film of '03; SF & Boston Critics Also Weigh In | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = December 16, 2003 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/ny_critics_crown_king_top_film_of_03_sf_boston_critics_also_weigh_in/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref> Coppola received an award for special filmmaking achievement from the [[National Board of Review]].<ref name=\"Mitchell2\">{{cite news | last = Mitchell | first = Wendy | title = National Board of Review Says ''Mystic River'' is Tops For 2003 | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = December 4, 2003 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/national_board_of_review_says_mystic_river_is_tops_for_2003/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref> ''Lost in Translation'' also appeared on several critics' top ten lists for 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2003/toptens.shtml|title=Metacritic: 2003 Film Critic Top Ten Lists|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225093312/http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2003/toptens.shtml|archivedate=December 25, 2007|accessdate=March 25, 2009|publisher=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] added it to his \"great movies\" list on his website.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100804/REVIEWS08/100809996 | work=Chicago Sun-Times | title=Lost in Translation (2003)}}</ref> ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' named it one of the 50 Best Movies of the Decade (2000-2009), ranking it at #7.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Movies of the Decade (2000-2009)|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2009/11/50-best-movies-of-the-decade-2000-2009.html?p=5|work=[[Paste Magazine]]|accessdate=December 14, 2011|date=November 3, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' named it one of the best films of the decade, writing: \"Six years later, we still have no clue what Bill Murray whispered into Scarlett Johansson's ear. And we don't want to. Why spoil a perfect film?\"<ref>Geier, Thom; Jensen, Jeff; Jordan, Tina; Lyons, Margaret; Markovitz, Adam; Nashawaty, Chris; Pastorek, Whitney; Rice, Lynette; Rottenberg, Josh; Schwartz, Missy; Slezak, Michael; Snierson, Dan; Stack, Tim; Stroup, Kate; Tucker, Ken; Vary, Adam B.; Vozick-Levinson, Simon; Ward, Kate (December 11, 2009), \"THE 100 Greatest MOVIES, TV SHOWS, ALBUMS, BOOKS, CHARACTERS, SCENES, EPISODES, SONGS, DRESSES, MUSIC VIDEOS, AND TRENDS THAT ENTERTAINED US OVER THE PAST 10 YEARS\". Entertainment Weekly. (1079/1080):74-84</ref> Director [[Quentin Tarantino]] included ''Lost in Translation'' in his list of top 20 films released since 1992, when his career as a filmmaker began.<ref>{{cite web | title = Team America, Anything Else Among the Best Movies of the Past Seventeen Years, Claims Quentin Tarantino| last=Brown|first=Lane | work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] | publisher=New York Media LLC | url =http://www.vulture.com/2009/08/speed_and_team_america_among_q.html | accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2016 international critics' poll by the [[BBC]], ''Lost in Translation'' was voted the 22nd greatest film since 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films |title=The 21st century's 100 greatest films |publisher=BBC |date=August 23, 2016 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Criticism ===\nThe film received some negative reviews, many from Japanese critics. Japanese TV critic Osugi {{small|{{bracket|[[:ja:\u304a\u3059\u304e|ja]]}}}} of Osugi and [[Peeco|Piko]] fame said \"The core story is cute and not bad; however, the depiction of Japanese people is terrible!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2004/0419/p07s01-woap.html|title='Lost in Translation' doesn't translate well in Japan|first=Robert|last=Marquand|date=April 19, 2004|publisher=|accessdate=August 29, 2017|via=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> In a ''Guardian'' article about the film, Kiku Day, a musician specializing in the ''[[shakuhachi]]'' Japanese flute, wrote that she \"couldn't help wondering not only whether I had watched a different movie, but whether the plaudits had come from a parallel universe of values\"; according to Day, there is \"no scene where the Japanese are afforded a shred of dignity. The viewer is sledgehammered into laughing at these small, yellow people and their funny ways.\"<ref name=\"kikuguard\">{{cite news| url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/jan/24/japan.film | title= Totally lost in translation | date= January 24, 2004 | last= Day | first= Kiku | publisher=The Guardian | accessdate= October 10, 2010 | location=London}}</ref> Day also said \"while shoe-horning every possible caricature of modern Japan into her movie, Coppola is respectful of ancient Japan. It is depicted approvingly, though ancient traditions have very little to do with the contemporary Japanese. The good Japan, according to this director, is Buddhist monks chanting, ancient temples, [[Ikebana|flower arrangement]]; meanwhile she portrays the contemporary Japanese as ridiculous people who have lost contact with their own culture.\"<ref name=\"kikuguard\" /> Furthermore, the critic Inkoo Kang has criticized the film for its xenophobia, racism, and anti-Asian bias, in which the film expresses a dismissive attitude in aspects such as speech, sexuality, tastes, and contemporary culture.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kang |first1=Inkoo |title=Lost In Translation Is An Insufferable, Racist Mess \u2014 Why Would We Expect The Beguiled To Be Any Different? |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3021638/lost-in-translation-is-an-insufferable-racist-mess-why-would-we-expect-the-beguiled-to-be-any-different/ |website=MTV News |language=en |date=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHawaiian filmmaker and author E. Koohan Paik wrote that \"The Japanese are presented not as people, but as clowns\" and that \"''Lost in Translation'' relies wholly on the '[[Other (philosophy)|otherness]]' of the Japanese to give meaning to its protagonists, shape to its plot, and color to its scenery. The inaccessibility of Japan functions as an extension of the alienation and loneliness Bob and Charlotte feel in their personal lives, thus laying the perfect conditions for romance to germinate: they're the only ones who understand each other. Take away the cartooniness of the Japanese and the humor falls flat, the main characters' intense yearning is neutralized and the plot evaporates.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianamericanfilm.com/archives/000602.html|title=Asian American Film: Commentary|website=asianamericanfilm.com|accessdate=August 29, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017222616/http://www.asianamericanfilm.com/archives/000602.html|archive-date=October 17, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn another ''Guardian'' article, journalist David Stubbs described ''Lost in Translation'' as \"mopey, self-pitying drivel\", and its characters as \"spoiled, bored, rich, utterly unsympathetic Americans\".<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/dec/04/culture.features | title= No more heroes: film | date= December 4, 2004 | last= Stubbs | first= David | publisher=The Guardian | accessdate= June 19, 2012 | location=London}}</ref> In an article published in a 2004 issue of ''[[Maclean's]]'', Steve Burgess criticized the film as an ethnocentric \"compendium of unpleasant stereotypes{{nbsp}}... indicative of the way visitors and foreign workers often view Japan.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Burgess|first=Steve|date=April 26, 2004|title=Found in Translation|journal=[[Maclean's]]|volume=117|issue=17|pages=38\u201339|publisher=Rogers Communications|issn=0024-9262}}</ref> Robin Antepara, an educator writing for an issue of ''[[Commonweal (magazine)|Commonweal]]'', wrote that while the story embodies stereotypes, \"Charlotte is the personification of Japanese watchfulness,\" an often neglected virtue.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Antepara|first=Robin|date=April 8, 2005|title=Culture Matters: Americans through Japanese Eyes|journal=[[Commonweal (magazine)|Commonweal]]|volume=132|issue=7|pages=10\u201311|publisher=Commonweal Foundation|issn=0010-3330}}</ref> The academic Maria San Filippo wrote that the \"retreat into America-centrism would be disappointing if, again, it were not so truthful{{nbsp}}... Coppola knows firsthand that American tourists rarely get to know any Japanese well enough to discover their depth as sympathetic human beings.\"<ref name=\"San2003\" /> Producer Ross Katz responded to some of the criticism by saying \"Sofia's love of Japan and love of the people that she's met there is incredibly evident in the film,\" and said that none of the scenes were \"any slight to Japanese people.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Land Of the Rising Clich\u00e9|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/01/04/movies/land-of-the-rising-cliche.html|first=Motoko|last=Rich|date=January 4, 2004 |author2=Lukas Schwarzacher |author3=Fumie Tomita|publisher= [[The New York Times]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191018122521/https://www.nytimes.com/2004/01/04/movies/land-of-the-rising-cliche.html?pagewanted=all | archive-date= 2019-10-15 | url-status= live |accessdate= October 15, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of accolades received by Lost in Translation}}\n''Lost in Translation'' won an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] for [[Academy Award for Writing Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/bestscreenplays4.html |title=Academy Awards Best Screenplays and Writers |publisher=Filmsite.org |accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeprophets.com/awards/display.cfm?awardsaxID=16&awardsyear=2003 |title=Box Office Prophets Film Awards Database: Best Adapted Screenplay 2003 |publisher=Boxofficeprophets.com |accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref> It was also nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], but lost both to ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]''. Bill Murray was also nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]], but lost to [[Sean Penn]] for ''[[Mystic River (film)|Mystic River]]''.\n\nThe film won [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globes]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture - Musical or Comedy|Best Musical or Comedy Motion Picture]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]], and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy#2000s|Best Musical or Comedy Actor]]. It was also nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director - Motion Picture|Best Director]], and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Musical or Comedy Actress]].<ref name=\"Hernandez3\">{{cite news | last = Hernandez | first = Eugene | title = ''Lord of the Rings'' and ''Lost in Translation'' Big Winners at Golden Globes | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = January 26, 2004 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/lord_of_the_rings_and_lost_in_translation_big_winners_at_golden_globes/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] film awards, ''Lost in Translation'' won the Best Editing, [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor]] and [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role#Winners 1968-present|Best Actress]] awards. It was also nominated for best film, director, original screenplay, music and cinematography. It won four [[IFP Independent Spirit Awards]], for Best Feature, Director, Male Lead, and Screenplay.<ref name=\"Hernandez\">{{cite news | last = Hernandez | first = Eugene | title = ''Lost In Translation'' Tops Independent Spirit Awards, ''Station Agent'' Another Big Winner | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = February 28, 2004 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/lost_in_translation_tops_independent_spirit_awards_station_agent_another_bi/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref> The film was honored with the original screenplay award from the [[Writers Guild of America]].<ref name=\"Hernandez2\">{{cite news | last = Hernandez | first = Eugene | title = WGA Opts for ''Translation'' and ''Splendor'', While SAG Goes for ''Rings'' | work = indieWIRE | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = February 23, 2004 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/wga_opts_for_translation_and_splendor_while_sag_goes_for_rings/ | accessdate = March 13, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\n''Lost in Translation'' was released on DVD and VHS on February 3, 2004.<ref name=\"metacritic\" /><ref>{{cite web|first= Andy|last= Patrizio |url=http://dvd.ign.com/articles/489/489848p1.html |title=Lost in Translation - DVD Review at IGN |publisher=Dvd.ign.com |date=February 3, 2004 |accessdate=February 19, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it an \"A\" rating and criticized \"the disc's slim bonus features\", but praised the film for standing \"on its own as a valentine to the mysteries of attraction\".<ref name=\"fonseca\">{{cite news | last = Fonseca | first = Nicholas | title = ''Lost in Translation'' | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = February 13, 2004 | url = http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,588239,00.html | accessdate = March 16, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n''Lost in Translation'' was also released in high definition on the now defunct [[HD DVD]] format. A [[Blu-ray]] edition was released on January 4, 2011.<ref>[http://www.highdefdigest.com/news/show/Disc_Announcements/Universal/Lost_in_Translation_Blu-ray_Detailed_and_Delayed/5513 'Lost in Translation' Blu-ray Detailed and Delayed], a September 30, 2010 article from High-Def Digest</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Lost in Translation (film)|Lost in Translation}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.lost-in-translation.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|0335266}}\n* {{AllMovie title|283628}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|lost_in_translation}}\n* {{metacritic film|lost-in-translation}}\n* {{mojo title|lostintranslation}}\n<!-- Do not add personal webpages offering opinions about perceived racism, they will be removed. -->\n\n{{Sofia Coppola|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= [[List of accolades received by Lost in Translation|Awards for ''Lost in Translation'']]|state=collapsed\n|list1=\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Foreign Film}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestMotionPictureMusicalComedy 2001-2020}}\n{{Independent Spirit Award for Best Film}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Motion Picture}}\n{{TFCA Award for Best Film}}\n{{Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award for Best Film}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2003 films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s independent films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American Zoetrope films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Film C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Picture Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about language and translation]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sofia Coppola]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Musical or Comedy Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films set in hotels]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kyoto]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Kyoto Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Original Screenplay Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Film winners]]\n[[Category:Japan in non-Japanese culture]]\n[[Category:Japanese comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:Japanese independent films]]\n[[Category:Japanese romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:Japanese romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language films]]\n[[Category:Midlife crisis films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Sofia Coppola]]\n", "name_user": "Dag777TX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lost_in_Translation_(film)"}
